<FIRST>u i AM-China-HongKong 1stLd-Writethru   06-06 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Hong Kong, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0682,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hong Kong Share Prices Plummet, Protesters March</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Tuesday figures. Pick up
12th pvs, `In nearby...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HK2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices opened lower Tuesday in nervous
reaction to China's military crackdown on pro-democracy
demonstrators, and thousands of residents staged funeral
processions for slain protesters.
   The developments in China have focused new public attention on
the accord under which the British colony will revert to Chinese
rule in 1997.
   Officials reported a run on some China-owned banks Monday in
withdrawals aimed at protesting the Chinese military's killings of
hundreds and perhaps thousands of unarmed protesters in efforts to
quell a popular uprising in Beijing.
   Thousands of angry Hong Kong residents gathered outside the
Xinhua News Agency, the mainland government's de facto embassy in
the territory.
   Governor Sir David Wilson also met Xu Jiatun, head of the
agency, to express his concern over the brutal force used, the
government reported without giving details.
   Wilson originally was to leave Monday for London to discuss Hong
Kong's future with members of the British House of Commons' Foreign
Affairs Committee. He delayed his departure to Wednesday because of
the developments in China.
   In London, some lawmakers called for a reconsideration of the
agreement. But British Foreign Secretary Geoffrey Howe reaffirmed
Britain's agreement to the accord.
   Under a Chinese-British agreement signed in 1984, China has said
the territory can maintain its capitalistic lifestyle under a ``one
country, two systems'' concept run by Hong Kong people without
Chinese interference.
   Ming Pao, a Chinese-language daily respected for its China
coverage, said a young guard fired four shots at Chinese Premier Li
Peng in the Great Hall of the People on Sunday and the premier was
hit in the thigh. He was not seriously injured, and the guard was
killed, the newspaper reported.
   The Hang Seng Index of blue chips, which plummeted on Monday to
its worst loss since the worldwide market collapse in 1987, fell
about 70 points shortly after the market opened Tuesday, but
rebounded within an hour to 2,075 points.
   On Monday, the index closed at 2,093.61 points, down 581.77
points from Friday. The drop was the worst since the 1987
international market collapse, when the index fell 1,120.99 points.
   In nearby Taiwan, the weighted stock market index dropped 455.44
points to close at 9,120.54, the largest single-day loss in the
market's 27-year history.
   Real estate specialists in Hong Kong said property values could
fall 15 to 20 percent unless the Chinese situation stabilizes.
   ``This is the worst scenario come to pass,'' said real estate
executive Paul Varty. ``Over the past few weeks everyone has been
looking at how this matter will be played out, and this bloodshed
is the worst possible way.''
   Monetary Affairs Secretary David Nendick urged investors to
remain calm and cautioned a run on mainland banks could reflect
adversely on the territory's status as the world's third financial
center after London and New York.
   Some banks said their rate of withdrawal was 30 percent higher
than usual, but no figures were available.
   ``I think they have gone mad,'' said Martin Lee, an outspoken
member of the Legislative Council. ``I believe it (the military
crackdown) is the work by a group of very old men who want to cling
to their power and are prepared to sacrifice thousands and millions
of lives.''
   Protesters continued the rallies held daily to support the
democracy movement since martial law was imposed May 20. On Monday,
about 3,000 Catholics and Protestants marched past the Xinhua
office in a funeral procession for the dead.
   About 98 percent of Hong Kong's population of 5.7 million are
Chinese, and two-thirds are refugees from China or their
descendants.
</TEXT>
