<FIRST>r a AM-BlackFilmMakers     06-06 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Black Film Makers,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spike Lee and Robert Townsend Honored as Independent Film Makers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spike Lee and Robert Townsend, the two major
representatives of the newest wave of make-it-on-your-own black
film makers, were honored Monday night for doing things their way.
   ``They are independent in spirit, they are determined and they
fought against insurmountable odds and surmounted them,'' said
Melvin Van Peebles, who overcame the odds a generation ago with
``Sweet Sweetback's Baadasssss Song.''
   Van Peebles, an elder statesman of black film making, presented
a special award to Townsend and Lee at the Black Filmmaker
Foundation's 10th anniversary gala and tribute at the Majestic
Theater in New York.
   The foundation is the nation's largest distributor of
independently produced work by black film makers. Its 1,500 members
include major film and television producers, writers, directors,
actors and film students.
   Also being honored were films and videos produced independently
of Hollywood and commercial television in the last 10 years.
   Lee first became known three years ago for ``She's Gotta Have
It,'' a sexual comedy about a young woman and her partners.
   He furthered his reputation with ``School Daze,'' a peek at
black colleges, and his ``Do the Right Thing'' was the talk of the
Cannes film festival last month. It premieres later this month.
   Townsend raised cash with his credit cards to finance
``Hollywood Shuffle,'' a revealing look at the stereotypes and
prejudices black actors face on and off the screen in the
movie-making world.
   He has moved on to four HBO specials and a feature film, ``The
Mighty Quinn,'' with Oscar nominee Denzel Washington. Townsend now
is writing and starring in a musical comedy, ``Heartbeats,'' about
a singing group.
</TEXT>
