<FIRST>r a AM-Sun-TimesChanges     06-06 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sun-Times Changes,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names Philadelphia Publisher as Chairman, Promotes Acting Publisher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sun-Times Co. announced Monday it has hired
Philadelphia publisher Sam S. McKeel as president and chief
executive officer in a move to become a national media company and
improve the city's second-largest newspaper.
   McKeel, 62, is a 35-year veteran of Knight-Ridder, Inc., most
recently as publisher of The Philadelphia Inquirer and The Daily
News of Philadelphia, and chairman of the firm that oversees both.
   In addition, the Chicago Sun-Times' acting publisher, Charles T.
Price, has been promoted to publisher of the paper, the nation's
10th-largest metropolitan daily, the holding company announced.
   ``These appointments strengthen our management team and
represent our continued commitment to the future of this
organization,'' said Leonard P. Shaykin, company chairman.
   At a brief afternoon news conference in the downtown Sun-Times
building, McKeel said the holding company's offer ``was a lure I
couldn't really resist.''
   He acknowledged that one of his first tasks will be to help
reverse circulation decline. With a daily circulation of 554,670
and 595,311 on Sundays, the Sun-Times is second in the city to the
Chicago Tribune.
   McKeel indicated no major immediate changes are planned in
management or staff, although he declined to specify his agenda.
   ``It would be very presumptuous to think I had changes in mind''
other than to make the newspaper ``more interesting, to expand
readership and expand sales,'' McKeel said.
   Price, 45, called his new boss ``a proven competitor and he is a
winner'' who will help make it possible for the Sun-Times ``to
better serve the community and also to better serve our
advertisers.''
   McKeel said the parent will seek compatible media companies to
acquire in its move to become a national media organization, but he
declined to elaborate.
   Besides the newspaper, the Sun-Times Co.'s holdings include the
Pioneer Press, which publishes 43 weekly papers in the Chicago
suburbs, and Star Publications, a group of 18 twice-weekly suburban
newspapers.
   P. Anthony Ridder, president of Knight-Ridder newspaper
division, said in a statement that ``McKeel's vision and leadership
are treasured assets that will be difficult to replace. He'll be
missed by all of his colleagues.''
   ``Sam's legacy will be the fine team he has built here which
will help to ensure the continued excellence of the Inquirer and
the Daily News. That team will have my close support and
assistance.''
   McKeel will continue to live in the Philadelphia suburb of
Rosemont, commuting to Chicago when necessary.
</TEXT>
