<FIRST>u a PM-Brown-Desegregation 1stLd-Writethru a0474 06-06 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brown-Desegregation, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0474,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Rules Topeka Schools Allowed Desegregation to Falter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to RECAST; PICKS UP 3rd graf pvs, `The
case ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HANNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vestiges of school segregation remain in
Topeka 35 years after it lost the Brown vs. Board of Education
decision, which paved the way for desegregation of schools
nationwide, a federal appeals court ruled.
   The 10th U.S. Court of Appeals panel's decision, made available
Monday, reversed a ruling that would have closed the case that
found ``separate but equal'' schools for blacks and whites
unconstitutional.
   The case was reopened 10 years ago by parents who said Topeka's
schools were still segregated.
   ``We won,'' said Rich Jones, an attorney representing the
parents of 17 black schoolchildren. ``We feel that 10 years of work
was not in vain. We feel vindicated by the decision. It's been
quite a long time coming.''
   The group involved in the lawsuit included parent Linda Brown
Buckner, who was a student when her name went on the original
lawsuit.
   ``My first reaction was shock, then I was pleased, very
pleased,'' said Cheryl Brown Henderson, Buckner's sister. ``I
believe that the case showed that there is a lot of educational
enhancement that is not taking place here.''
   In its decision published in Denver on Friday, the panel
rejected U.S. District Judge Richard Rogers' contention in April
1987 that parents of minority students had to prove a pattern of
intentional discrimination to force the district to come up with a
plan for more racially balanced schools.
   ``Because we are convinced that Topeka has not sufficiently
countered the effects of both the momentum of its pre-Brown
segregation and its subsequent segregative acts in the 1960s, we
reverse,'' the appeals court said. The judges also reversed a lower
court ruling that the Topeka school district had not violated Title
VI of the Civil Rights Act of 1964.
   Gary Sebelius, an attorney for the the school district, said
officials were awaiting receipt of the dissenting opinion in the
2-1 ruling before deciding whether to appeal.
   He added that the ruling confirmed the high quality of Topeka's
schools.
   ``Throughout their decision they note that Topeka offers
excellent educational opportunities to all its students, wherever
they be,'' Sebelius said. ``There was absolutely no hint or contest
of the quality education the district provides.''
   The court noted that neither the school district nor the Topeka
community was actively resisting desegregation, and cited the
national recognition of the district's innovative curriculum.
   ``This active engagement has largely been directed at concerns
other than desegregation, however,'' the appeals court said. ``For
the most part, the Topeka school district has exercised a form of
benign neglect.''
   The original class-action lawsuit challenged the
constitutionality of a Kansas law authorizing school segregation.
The May 17, 1954, Supreme Court decision paved the way for
nationwide school desegregation and busing.
   Topeka schools were required to submit an integration plan,
which was approved in 1955.
   In 1979, the case was revived by black parents who claimed
Topeka had failed to desegregate its schools. Rogers found the
school district to be integrated and unified.
   Local officials of the National Association for the Advancement
of Colored People at the time blasted Rogers' decision, saying
blacks could not get a fair hearing because of racism in Topeka.
   The appeals court ruled that the district's policy of permitting
students to attend neighborhood schools was insufficient to
desegregate schools because neighborhoods are still racially
segregated. Topeka is 90 percent white.
   There are about 14,000 students in the city school district.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
