<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Trial,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Selected As Abortion Demonstration Trial Takes Center Stage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge sat center stage, the defendants
took up the orchestra, mezzanine and balcony and a defense attorney
asked potential jurors if they'd ever had an abortion.
   Set in a 300-seat theater, the drama was real as 155
anti-abortion activists went on trial Monday for trespassing during
a protest at a clinic April 15.
   The judge had to rent the hall intended for nightclub acts and
jazz ensembles because no local courtroom was big enough.
   ``Here in the first row,'' attorney B. Larry Smith asked before
a jury of six was selected, ``has anyone had an abortion?''
   When a prosecutor objected, Smith asked whether any of the 95
prospective jurors knew of anyone who had had an abortion. About
half said yes.
   More than 180 people were arrested and charged with trespassing
during the protest organized by Operation Rescue. The charge
carries up to a year in jail and a $1,000 fine. Some pleaded no
contest and received six months' probation.
   Judge James D. Arnold merged the cases and rented a theater at
the Tampa Performing Arts Center complex for about $5,000 for what
is expected to be a weeklong trial.
   ``We're not here to determine the issue of abortion,'' said
Assistant State Attorney Hank Lavandera, standing before a stage
set up with a makeshift judge's bench.
   ``You are being selected to serve on a jury, not on a
legislative delegation,'' he said. ``What I'm concerned with is if
you can set aside your own preconceptions and follow the law.''
</TEXT>
