<FIRST>r a PM-Court-SemenDonor     06-06 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Court-Semen Donor,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agreement Must be Studied in Artificial Insemination Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who got a semen sample from a friend and
bore a child _ then got a court to rule that the man had no rights
as the father _ has been dealt a setback by the Colorado Supreme
Court.
   The Juvenile Court judge who held that the friend was not,
technically, the father must take another look at the case to
determine precisely what the pre-conception agreement between the
two was, the high court ruled Monday.
   The woman had argued that she never promised to recognize her
friend as the father and that even if she had, state law specifies
that sperm donors have no parental rights. Court papers identified
the couple only by initials.
   Records showed that in 1985, J.R. donated semen to E.C., a woman
he had known for two years. A doctor inseminated her, and she gave
birth in 1986.
   J.R. then sought a declaration he was the father, alleging that
he and E.C. had agreed in advance that he would be treated as the
father.
   He also argued that the law giving sperm donors no parental
rights did not apply to unmarried women who knew the donor.
   Juvenile Court Judge Morris E. Cole ruled that evidence of a
pre-conception agreement was irrelevant.
   But Justice Anthony Vollack said that what the man and woman
agreed to in advance is indeed relevant. The high court cited a
California case in which a sperm donor was declared the legal
father and given visitation rights.
</TEXT>
