<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Jews     06-06 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Jews,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emigration Drops During May, But Exodus Still at 10-Year High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish emigration from the Soviet Union dropped
sharply last month but is still at a 10-year high, according to
figures released today.
   The Intergovernmental Committee for Migration said 3,333 Soviet
Jews registered at a Vienna transit center in May, a 20 percent
drop from April. The committee helps Jews leave the Soviet Union
and resettle elsewhere.
   Only 96 emigrants opted for new homes in Israel, said committee
spokeswoman Regina Boucault. Most want to settle in the United
States, she said.
   Ms. Boucault said the agency had no explanation for the decline
in emigration.
   The May arrivals brought the 1989 total to 16,197; 524 chose the
Jewish state as their destination, she said. The total for all of
1988 was 20,082.
   The program began in 1971 and reached a peak in 1979 when 51,328
Jews were allowed to leave the Soviet Union. The numbers dropped
sharply after the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan chilled
East-West relations.
   The pace of emigration is now at its highest level since 1979.
</TEXT>
