<FIRST>r a PM-RiverboatGambling     06-06 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Riverboat Gambling,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Illinois Trying to Catch Up in Riverboat Gambling Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS CONRAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like a paddlewheel steamer trailing in
a Mississippi River race, Illinois is trying to pass Iowa in the
riverboat gambling sweepstakes and pull in the fresh catch: dollars.
   Backers of Illinois legislation to legalize riverboat gambling
say the payoff could be 2,500 new jobs, $200 million in initial
riverfront investment and as much as $700 million a year in
economic spinoffs.
   The loser, they say, could be left at the dock.
   Iowa already has authorized riverboat gambling on the
Mississippi beginning in 1991.
   ``The (state) there first is going to attract the people,'' said
Sen. Denny Jacobs, sponsor of legislation to legalize riverboat
gambling next year on the Illinois side of the Mississippi and much
of the Illinois River.
   Jacobs' bill, and one allowing betting on the Des Plaines River,
were overwhelmingly approved by the Senate last month and are now
in the House.
   The proposals would allow blackjack, poker, slot machines and
other games on 19th-century-style riverboats or casino cruise ships.
   Unlike the Iowa legislation, which limits bets to $5 and losses
to $200 per person per excursion, the Illinois bills permit losses
up to $500. Gamblers can wager no more than an initial $5 but can
parlay their winnings without limit.
</TEXT>
