<FIRST>r a PM-ChelseaSchools     06-06 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chelsea Schools,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Senate Approves BU Takeover of Chelsea Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Senate has approved a plan by Boston
University to take over the troubled Chelsea schools for 10 years.
   In a 29-10 vote Monday, the Senate endorsed the
first-in-the-nation plan for a private university to run a public
school system.
   Chelsea schools have been woefully underfunded, according to
officials, and the 3,400 students in the largely working-class and
predominantly Spanish-speaking city outside Boston have one of the
highest dropout rates in the state.
   The bill now goes to the House, which gave its approval last
week but must consider a Senate amendment requiring periodic
reports to the state by BU.
   Monday's vote was criticized by teachers unions who say the plan
would deprive teachers of access to important personnel records.
Many officials, including Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, have also
criticized provisions exempting BU from open meeting laws.
   Dukakis has not said whether he will sign the legislation.
   BU said it will raise money from foundations and corporations
and offer a variety of programs, including education of
preschoolers and aid for pregnant teen-agers.
   ``The schoolchildren of Chelsea are going to be very happy,''
said BU spokesman Ed King. ``We're going to abide by the open
meeting and the public records laws, and we've said all along we're
going to abide by those.''
   ``The fight is not over,'' declared Paul Devlin, president of
the Massachusetts Federation of Teachers, which represents
Chelsea's teachers. The union has sued to block what he called ``an
arrogant kind of takeover.''
   Rosanne Bacon, president of the Massachusetts Teachers
Association, called the takeover an embarassment for the state.
   ``It's outrageous that Chelsea has been allowed to get to the
condition it's in,'' she said.
</TEXT>
