<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1121EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-ChinaataGlance     06-06 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China at a Glance,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summary of Developments in China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are developments in China
today:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>RIVAL ARMY FACTIONS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Armies loyal to rival political factions were reported battling
for control of Beijing.
   Soldiers of the 28th Army, believed loyal to ousted Communist
Party leader Zhao Ziyang, exchanged fire with the 27th Army, which
invaded central Beijing Saturday night to crush the pro-democracy
movement.
   A soldier of the Beijing-based 38th Army said it was fired upon
by the 27th on the west side of the city.
   The 27th has been fortifying positions around Tiananmen Square.
   Hundreds of soldiers were seen along the airport road and a main
highway in northeastern Beijing. Residents said the troops, from
the northeast city of Shenyang, were ``not shooting at the people.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OFFICIAL CASUALTIES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced that nearly 300 people had been killed
and more than 7,000 injured and said the figure included soldiers,
``thugs,'' bystanders and 23 students.
   The official figures were far lower than unofficial estimates of
more than 500 deaths.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>LI SHOOTING</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   A young guard reportedly shot four times at Premier Li Peng in
Beijing's Great Hall of the People on Sunday, slightly wounding him
in the thigh.
   The guard was immediately killed, according to the report in a
Hong Kong daily.
   Li has not been seen in public since May 25, five days after he
declared martial law.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>DENIAL OF DENG'S DEATH</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The government denied a report from Taiwan that leader Deng
Xiaoping had died, calling it a ``fabrication designed to make
people uneasy and create chaos.''
   Deng, 84, has been out of sight since May 16 and there were
reports he was hospitalized for treatment of prostate cancer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OTHER REPORTS OF FIGHTING</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   A contingent of soldiers fired directly on a crowd near a major
intersection west of Tiananmen, a foreign witness said. The witness
heard screams from the crowd, but did not know if anyone was hit.
   Another source said tanks were moving north and firing near the
university area in northwestern Beijing.
   Soldiers at some intersections have fired at any passing
vehicles.
   Unidentified people opened fire from a window on soldiers and
tanks outside the military museum in western Beijing, a witness
said. Some students and other civilians are known to have captured
weapons from soldiers over the weekend.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>BEIJING AT STANDSTILL</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   People hoarded food, public transportation was at a halt and
many people did not go to work.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>DEMONSTRATIONS IN OTHER CITIES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-government demonstrations have spread to Shanghai, Nanjing,
Chengdu and numerous other cities. Shanghai Radio said student-led
barricading of streets ``had brought the whole municipal economy to
the brink of collapse.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>FOREIGNERS IN CHINA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign embassies, including the U.S. mission, urged their
nationals to leave and some arranged special charter flights to
speed evacuation.
   Hundreds of anxious foreigners jammed airline offices and
swamped embassy switchboards with telephone calls. Several thousand
filled the international departure area of Beijing Airport.
   Several U.S. companies have accelerated a withdrawal of
expatriates from Beijing. General Electric Co., International
Business Machines Corp., Chrysler Corp. and Boeing Co. were among
companies that said they had evacuated people because of the
violence and uncertainty elsewhere in China.
   Some companies far from the violence said they had no plans to
move staff, and that operations were normal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
