<FIRST>r a PM-ByrneKilling     06-06 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Byrne Killing,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maximum Sentences Given To Two Convicted In Policeman's Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAYNER PIKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two narcotics dealers who murdered a rookie
policeman _ allegedly on orders from a drug lord _ were sentenced
to the maximum 25 years to life in prison today as more than 100
police officers cheered.
   A third dealer received the same sentence May 16 for his role in
the 1988 death of Edward Byrne, whose slaying outside the home of a
drug witness became an issue in the White House campaign and a
battle cry for law enforcement.
   Justice Thomas Demakos, in sentencing Scott Cobb and Todd Scott,
recommended that neither receive parole.
   Neither Cobb, 25, nor Scott, 20, addressed the judge.
   Demakos promised, as he did at the sentencing of co-defendant
Philip Copeland, that his last act as a judge would be to remind
the parole board of his recommendation. He labeled the pair ``unfit
to live in society.''
   Byrne, 22, was shot five times in the head at close range while
he sat in a patrol car guarding the home of a drug witness.
   Prosecutors charged that the officer was killed on orders from
alleged drug lord Howard ``Pappy'' Mason in retaliation for his
jailing on a weapons charge.
   Mason has not been charged in the slaying and has denied
involvement.
   The slaying gained widespread attention during the White House
campaign when Byrne's father, Matthew, presented his son's badge to
George Bush, saying he supported him because of Bush's support of
the death penalty.
   Matthew Byrne, a former police officer, left the courtroom
without comment today.
   The sentencing of Scott and Cobb was postponed last month while
prosecutors tried unsuccessfully to persuade the two to provide
evidence against Mason.
   A fourth defendant, alleged triggerman David McClary, is on
trial in the slaying.
</TEXT>
