<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     06-06 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khomeini Supporters Shut Down West Beirut, Shiite Areas</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Iran-Khomeini, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mourners bewailing the death of Iranian
patriarch Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini brought west Beirut to a
standstill today, but did not stop Christians and Syrians from
exchanging salvos of shellfire.
   Police said four Christian and five Druse Moslem civilians were
wounded in sporadic overnight shelling duels that ended before dawn.
   In an unrelated incident, gunmen shot and killed a Palestinian
employee of the United Nations Relief and Works Agency in
Syrian-policed west Beirut early today, police said.
   A police spokesman said Nafez Awdeh ``died instantly and the
gunmen sped away in a green Mercedes-Benz. UNRWA was notified.'' He
gave no other details.
   No comment was available immediately from the U.N. agency, which
cares for Palestinian refugees in the Middle East.
   Black flags and posters of Khomeini decorated Shiite Moslem
districts of Beirut and its southern slums.
   The 86-year-old Iranian patriarch died on Saturday of a heart
attack in Tehran after surgery for internal bleeding.
   Lebanese cranked up generators to watch Khomeini's funeral
broadcast live by the Lebanese Broadcasting Corp., run by
right-wing Christian militias. Three months of Syrian-Christian
clashes have caused chronic power shortages.
   Shiite mosques blared verses from the Koran, Islam's holy book,
as thousands of mourners flooded the Iranian Embassy to deliver
condolences.
   Cars mounted with loudspeakers drove the streets urging
businesses to close.
   ``Close! Close!'' shouted a bearded man from a car that flew the
Iranian flag and blared verses from the Koran as he drove across
west Beirut's Hamra commercial thoroughfare.
   ``Sure, sure,'' muttered a grocer, lowering his shutter.
   Banks and other private businesses that opened after observing a
one-day closure also shut down again.
   Meanwhile, police said the overnight casualties raised the toll
in the latest round of fighting in Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war
to 363 people killed and 1,430 wounded. The battles began on March
8 over a blockade Christian Gen. Michel Aoun imposed on illegal
ports run by Syrian-backed Moslem militias.
   A Arab League committee met for seven hours on Monday and made
yet another appeal for a cease-fire.
   King Hassan II of Morocco, King Fahd of Saudi Arabia and
President Chadli Bendjedid of Algeria make up the committee. The
league plans to dispatch a representative to Lebanon on Thursday to
pursue a cease-fire, said reports in Beirut's leftist newspaper
As-Safir and the independent daily An-Nahar.
</TEXT>
