<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1206EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CosmeticSurgery-Inmates     06-06 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cosmetic Surgery-Inmates,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medical Branch to Halt Cosmetic Surgery for Prison Inmates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Texas medical school
says it will put stricter limits on plastic surgery on inmates, two
years after the Legislature banned frivolous cosmetic surgery at
taxpayer expense.
   ``It is our intent to `limit down' so that we can stay out of
trouble with everybody,'' said Dr. Alvin L. LeBlanc, vice president
for hospital affairs. ``We are going to try to please the
Legislature, I can tell you that.''
   A rider to prison appropriations bills passed in 1987 and this
year prohibits use of state money for cosmetic surgery on prisoners
unless they are disfigured and suffer psychological problems
because of it.
   The university, a state school, operates a 120-bed prison
hospital in Galveston.
   The Houston Chronicle reported two months ago that hundreds of
prisoners over the years have gotten facelifts, liposuction _ fat
removal _ and other cosmetic surgery.
   The article quoted a 59-year-old inmate who received face and
brow lifts and liposuction as saying, ``I think it will help my
attitude and feeling about myself when I go back to the free
world.''
   School officials were quoted as saying that the practice helps
surgeons perfect their skills and improves prisoners' outlook.
   A prison policy that took effect April 28 requires that requests
for cosmetic surgery be approved by the deputy director for medical
services in the prison system and a university doctor, officials
said.
   In the past, prison psychiatrists could recommend the surgery.
   LeBlanc said he was unaware of the Legislature's limit on
cosmetic surgery until contacted by the Houston Chronicle on Monday.
   Jim Lynaugh, executive director of the Texas Department of
Corrections, said, ``We definitely were aware of that rider and
have not violated it.''
   ``When my inmates check into that hospital, I have no control of
anything except security. I don't control any medical practices in
that hospital,'' Lynaugh said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
