<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1212EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e AM-APArts:Beardsley     06-06 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Beardsley,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talent, Technology Coincide in Beardsley Exhibit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Also moved for PMs</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX4 of June 2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN J. MULLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The timing couldn't have been better:
talent and technology coincided beautifully at the end of the 19th
century for controversial artist Aubrey Beardsley.
   Though little trained in art and just 25 when he died of
tuberculosis in 1898, the drawings Beardsley made the last six
years of his life are credited with influencing such giants of
20th-century art as Pablo Picasso, Paul Klee and Edvard Munch.
   Beardsley's black and white drawings, usually for book or
magazine illustrations, were printed _ when not suppressed _
through the then new photo-mechanical reproduction process, said
Miriam Stewart, a curatorial associate at Harvard University's Fogg
Art Museum. The reproductions were faithful to the drawings and
cost less than those carved into wood blocks by craftsmen rather
than the artist.
   The Fogg has more than 50 of the drawings, which were donated by
two alumni. They constitute the most important collection of the
artist's work outside Great Britain, said Fogg Curator of Drawings
William Robinson.
   For the first time in six years the drawings are on public
display, and for the first time in more than a dozen years, they
are together in one exhibit. And since the drawings are on paper,
making them delicate and sensitive to light, they can be exhibited
only briefly, museum officials said.
   They will be shown at Harvard's Sackler Museum through July 9
together with other material, including books illustrated by
Beardsley, loaned by Harvard's Houghton Library, the Boston Public
Library and Boston's Museum of Fine Arts.
   Some of the drawings are overtly erotic; others have touches
typical of his mischief.
   He usually started his drawings with pencil and perfected them
with ink, Stewart said. In some, he used graphite.
   His acquaintances included the playwright Oscar Wilde, and
Beardsley became a sensation with his illustrations for Wilde's
play, ``Salome,'' published in 1894. The illustraions were
``described variously as having nothing to do with the play and
everything to do with it,'' Stewart said.
   Included in the Fogg exhibit are two drawings intended for the
book but suppressed from publication.
   The show also includes work done for a reprint of Malory's ``Le
Morte d'Arthur,'' Ben Johnson's ``Volpone,'' Alexander Pope's ``The
Rape of the Lock,'' Aristophanes' ``Lysistrata,'' and for the
periodicals, The Yellow Book and The Savoy.
   Drawings for ``Bon-Mots,'' a collection of witticisms are ``sort
of elaborate doodles ... some quite grotesque,'' Stewart said.
   A voracious reader, Beardsley sometimes exchanged drawings for
books, and it was through this that his career was launched when he
was chosen to illustrate ``Le Morte d'Arthur.'' He was 20.
   Some drawings resemble posters and advertisements. ``He was of
his time, and he was not trying to create a lyrical past,'' Stewart
said.
   Beardsley began writing an erotic novel, but never completed it.
He became a Roman Catholic the year before he died, and on his
death bed asked that some of his drawings be destroyed. The
publisher who had them did not.
   The Fogg's collection came from alumni who had different reasons
for collecting Beardsley's work. Grenville L. Winthrop, who was
graduated in 1889 and who descended from the first governor of
Massachusetts, bequeathed to Harvard 23 original Beardsley drawings
among more than 3,700 art objects.
   Scofield Thayer, class of 1913 and onetime editor and part-owner
of the literary review The Dial, had more than 30 drawings that
became the Fogg's when he died.
   Winthrop liked the lines and design of Beardsley's work; Thayer
liked the daring subject matter, Robinson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890606-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1216EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e AM-APArts:Carreras     06-06 0826</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Carreras,0843</SECOND>
<HEAD>Music Helped Spanish Tenor Live</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the Spanish tenor Jose Carreras lay in a
Seattle hospital battling leukemia, music helped him to get through
the ordeal. Music, he says, ``has this spiritual strength.''
   ``Every day, I was listening to music with a Walkman in my
sterilized room. One of the pieces _ I had to hear it every day _
was Rachmaninoff's `Piano Concerto No. 2.' I was listening to many
versions of it, also Rachmaninoff playing it himself,'' said
Carreras who gave a recital at Carnegie Hall on May 25, his first
appearance in more than two years.
   ``The most important thing for me was to save my life. All the
rest came after this,'' he said.
   Carreras' leukemia is now in remission. ``Now I'm not under any
kind of treatment. I have a routine blood test once a month, that's
all. I travel around, I play some sports, I eat anything, drink
anything. There are no limitations in my life.''
   He makes long-range plans, including a co-production next year
between several European TV networks on the great opera singer
Enrico Caruso.
   Audiences are delighted as the 42-year-old Carreras makes his
``comeback'' recitals.
   He performed last July before 150,000 in Barcelona, and also
appeared in Vienna, at the Vatican and in other European cities.
This spring he was in Seattle, Washington and New York. In
February, he recorded Saint-Saens' ``Samson et Dalila'' and since
has recorded Halevy's ``La Juive'' for Philips. In July, he'll
return to opera, where he made his fame, singing in Barcelona in
Cherubini's ``Medea'' with soprano Montserrat Caballe.
   Carreras is ranked as one the top tenors in the world. But he
was often taken to task for vocal roughness, believed to be caused
by singing too often and singing roles too heavy for his voice, so
that he had to press for volume.
   ``Before, my career was the most important thing in my life,''
he said. ``Like anybody who succeeds, I had to fight a lot and have
a lot of discipline. Now, I'm more interested to have the
opportunity to sing on stage again and communicate with people
through my voice.''
   Carreras thinks his voice is essentially the same, but rested.
``I was lying in a hospital for nine months. It was a hard period.
But my vocal chords were resting. Thank God all the therapy and
treatments and radiation did not affect my vocal chords or mucous
membranes.
   ``Maybe as a singer I'm a little deeper or more mature. There is
a parallel between the artist and the human being.''
   He plans to include more lyrical roles in my repertoire as he
gets back to work. ``What is going to change for sure is the rhythm
of my career. I don't plan to sing more than three or four times in
one month and to have, if possible, a month of holiday every year.
   ``I'm going to enjoy not only my professional life, that is what
I did for 17 years, but to enjoy also the human side of my life
more than before,'' he said. Carreras has two children, Alberto,
15, and Julia, 10.
   ``I don't regret at all that I concentrated so much on my
profession. I had a wonderful life.''
   Carreras, who sang the part of Tony on the ``West Side Story''
record conducted by Leonard Bernstein, made the soundtrack for a
``La Boheme'' film in May 1987. That was when he fell ill.
   The diagnosis was acute lymphocytic leukemia. His doctors in
Spain recommended that he go to Seattle's Fred Hutchinson Cancer
Research Institute. Seattle also appealed to Carreras because he
felt he would be less of a media event there than in Europe.
   ``The treatment was bone marrow transplant. They took out my
bone marrow, treated it and gave it back to my body. This is a
revolutionary treatment which needs more and more research,'' he
said. To this end, the singer founded the Jose Carreras
International Foundation for the Prevention of Leukemia.
   ``It is unbelievable the thousands of letters, messages,
telegrams, phone calls,'' he said. ``This really touched me so
much. I think that gave me even more the strength to fight.''
   His next opera appearance after ``Medea'' will be in a new opera
about Columbus, which was postponed when he became sick. Now he'll
sing the title role in September in Barcelona. ``After this, I
think I will go back to opera in Vienna, Covent Garden, La Scala
and the Metropolitan Opera.''
   His time will be divided three ways, Carreras said, among
``singing new roles, new recitals, new recordings; free time _
pleasure, sports, friends; and the foundation _ meetings,
appointments, traveling, besides all the performances I give to
benefit the foundation. I have to tell you my life is quite busy
even though I sing less.
   ``I do everything with such a joy, you cannot imagine.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890606-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1217EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CrackHouse-PhotoPkg     06-06 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crack House-Photo Pkg,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Bronx Commune Members Share Life of Drugs and Crime</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY300,301,302,303,304,305 May 31</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP LaserPhoto Package</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK LENNIHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Staff Photographer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The five men and one woman have shared the
boarded-up South Bronx brownstone since 1983, their lives devoted
to drugs and crime.
   ``We're closer to each other than to our families,'' says Donna,
a crack addict who is undergoing methadone treatment to help fight
heroin addiction. ``We survive because we take care of each other.''
   Frank, 33, is the group leader. Hooked on heroin when he was 11,
the Bronx native has been in and out of methadone programs since he
was 18. The methadone blocks his appetite for heroin, but smoking
crack, a concentrated cocaine crystal, now satisfies his cravings
for a high.
   Albert, Michael and Fred are crack addicts, too. Kenny has a
heroin habit.
   The commune members have been evicted four times from the
building, which Michael's parents owned until the city seized it
for back taxes. The roof leaks and the ceilings are falling in. The
dank hallway reeks of urine. A rotting staircase leads to the
second-floor living area. A single bulb illuminates a semicircle of
mattresses that are beds by night and sofas by day. Old clothing is
stuffed in plastic bags or piled in corners. Frank's pit bull,
Coco, is kept chained to a radiator, a deterrent to unwanted
visitors.
   There is no heat or running water. The group members take sponge
baths using buckets filled with water taken from a hydrant outside.
A plastic pail is their toilet; it is emptied each morning into a
sewer pipe out on the street.
   Each member is responsible for raising the $1,000 a week it
takes to keep the group's drug habit satisfied. They're willing to
talk about their lives and crimes, they say, because they have
nothing to lose.
   Frank breaks into subway turnstiles and steals tokens. Each
token is worth $1 to a subway rider; newsstand operators and
convenience store owners in the Bronx pay him $75 for 100 tokens.
   ``It's a victimless crime. (We're) not hurting anybody. (We're)
taking back a little of what (we) gave the city,'' he says.
   But his crimes aren't always victimless.
   ``When we ran out of money we've looked at each other and said,
`Let's go hold up a taxi cab driver.' And we did.''
   Frank also deals crack. He pays $5 for a vial that holds less
than a quarter-teaspoon and sells it for $10. Some of his regular
customers include a Long Island gas station owner, a stockbroker, a
Manhattan free-lance artist, a former Amtrak motorman and a Xerox
customer service representative.
   Albert steals copper wire from Metro North commuter railroad
yards and sells it as scrap. He also strips copper wiring and pipes
from abandoned refrigerators and buildings, collects abandoned
mattresses and recycles bundles of unsold newspapers.
   Kenny describes himself as a ``real, real, real good thief.'' He
shoplifts, specializing in videotapes, electronic goods, medicines
and cigarettes. ``I take anything that ain't nailed down.''
   Donna's monthly welfare check goes for crack. ``The day her
welfare check comes in we lay in bed all day getting high,'' says
Frank.
   The group is not unaware of their condition.
   ``We're living like animals,'' Frank says. Since their most
recent eviction, in February, Frank has picked out two abandoned
buildings in the neighborhood in better condition that they can
move into.
   In addition, Donna expects to begin receiving her late husband's
Social Security benefits. He was a heroin addict who died in
December. Their 15-year-old son is in her parents' custody.
   She and Frank have been thinking of using the benefits to rent
an apartment to escape their squalid lifestyle.
   Albert is convinced he can break his crack addiction and
re-enter the mainstream. He has moved into a shelter for homeless
men and says, ``I'll be better in a few months, looking for a job.''
   Frank isn't so hopeful for himself and the others. ``Some of us
are beyond being saved. All of us somewhere in the back of our mind
have a death wish. We just don't have the courage to do it
outright.''
</TEXT>
