<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1218EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Merrimac     06-06 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Merrimac,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Floating Power Plant Starts Trip Up the Mississippi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's largest prefabricated, floating
power plant _ 25,000 tons, 12 stories high and 456 feet long _
began a slow, 208-mile journey up the Mississippi River today to
its work site.
   Pushed and pulled by six tugboats, the Merrimac headed for a
point 40 miles south of Vidalia, where it will be put in operation
on the west bank of the Mississippi.
   Louisiana's first hydroelectric plant will creep upriver at 2 to
4 mph, meaning a trip of two to four days, according to Merrimac
Corp., which commissioned the $500 million project. The plant will
serve Vidalia.
   About 75 people applauded as the Merrimac slipped away from the
docks at Avondale Shipyards.
   A highway bridge at Baton Rouge is expected to be the major
obstacle. The vessel will have to be pumped with ballast water and
sunk 40 to 50 feet to pass safely underneath.
   The Merrimac will divert water from the Mississippi through
eight giant turbines, creating 192 megawatts of electricity, enough
to light a city of 200,000.
   Owners of the power plant are Merrimac of New York and Dominion
Capital Inc. of Virginia.
</TEXT>
