<SECOND>PM-Overnight Visits,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Goes To U.S. Supreme Court To Have Boyfriend Spend The Night</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A divorcee whose boyfriend was barred by
a judge from spending the night while her children were home has
taken her case to the nation's highest court.
   Carla J. Parrillo appealed to the Supreme Court on Monday,
arguing she was deprived of a ``fundamental right to be free from
government influence within the confines of her own home,'' said
her lawyer, Patrica A. Hurst of the American Civil Liberties Union.
   In a case initiated by Ms. Parrillo's former husband, Justin
Parrillo Jr., a Family Court judge ruled in 1986 that she may not
let her boyfriend stay over because the visits seemed to harm her
three children psychologically.
   The ruling by Judge William Goldberg was upheld in March by the
state Supreme Court.
   The Parrillos were divorced in 1986 and she was given custody of
the children, ages 9, 11 and 13 at the time.
   Ms. Parrillo maintained that overnight visits by boyfriend
Joseph DiPippo once or twice a week caused no harm to the children.
She testified they liked him.
   The children told the judge they got along well with DiPippo,
although the eldest said there were times he did not like the man.
   The judge found that if Ms. Parrillo married DiPippo, the issue
would become moot.
</TEXT>
