<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1237EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-DukeEffect Bjt   06-06 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Duke Effect, Bjt,0757</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-KKK Leader Stirs Things Up But Changes Little</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Duke, ex-Ku Klux Klan leader
turned ambitious freshman legislator, riled some people with his
election, but during his first regular lawmaking session he has
hardly made a dent in Louisiana government.
   With the 1989 general session nearing its end, none of his bills
has made it through the legislative process. Only one was passed by
the House and it is pending in a Senate committee.
   ``Some of my legislation's gone through. I mean I'm only a
two-month freshman legislator and I think I've done quite well,''
Duke said.
   It's not unusual for a newcomer to have difficulty getting
legislation passed. Rep. James St. Raymond had a similar experience
last year.
   ``The major difference is David is sort of a one-issue type of
guy. He's interested in the racial issue,'' St. Raymond said.
   The legislative session could end as early as this weekend.
   Duke, 38, was elected in February to represent a nearly
all-white district in suburban New Orleans after a ``no-tax''
campaign that focused on ``civil rights'' for everyone _ including
whites.
   Duke is a former grand wizard of the Ku Klux Klan, which he left
in 1980 in a dispute with a rival faction. He then formed the
National Association for the Advancement of White People, which he
still heads.
   He ran for president in 1988, first as a Democrat and then on
the Populist Party ticket. He registered as a Republican days
before entering the House race, which he won by 227 votes in a
runoff with a long-time Republican who was endorsed by President
Bush and former President Reagan.
   Republican National Committee Chairman Lee Atwater called for
Duke's censure as a charlatan after the election.
   A challenge to his seating in the Legislature fizzled when 69 of
102 lawmakers backed him. Several representatives said they were
inundated with calls from constituents across the state insisting
that Duke be seated.
   When the regular session began in April, Duke offered nine bills
which would, among other things, have eliminated affirmative action
and minority set asides and required drug testing for housing
project residents and welfare recipients.
   One Duke bill is dead on the House floor. One is pending in a
Senate committee. A third was gutted in committee and sent to the
House floor, where it was shelved. Six languish in House committees
and are not expected to get out.
   Seated at one end of the back row of desks, Duke is not one of
the plentiful lower chamber gadflies. He rarely goes to the
microphone to speak on others' bills.
   Duke's legislation seems to be a target for procedural
torpedoes, including one fired by Rep. Mitch Landrieu, a young
white legislator whose district includes a housing project.
Landrieu got the House to table Duke's bill to scrap affirmative
action laws.
   ``It was a short House and they just happened to get two switch
votes which made a difference on that particular vote,'' Duke said.
``What Mitch Landrieu did is he robbed the people of the right to
hear the points of view and really have equal rights on this
matter. We must have equal rights in this state for everybody.''
   Another Duke bill, to deny welfare benefits to drug users by
requiring them to be tested, was weakened in a House committee to
affect only welfare recipients convicted of drug crimes. It is
awaiting debate by the full House.
   The bill in the Senate committee would require teen-agers to
pass drug tests to get driver's licenses, but it was gutted by
amendments offered by a black legislator, Rep. C.D. Jones.
   ``It's a unique situation. He's sort of an internationally known
fellow and that puts added pressure on him ... to get a lot
accomplished,'' St. Raymond said. ``I told him he could work within
the Republican Caucus _ `We'll give you a chance or you can go off
and set your agenda.' He's kind of gone off on his own.''
   But Duke said he believes his presence has made a difference.
   ``I think I've pushed the whole House of Representatives more to
the issues of the middle class and more to the issues of my agenda,
my campaign agenda, which is equal rights for all and reform of the
welfare system,'' Duke said. ``I think we're moving along quite
well.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
