<DOCNO> AP890606-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1253EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Poland-Elections 3rdLd-Writethru a0541 06-06 0803</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Elections, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0541,0829</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Rejects Government's Offer Of Governing Coalition</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to move up to 4th graf reference to prime
minister, Cabinet resignations, EDITS to conform; Pickup 11th graf pvs:
`At a...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity said today that despite its
overwhelming victory in parliamentary elections it will not accept
the Communist Party's offer to join a governing coalition.
   In a conciliatory move, however, the free trade union movement
offered to stand by the agreement made with authorities in April
and allow the party the two-thirds majority in Parliament's
powerful lower house.
   Up to 35 of those seats may be vacant because high party and
government officials such as Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski
appeared to have been defeated in Sunday's vote despite running
unopposed.
   Rakowski will offer his resignation and that of his Cabinet when
the new parliament convenes in June, said deputy government
spokesman Zbyslaw Rykowski.
   Voters disgruntled by the Communists' more than 40 years of
authoritarian rule and mismanagement of the economy gave few of the
high-ranking officials the majority needed to gain seats.
   Solidarity won an overwhelming majority of seats to the new
100-member Senate and virtually all the 161 seats it was permitted
in the lower house, or Sejm, according to unofficial returns. A
handful of seats may be decided in runoffs on June 18.
   On Monday, the party conceded defeat in what was Poland's most
democratic balloting in more than four decades, but fears were
raised that the outcome could precipitate a new political crisis.
The result gave an opposition group in Eastern Europe control of a
freely chosen chamber of Parliament for the first time since the
postwar Communist takeover.
   The Communists have urged Solidarity to join a governing
coalition, an arrangement unprecedented in the Soviet bloc.
   ``We cannot do reforms by ourselves. ... We need each other,''
Rykowski said today.
   He declined to be specific, saying such questions would have to
wait until the new parliament is seated.
   At a news conference today, Solidarity spokesman Janusz
Onyszkiewicz said the union considers itself bound by the April
accords in which it agreed to give the government a majority in the
460-member Sejm _ 299 seats.
   Authorities should thus be allowed to fill the vacant seats as
they please, he said.
   Onyszkiewicz ruled out a formal governing coalition: ``All
candidates for deputy and senator stated that they will enter the
Sejm or Senate as the opposition. That was made very clear.''
   But he said that did not rule out future ``joint actions and
joint decisions'' to solve specific problems.
   Senior Solidarity adviser Bronislaw Geremek told reporters the
union was ready to act jointly with the government to work for
reform.
   Onyszkiewicz praised Monday's statement by Communist Party
spokesman Jan Bisztyga, who acknowledged the party's electoral
defeat.
   ``It was a very important statement because it shows that the
government and the party are committed to a peaceful transition
from the present political situation to a more democratic
situation,'' he said.
   Solidarity wants totally free elections in four years, without
any pre-reserved seats for either side.
   Jubilant union supporters celebrated their election win with
Russian champagne into the night Monday at Warsaw campaign
headquarters.
   Although final official results were not expected until midweek,
voters rejected government-backed candidates nearly everywhere.
   Poland's leader, Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, on Friday suggested a
post-election ``grand coalition,'' though no specific explanations
have been given of what he intended.
   Solidarity's victory was shocking in its proportions for the
authorities.
   Leading officials likely failing to win the necessary votes for
a seat in Parliament include Interior Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak and
eight of the ruling Politburo's 17 members, including No. 2 Jozef
Czyrek.
   Though rejected, the government officials are allowed to keep
their posts. In his dramatic concession of defeat Monday, Bisztyga
acknowledged on television a ``decided majority'' for Solidarity
and appealed for calm.
   With or without a formal coalition of Solidarity and the
Communist leadership that long sought to crush it, it appeared
certain the two would have to cooperate.
   The government needs Solidarity if it is to end a protracted
economic crisis that includes 80 percent inflation that last year
touched off a series of crippling strikes. The country has a $39
billion foreign debt.
   The Solidarity-controlled Senate will have veto power over all
legislation, and could only be overridden by a two-thirds majority
in the Sejm.
   But with at best a 65 percent majority of the Sejm seats, the
Communist Party and its allies would need at least 10 Solidarity
votes in the lower house to override a veto.
   The Sejm and Senate are required to convene after June 18 to
elect the president, a new office the Communists had hoped to award
to Jaruzelski through a majority in the Sejm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
