<FIRST>r a PM-MosaicsTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0566 06-06 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mosaics Trial, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0566,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gallery Owner Says Dealer Was Diligent in Researching Mosaics</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with New York dealer saying Indianapolis
was diligent in seeking information on the mosaics. PICKS UP 8th graf pvs,
`Goldberg testified ...'; DELETES last two grafs to tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JODI PERRAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York City art dealer testified today
that Peg Goldberg ``left no stone unturned'' in her attempt last
summer to learn whether four sixth-century Christian mosaics
offered for sale were stolen.
   ``I think her inquiry met the best professional standards,''
said Andre Emmerich, owner of Andre Emmerich Gallery.
   Goldberg's ownership of the mosaics is being challenged by the
Republic of Cyprus and its Greek Orthodox Church, who claim the
works were stolen from a church in northern Cyprus and smuggled out
of the Mediterranean island nation.
   They are asking a federal judge to order the suburban
Indianapolis dealer to return the mosaics.
   On Monday, Goldberg testified she believed the man who sold her
the four mosaics obtained them legally. She also said she made
inquiries around the world to see if any claims had been made
against the art.
   Emmerich, a witness for Goldberg, said in a videotaped
deposition that comparing her with international dealers would be
like comparing ``the corner store to Bloomingdale's.'' But he said
her investigation of the mosaics before she purchased them was as
complete as any more-experienced dealer would have made.
   ``I couldn't have expected more. She left no stone unturned,''
he said.
   He said the International Foundation for Art Research, which
Goldberg contacted by telephone, is considered the most complete
and readily available source on stolen artwork.
   The mosaics, which are believed to date to 525 A.D., depict
Jesus Christ as an adolescent, the apostles James and Matthew and
an archangel. They are among only a handful of icons surviving from
the first centuries of Christianity.
   Goldberg on Monday testified she believed Aydin Dikmen, who sold
her the mosaics, had been an archaeologist for the Turkish Republic
of Northern Cyprus. She said she did not know the breakaway
government is not recognized by the United States.
   She said she was told ``that in the process of his other duties,
he had found these pieces, that he had been able to make
application to acquire them and that had subsequently been granted
by the government.''
   Goldberg testified she called customs officials in the United
States, Switzerland, Germany and Turkey and found no claims against
the mosaics.
   She said she also called UNESCO in Switzerland and the
International Foundation for Art Research, which keeps an inventory
of stolen art.
   She did not ask UNESCO if the mosaics were stolen, only whether
any treaties would prevent her from bringing them to the United
States, and was told no, she testified.
   Goldberg said she asked the art foundation whether it had any
record of the mosaics being reported stolen and was told no.
   UNESCO and several other international art groups did have
reports that the mosaics were stolen.
   On cross-examination by attorney Thomas R. Kline, Goldberg said
she could not recall the names of the people she talked to.
</TEXT>
