<FIRST>r a AM-InvasionCanceled     06-06 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Invasion Canceled,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mock Invasion Of Duluth Beach Canceled After Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DULUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy has canceled plans for an
amphibious assault on a Duluth beach during a goodwill recruiting
visit this summer because of protests by peace activists, city
council members and others.
   Opponents had threatened to meet the Marine landing force on the
beach with an army of protesters.
   However, the Navy said it hasn't canceled mock landings at five
other Great Lakes cities as part of a 21-city Great Lakes
recruiting tour. ``As far as I know, Duluth is the only place in
the Great Lakes where we've met opposition,'' said Navy Chief Petty
Officer Steven Fiebing.
   He said the USS Boulder still will dock in Duluth on July 21 so
people can tour the ship.
   ``I spent a horrible weekend watching the news from China. It's
nice to know we can communicate with our military,'' said City
Council President Joyce Benson.
   Not everyone was happy.
   ``There was more opposition to this than the invasion of
Grenada,'' said Dan Russell, head of the Duluth Convention and
Visitors Bureau, which helped organize the event. He said the
landing would have been a ``great opportunity for us to sell the
fact that Duluth has seven miles of beautiful beach.''
   Original plans called for 200 Marines in amphibious tanks to
storm ashore and ``capture'' a beach house on Minnesota Point, a
narrow strip of land that separates Duluth Harbor and Superior Bay
from Lake Superior.
   But at least a dozen religious and peace groups said such an
exercise glorified violence and war and was not an appropriate way
to recruit the city's young people, and they planned a group of
protesters to defend the beach.
   The Navy said it was not swayed, but relented after Benson
telephoned some top Navy officials and Council Member Frank Jewell
threatened to introduce a resolution opposing the use of the beach
for the landing.
   ``The resolution would say there are a number of ordinances that
prohibit such things as the use of firearms or motorized vehicles
from the beach,'' said Jewell.
   ``They probably just assumed a permit wouldn't be necessary. The
military usually doesn't apply for a permit to storm beaches,''
Russell said.
   Other cities where amphibious landings are scheduled are
Cleveland; Michigan City, Ind.; Lorain, Ohio; Erie, Pa., and
Rochester, N.Y.
</TEXT>
