<FIRST>r a AM-OnionField     06-06 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Onion Field,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Onion Field' Killer's Arrest Is Latest in Long String</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST COVINA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Onion Field'' police killer Jimmy
Lee Smith was in jail without bail Tuesday on charges of
terrorizing a woman, the latest in a string of run-ins with the law
since he was paroled in 1982.
   Smith, 58, was being held for investigation of false
imprisonment, attempted rape and assault with a deadly weapon,
police said Tuesday.
   Smith and Gregory Powell were convicted of kidnapping two Los
Angeles policemen in March 1963 and driving them to an onion field
south of Bakersfield, where Powell shot one officer to death and
wounded his partner.
   The crime was recounted in former Los Angeles policeman Joseph
Wambaugh's best-selling novel, ``The Onion Field,'' which was made
into a movie. Powell and Smith were twice sentenced to death for
the killing, but the sentences were overturned on appeal.
   Smith was paroled in February 1982 after serving 19 years at
Soledad Correctional Facility. A few months later, he was back in
prison for six months after failing a drug test and not telling his
parole officer he was leaving the Los Angeles area.
   Two years later, he was convicted in Los Angeles of selling
heroin while on parole and was sentenced to five years in prison.
He served 2{ years and was released in 1986.
   Police Lt. Lee Rossman said Smith is accused of holding a
36-year-old woman against her will over the weekend and of
assaulting and attempting to rape her. Powell is serving a life
term and was denied parole last year.
</TEXT>
