<FIRST>r a AM-ArizonaBudget     06-06 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arizona Budget,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mofford Vetoes Spending Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Gov. Rose Mofford vetoed a $3.2
billion budget from the Republican-controlled Legislature and
demanded that Democrats get a greater say.
   The veto, unprecedented in state history, came Monday on the
148th day of what was supposed to be a 100-day session and left the
state without a spending plan for the fiscal year that begins July
1.
   Republican legislative leaders agreed to meet with Democrats and
said they would suspend most other business for the week.
   Conservative lawmakers said the veto might backfire on Mrs.
Mofford if it prompted them to reopen budgets for agencies for
which she already had gotten what she wanted.
   In a radio address, Mrs. Mofford said the GOP plan was at least
$165 million out of balance, ``does not meet or adequately fund our
moral and legal obligations'' and ``undermines the economic future
of the state by defaulting on investments that need to be made.''
   The budget was put together on an ``exclusively partisan basis''
with the 90-member Legislature's 39 Democrats left on the
sidelines, she said.
   Mrs. Mofford's spending proposal calls for $86 million to $116
million more in overall spending than the GOP plan, and puts
different amounts of money into some areas.
   Mrs. Mofford's budget seeks about $40 million for employee pay
raises, while the Legislature wants to spend $17.8 million, for
example. And it proposes $22 million more in welfare agency
spending than the GOP plan.
   The GOP plan represents an 11 percent increase over this year's
spending. Some Republicans criticized Mrs. Mofford for vetoing the
full budget, instead of just the items she objected to, adding that
she had not played a major role in budget talks apart from putting
out an official proposal in January as part of her State of the
State message.
   ``She reminds me of groundhog day,'' said Sen. Leo Corbet. ``She
came out and gave the State of the State, and saw her shadow and we
haven't seen her since.''
   No other governor in Arizona's history has vetoed a full budget,
according to the House clerk's office.
   ``I think of all of the options the governor had available to
her, she selected the worst one,'' said Senate majority leader John
Mawhinney.
   ``If the governor was unhappy with either the revenue package or
the budget, then what we needed was clear indication of what it is
that she felt she couldn't live with,'' he added.
</TEXT>
