<DOCNO> AP890606-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1324EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Foley-InWaiting     06-06 0807</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foley-In Waiting,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>The New Speaker: Business As Usual in Extraordinary Times</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-House Leadership Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Wright sat alone over a draft of his
resignation speech, while nearby in the Capitol, House Majority
Leader Tom Foley hosted a breakfast meeting with Bush
administration budget officers.
   All around him last week, ambitious Democrats were scrambling
for support in House leadership races, but not Foley. ``I was not
going to campaign for an office for which there was no vacancy,''
he would say later.
   Tuesday, just after noon, the man from Spokane, Wash., filled
the vacancy. Wright was out as Speaker of the House. Foley was in.
   Throughout the turmoil over Wright's political demise, Foley
went out of his way to conduct business as usual. Budget meetings,
funerals, a ride down Main Street _ he kept to a normal schedule
during an extraordinary week.
   ``It was a very very wrenching time,'' he says now. ``I would
have hoped if I had a chance to become speaker, it would have
happened through the normal succession.''
   His activities during this unusual succession may provide a hint
of his leadership style in the House. Publicly, Foley worked to
keep the House moving on a legislative agenda that slipped badly
over the past several months. Privately, he played a quiet,
behind-the-scenes role in the tumultuous events.
   Some Democrats urged Foley, 60 years old and a 25-year veteran
of the House, to distance himself from the wounded speaker. He
refused, telling a reporter, ``I believe strongly in political
loyalty.''
   ``It hasn't been that difficult to stick with Wright,'' he
added. In fact, political observers would have been astonished to
see Foley add to Wright's difficulties. Instead, he seemed to
bolster the beleaguered speaker by working to keep the House in
motion.
   Foley kept one eye on the politics of succession, one eye on
legislation.
   He invited budget director Richard Darman and others over for
breakfast. Over scrambled eggs and bacon served in the elegant
majority leader's dining room, the session revolved around the nuts
and bolts of a budget.
   Foley flew to Seattle for former Sen. Warren Magnuson's funeral
and then went on to his eastern Washington district. With a growing
entourage of reporters, he tended to local matters and took time
for a ride in an old Chevy convertible down the main street of
Oakesdale _ about as far away from the Capitol as a politician can
get in both distance, attitude and spirit.
   Even there, Foley was unable to escape from the political
firestorm building in the other Washington. Foley had been
surprised two days before by the news that Democratic Whip Tony
Coelho, following a barrage of reports about his junk bond
investments, was going to resign.
   Late in the day came a CBS report that said the Justice
Department was investigating the personnel practices of Rep.
William Gray, D-Pa., the man who heads the Democratic caucus in the
House.
   ``I want to believe and I hope there was no plan to attempt
political intervention by the Justice Department'' in the Coelho
and Gray cases, Foley said.
   In private back at the Capitol, trusted by both sides, he played
a quiet role in ill-fated negotiations that would have brought
Wright's immediate resignation in exchange for dismissal of some
charges by the House ethics committee.
   He had been Wright's occasional confidant, as well.
   Twice during recent months, Wright indicated he was thinking of
stepping down at the end of his term and told Foley he should
prepare to become speaker. Both times, Foley urged Wright to avoid
any precipitous decisions.
   Foley and Wright met last Tuesday morning, ostensibly to discuss
the week's legislative agenda, but the speaker broached the subject
of resignation and again made clear he wanted to lay his case
before the country and Congress and also wanted a permanent record
in the annals of the House.
   Wednesday began with the budget summit, but within hours Wright
told Foley he intended to make a speech on the House floor _ a
signal he was going to resign.
   A flurry of meetings in Foley's office followed, including one
with Rep. Julian Dixon, D-Calif., chairman of the ethics committee.
   Foley spent the next several hours on the House floor. In the
process, he informed Republican Leader Bob Michel of the speaker's
decision. Wright asked Foley to preside over the House and it was
Foley who recognized the speaker for his hour-long resignation
speech.
   Afterward, Foley quickly was on the phone asking colleagues for
support, now that he could make an open bid for the speakership.
   There were no other contenders. But he said he had learned from
former Speaker Thomas ``Tip'' O'Neill not to take anything or
anyone for granted.
   ``People like to be asked for their support one-on-one,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
