<FIRST>r w AM-BosWash     06-06 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BosWash,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Boston-Washington Corridor Is Home to One in Six Americans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The massive Boston-Washington urban corridor
is home to one in six Americans, the Census Bureau reported Tuesday.
   Data from a new census study also show that the corridor
contains almost one in four of the Americans who reside in
metropolitan areas.
   The data, for 1987, showed 43.5 million people residing in the
East Coast corridor which includes 25 contiguous metropolitan
statistical areas.
   With a national population of 243,396,000 people as of July 1,
1987, that means about 17 percent of the nation lived in the
megalopolis.
   And the bureau reports that 187,072,000 Americans lived in
metropolitan areas, nearly 23 percent of them in the
Boston-Washington region.
   There are four major clusters within the Boston-Washington
region: New York-Philadelphia, 27.8 million; Boston-Providence,
R.I., 6.2 million; Washington-Baltimore, 6.1 million and
Harrisburg-York, Pa., 1 million.
</TEXT>
