<FIRST>r w AM-US-IndiaPrize     06-06 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-India Prize,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prize Goes to Developer of Indian Milk Cooperatives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Verghese Kurien, responsible for a network of
milk cooperatives credited with improving the diet of millions in
his native India, was named winner of a $200,000 prize Tuesday.
   Kurien, 67, was the second Indian to get the prize since it was
created in 1987 and given to M. S. Swaminathan. Last year, it was
won by Robert F. Chandler, founder of the International Rice
Research Institute.
   The World Food Prize is given by General Foods Fund Inc., a
foundation financed by General Foods Corp.
   The prize was announced by Norman Borlaug, the American who won
the Nobel Peace Prize in 1970 for his work on the ``green
revolution'' in the production of grain.
   Kurien is chairman of India's National Dairy Development Board.
Under his supervision, milk procurement rose from 190,000 tons in
1970 to almost 3 million tons now. His cooperative system has been
extended to other food products.
   He is a graduate of Michigan State University and of India's
Madras University.
</TEXT>
