<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1354EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Jackson     06-06 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jackson,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson Urges Bank to Make Loans for Housing and Small Firms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson asked Democratic senators
Tuesday to create a domestic world bank which would make loans for
housing and small businesses and generate revenue for government
services.
   Jackson, a former presidential candidate, spoke at a private
meeting of about 20 Democrats on investment plan, which would make
heavy use of pension funds but require no tax money.
   The bank would get its pool of capital from 10 percent of the
$800 billion in public pension funds and money that private pension
programs would be willing to invest, Jackson told reporters.
   The program would be administered by a board of labor,
management and government representatives.
   He said the bank would make government-secured loans which could
``begin to build affordable housing, economically integrated
housing, small and medium-sized businesses.'' The loans would
``generate revenue, which of course pays taxes for a health plan,
and for police and fire services and for education,'' he said.
   Jackson said the senators exhibited ``a great degree of
optimism'', adding that Sens. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., and
Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., promised to conduct hearings on the idea.
   The investment plan is needed, Jackson said, because the budget
deficit prohibits substantial investment in rural and urban
America, and ``banks and insurance companies, with redlining, would
not invest in urban or rural America.''
   ``The Democratic Party ... is at a point to take the offensive,
to take the lead,'' Jackson said. ``Right now, the headlines are
dominated by the leadership changes on the House side and focused
on personal ethics. There is no focus on the ethical challenge to
rebuild America.''
</TEXT>
