<FIRST>r a AM-Daley-O'HareContracts     06-06 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Daley-O'Hare Contracts,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicago Mayor Cancels `Worthless' O'Hare Consultant Contracts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Richard M. Daley says the city is wasting
hundreds of thousands of dollars on consultants to advise on how to
keep washrooms clean and how much toilet paper to use at O'Hare
International Airport.
   Daley said Monday he has halted $1.5 million worth of consultant
contracts at O'Hare.
   Among them was a $265,000 study of O'Hare janitors by Erwin A.
France, a top adviser to Daley's predecessor, Eugene Sawyer. Daley
took office in April.
   Daley said one other study detailed how much toilet paper was
used at the airport.
   ``Do I have to tell them how much toilet paper they need to
order?'' Daley asked. ``I mean that's ridiculous. It was a waste of
money, that's all it was.''
   Daley said he had also canceled a $208,000 contract awarded to
put up Christmas decorations and $36,000 for radio ads to tell
travelers to leave for the airport early on a holiday weekend.
   Some of the contracts may be reissued at lower rates, ``but the
city is not going to pay one more cent for unnecessary studies,''
he said.
</TEXT>
