<FIRST>r a AM-VegasGasoline     06-06 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vegas Gasoline,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pipeline Servicing City May Reopen Friday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pipeline that provided 90 percent of the
gasoline for the Las Vegas area before it exploded in California
could be back in operation by Friday, which could mean a drop in
prices at the gas pump.
   Prices jumped as much as a nickel a gallon when the pipeline
exploded May 25 in San Bernardino, Calif., killing two people and
injuring 31. The blast knocked out the Calnev Co. pipeline that
carried gasoline and diesel fuel from Southern California
refineries to the Las Vegas Valley.
   Oil companies had to ship gasoline 300 miles by truck,
increasing the cost of transportation.
   Arco, the dominant oil company in southern Nevada, raised its
prices to dealers 5 cents a gallon in the first days following the
explosion. Arco officials say the company's prices ``absolutely''
will drop once the line reopens.
   Chevron officials say it cost an extra 6{ cents a gallon to
truck gasoline to Las Vegas, and not all costs were passed on to
dealers.
   No gasoline shortages or service station lines have been
reported in the city.
   The price for self service unleaded gasoline has been running
$1.10 to $1.12 a gallon since the pipeline explosion.
</TEXT>
