<DOCNO> AP890606-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1529EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Crowe-Soviet     06-06 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crowe-Soviet,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crowe Will Ask Soviet Counterparts to Spell Out Their Force-Cutting
Plans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adm. William J. Crowe, the senior U.S.
military officer, begins his first visit to the Soviet Union next
Monday and will ask his Soviet counterparts to spell out their
proposals to cut conventional forces in Europe.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, in his arms-cut
proposals, ``has talked about men and he has talked about weapons
systems,'' Crowe, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, told
reporters at the Pentagon on Tuesday.
   ``There are a lot of questions in our mind about exactly what
that means, and what dismantling means, and what they will do with
those systems, and what systems they are talking about. Those
questions have not all been answered,'' said Crowe, who during his
11-day visit will go to five of the 15 Soviet republics.
   The Eastern and Western alliances have recently proposed very
similar ideas for cutting conventional forces in central Europe,
but have not yet concluded a deal.
   Crowe said that he would ask the Soviets why they recently
increased tank production, despite statements by Gorbachev that
defense spending would be cut by 14 percent and military production
by 20 percent over coming years.
   During the trip Crowe may sign an agreement on curbing dangerous
military incidents, such as the shooting death of Maj. Arthur
Nicholson at the hands of Soviet soldiers in East Germany on March
24, 1985.
   Crowe said the proposed agreement would address naval incidents
inside territorial waters, such as the bumping of two U.S. Navy
vessels by Soviet ships off the Crimea in the Black Sea on Feb. 12,
1988, and the use of laser range finders that might blind soldiers
or sailors on the either side.
   The visit by Crowe, who will be accompanied by the vice chiefs
of the four U.S. military services, follows a tour of the United
States last July by Marshal Sergei Akhromeyev, then the Soviet
chief of staff. Akhromeyev has since become an adviser to
Gorbachev, and been replaced as defense minister by Col. Gen.
Mikhail A. Moiseyev.
   The Americans, according to an itinerary handed out at the
briefing, will visit an unidentified Soviet missile facility near
Khelmnitsky in the Ukraine, see a ground exercise in Byelorussia,
and ride on a Soviet missile cruiser and watch a naval maneuver off
Murmansk, the northern Soviet port on the Barents Sea.
   Crowe, a submariner, has asked to see the inside of a submarine,
a request that the Soviets have neither accepted nor rejected.
   ``My instincts tell me that they will be very forthcoming,'' he
said.
   He will also deliver an address at the Voroshilov military
academy, and visit numerous graveyards, laying a total of seven
wreaths.
   ``I don't know who is behind the wreaths,'' he joked at the
briefing.
   The visit also includes time for extensive discussions with
Soviet military leaders.
   ``Certainly my purpose is not to negotiate. But I discovered
last year when Marshal Akhromeyev _ and he and I had many hours
together talking _ that it was very fruitful, at least from my
perspective,'' Crowe said.
   ``We clarified things. We attempted to brush away some of the
misunderstandings. There are a lot of questions that military
people always carry around in their minds. Often we develop on our
own the wrong answers. This gives me an opportunity to address my
counterparts directly,'' he said.
   ``When Marshal Akhromeyev departed last year, I felt much better
about what I knew and what they were saying and so forth,'' said
Crowe.
   The admiral said that U.S intelligence on Soviet military
capabilities ``has been good, but obviously in certain areas we
have done better than in others.
   ``We have been surprised on occasion. We have not done as well
as we would prefer. Marshal Akhromeyev and I actually talked about
that. I think there is a built-in tendency to overestimate the
strength of ... opponents,'' he said.
   ``Marshal Akhromeyev and I on occasion pointed out to each other
that he didn't understand our forces ... I told him that he
overestimated my capability and he told me that I greatly
overestimated his. He was talking about ground and I was talking
about Navy,'' said Crowe, a naval officer. Akhromeyev is an army
officer.
   Crowe also predicted that the two sides would discuss the
military crackdown in China and developments in North and South
Korea. ``We will both have some curiosity about the other's
feelings about what is going on in that part of the world.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
