<FIRST>r p AM-Pepper'sSeat     06-06 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pepper's Seat,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida Governor Sets Special Election Dates For Pepper's Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The race is on for the seat left vacant by the
death of Rep. Claude Pepper, with early expectations that the Aug.
29 special election called Tuesday could produce the first Cuban
exile in Congress.
   Gov. Bob Martinez announced the election schedule one day after
burial of the 88-year-old congressman following a week of
ceremonies and mourning.
   ``Claude Pepper will be difficult, if not impossible, to replace
in Congress. But it's vitally important that we move as quickly as
possible so that the people of Florida's 18th congressional
district can be represented,'' Martinez said.
   Some leaders of the Republican Party, riding a wave of GOP
momentum in the state, were focusing upon state Sen. Ileana
Ros-Lehtinen of Miami as their leading candidate for the seat that
had been held by Pepper, a liberal Democrat, since its inception.
   Carlos Perez, a Cuban-born millionaire banana importer and
active supporter of Ronald Reagan and Oliver North, also said he
will run as a Republican.
   Democrats, with a longer list of interested candidates, had no
one publicly committed.
   ``The Democrats should probably rally behind one candidate,''
said Miami City Commissioner Rosario Kennedy, a Cuban-American
among the potential Democratic contenders. ``But it's too early.''
   A first primary was set for Aug. 1 and any runoff would be Aug.
15. Martinez said elections would be held on the same day to
replace state officeholders who seek the congressional seat. Under
state law, they have to resign before they run.
   Candidates must file their nominating petitions with the state
Division of Elections on June 19 or 20.
   Pepper, known nationwide for his efforts on behalf on the
elderly, won every election for the district since the first in
1962, with his closest race in the past decade a 61-39 percent
victory in 1984 over Cuban-American Ricardo Nunez. Last year, he
had no opposition at all.
   But Republicans have gained strength in the district, as
Democratic registration has sagged from 72 percent a decade ago to
54 percent now.
   Hispanics, estimated by some politicians to comprise nearly half
the district, are considered likely to support a Cuban candidate.
It's estimated that three-quarters of Cuban-American voters in the
region are Republican.
   ``I think the chances are pretty good for a Cuban-American to be
elected from that district,'' said Sergio Bendixen, a Democratic
strategist. ``Without a doubt, that person would be the most
powerful Cuban-American in the country.''
   Miami Mayor Xavier Suarez, elected in 1985 as the city's first
Cuban-born mayor, ruled himself out of the House race Tuesday.
Suarez, an independent, didn't formally endorse anyone but praised
Ros-Lehtinen. She meanwhile said she would hold a news conference
Wednesday to discuss her future.
   Republican state Rep. Al Gutman, a Cuban-born Jew whose heritage
fits two large ethnic groups in the district, was also mulling his
possibilities Tuesday.
   On the Democratic side, state Sen. Jack Gordon said he will
decide by Friday whether to run. Gordon, 67, shares much of
Pepper's constituency and liberalism, but may have problems with
Hispanic voters because of his opposition to Nicaraguan Contra aid
and other foreign policy issues.
   Raul Martinez, Cuban-born mayor of Hialeah, has long said he'd
like to run for Congress, but spokesman Steve Bovo said Martinez
would wait to hear Gordon's decision.
   Other potential Democratic candidates include Commissioner
Kennedy, Miami Beach Mayor Alex Daoud, Dade County Commissioner Joe
Gersten, State Attorney Janet Reno and former school board chairman
Paul Cejas. Cejas and Kennedy are Cuban-born.
   In the 1988 elections, Florida gave George Bush his largest
margin in any state and Republicans gained a U.S. Senate seat, two
House seats and two state Cabinet jobs. Republicans then claimed a
10-9 majority in the congressional delegation when Rep. Bill Grant
of Tallahassee switched parties after the election.
</TEXT>
