<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--GunBan     06-06 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Gun Ban,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alameda County Enacts Emergency Assault Weapon Sales Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ordinance immediately banning the sale
of military-style assault weapons in unincorporated areas of
Alameda County was passed Tuesday by the county Board of
Supervisors.
   The 5-1 vote followed action by Gov. George Deukmejian and the
Legislature restricting the sale of more than 50 kinds of
semiautomatic assault weapons throughout California.
   Supervisor Don Perata said the Alameda County ordinance closes a
loophole in the state measure, which allows people to buy
semiautomatic weapons until January and to apply for permits to
keep them after January.
   The state law created a ``window of opportunity'' to buy the
weapons, Perata said.
   ``This ordinance intends to ban such sales immediately in the
county to prevent those who would evade the law from stockpiling an
arsenal while these weapons are still legally available,'' he said.
   He said he was concerned about weapon stockpiling by drug
dealers and others who have ``ravaged our communities.''
</TEXT>
