<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-EmployeeBenefits     06-06 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Employee Benefits,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bentsen Moves To Ensure Fair Health Coverage For Lower-Paid Employees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, chairman of the Senate
Finance Committee, on Tuesday introduced a bill aimed at ensuring
that lower-paid workers get a fair share of employer-paid health
insurance coverage.
   The bill was signed by 32 other senators, including 15 members
of the Finance Committee. It would substitute for a much criticized
provision of the 1986 tax overhaul known as Section 89.
   ``Section 89 has a desirable goal _ that rank-and-file employees
should have tax-favored health and life benefits comparable to
those provided to other, well-paid employees _ but the road map for
getting there is too complicated for most American businesses to
understand,'' said Bentsen, D-Texas. ``It isn't working and even
the so-called experts can't understand the details.''
   The law requires employers to demonstrate, through complex and
often expensive tests, that their health insurance plans do not
discriminate in favor of higher-paid employees. That generally
means employees earning more than about $50,000 a year.
   Employers have complained loudly about the rules. In some cases,
critics say, employers have decided it would be simpler and less
expensive to drop all health coverage for all workers.
   The Treasury Department has delayed enforcement of the rules
until Oct. 1. There is strong pressure in Congress to repeal the
rules altogether. The Senate spent a good part of its session
Tuesday debating repeal.
   However, the Bush administration, Bentsen and Rep. Dan
Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, are calling for major changes, rather than repeal.
   Bentsen's bill would delay the rules until January. It would
view as non-discriminatory any plan that offered health insurance
to 90 percent of all employees with the employer paying at least 60
percent of the premium.
   Rostenkowski earlier introduced a bill that, in essence, would
accept any health plan that was available to 90 percent of
rank-and-file workers for an employee premium not exceeding $10 a
week for a single person or $20 for family coverage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
