<DOCNO> AP890606-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1614EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Inferno     06-06 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Inferno,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>KGB Hunts For Workers Repsonsible For Blast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers kept pumping gas into a leaking pipeline
for nearly an hour after it already had blown to pieces, spawning a
fireball that engulfed two trains and turned scores of people into
ash, state-run media said Tuesday.
   Soviet news reports said at least 190 people died in the
pipeline blast early Sunday morning on the Trans-Siberian Railroad,
about 750 miles southeast of Moscow.
   Some of the 762 people who were hospitalized with injuries from
the blast are expected to die, according to television news program
``Vremya.'' It said said half of the injured had burns over more
than 70 percent of their bodies.
   More than 200 people still were missing, and some officials said
the final death toll could reach 500.
   Health Minister Yevgeny Chazov told the government newspaper
Izvestia that the third and fourth days are the most critical for
burn victims, and that Soviet doctors lack experience in treating
such severe burns.
   ``This lack of experience obviously is complicating our work,''
he said.
   Izvestia said doctors had determined 170 injured children needed
special equipment to help them breathe, and that they were
appealing for advice and urgent airlifts of equipment from West
Germany, Japan, the United States and Italy.
   A spokesman for U.S. industrialist Armand Hammer said 10 kidney
dialysis machines were being sent from the United States.
   The blast occurred when a pipeline carrying a highly flammable
mixture of benzene, propane and butane sprang a leak, filling a
forested valley with concentrations of gas. The gas was ignited by
a spark from one of the two trains on the Trans-Siberian line
nearby.
   The trains were traveling in opposite directions and had made
unscheduled stops in the valley in the Ural Mountains.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and other officials have
charged that workers in charge of the pipeline noticed a drop in
pressure before the blast, but increased pressure instead of
shutting the line down.
   ``Vremya'' said Tuesday night that the workers continued to pump
gas through the pipeline for 55 minutes after the blast.
   An exasperated Gorbachev, briefing parliamentarians Monday after
he returned from the scene, cited ``incompetence, irresponsibility,
mismanagement, disgrace'' in the work of the pipeline.
   KGB chief Vladimir Kryuchkov, also speaking to Izvestia, said
the secret police had sent a team of investigators to the area near
Ufa to establish the truth.
   Kryuchkov said the KGB was carrying out a ``careful
investigation of the reasons and circumstances of this
extraordinary event. We understand the great difficultly of this
work.''
   The KGB ``will do all that's possible to establish the truth and
publicize the results of our work,'' he said.
   Kryuchkov said the KGB was working with prosecutors and the
Interior and Health ministries.
   The blast was heard 16 miles away, and the Soviet military chief
of staff, Gen. Mikhail A. Moiseyev, told the official Tass news
agency Monday that it had the power of 10,000 tons of TNT, or half
the power of the first atomic bomb that was dropped on Hiroshima,
Japan.
   Many of the victims, including children on the way to summer
camp, were burned beyond recognition, said the Communist Party
daily Pravda.
   ``Identification of some of them is extremely difficult and in
some cases, nothing is left but ashes,'' Pravda said.
   The blast stripped the 2.5 miles of trees and turned rail
passenger cars into twisted hulks of charred metal.
   Dozens of airplanes and helicopters ferried the injured from the
site of the blast to hospitals in the nearby cities of Chelyabinsk
and Ufa. Izvestia said 65 of the most severely burned, including
eight children, had been brought to Moscow for treatment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
