<FIRST>r a AM-ByrneKilling     06-06 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Byrne Killing,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Life Terms for Two in Murder of Rookie Cop</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents 3rd graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAYNER PIKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The driver and lookout who aided in the murder
of rookie police Officer Edward Byrne, allegedly by order of a
jailed narcotics kingpin, were sentenced Tuesday to life in prison.
   Supreme Court Justice Thomas Demakos called the defendants,
Scott Cobb, 25, and Todd Scott, 20, unfit to live in society as he
reviewed a confession in which Cobb described Scott laughing at
Byrne's slaying.
   ``The first shot, he seen the cop's brains come out. He said
that's what he was laughing at. ... Dave said he had to pull Todd
from the other side of the cop car 'cause Todd's at the cop's car
laughing, hee-hee,'' Demakos read.
   Demakos sentenced each to 25 years to life for the murder and a
concurrent term of five to 15 years for gun possession.
   Demakos also declared that his last act as a judge would be to
remind the parole board in writing of his recommendation that the
prison doors never open for the two.
   Demakos made the same promise last month when he gave the same
maximum term to Philip Copeland, a co-defendant convicted of
setting up the hit on orders from Howard ``Pappy'' Mason. The
government said Mason decreed the killing as a sign of his
displeasure at being jailed on a gun charge.
   A jury is deliberating the case of a fourth defendant, David
McClary, the alleged triggerman, who was tried separately.
   Byrne, 22, was killed by five bullets on Feb. 26, 1988, as he
sat in his patrol car. He was guarding the home of a drug case
witness.
   Defense lawyers said their clients had not gotten a fair trial.
Demakos denied without comment a motion to set aside the guilty
verdict that was returned by a jury March 29.
</TEXT>
