<DOCNO> AP890606-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1635EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Future     06-06 0811</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Future,0833</SECOND>
<HEAD>After Elections, Who Will Govern Poland?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity says it does not want to govern
despite its overwhelming public mandate in Sunday's parliamentary
elections. But if the independent union won't, who will?
   That's the question facing both the opposition and government
authorities following Solidarity's big victory over the communist
party in the first largely democratic elections in the East bloc in
more than four decades.
   The communist Polish United Workers Party is making no secret of
the fact that it wants some sort of coalition or alliance with the
Solidarity-led opposition. As deputy government spokesman Zbyslaw
Rykowski said Tuesday, ``We need one another.''
   But Solidarity was born and thrived as an opposition movement
and has no appetite for assuming power in any way but through
completely unfettered elections in four years.
   Solidarity-endorsed candidates accumulated majorities of 70-80
percent Sunday in practically every race they entered. Out of 261
candidates for the two-chamber national legislature, it seems that
only eight failed to get the 50 percent of the vote needed to avoid
a runoff election on June 18.
   In a normal parliamentary democracy, Solidarity next would
peacefully assume the reins of power. But the Polish elections were
governed by the inescapable reality that Poland remains a communist
state. And so, before agreeing to the elections, authorities were
able to insist on reserving 65 percent of the parliament seats only
for communists and their allies.
   As it turned out, the communists were having trouble filling
even these ``guaranteed'' seats.
   Some of the party's best-known leaders, including Prime Minister
Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski and eight Politburo members, appear to have
been rejected by more than half the voters even though they ran
unopposed for parliament on a ``national list'' of 35 candidates.
   In a magnanimous gesture, the Solidarity leadership affirmed
Tuesday that it will live up to the 65 percent-35 percent division
of the parliament's lower house, the Sejm, that was provided for
under the April 3 accord between the union and government on
sweeping social reforms.
   But while that saves the party from having to stage a messy
court or parliament fight for its seats, it does not allay the
humiliation of the party's loss and the resulting undermining of
its standing at home and abroad.
   Everyone now understands that in fully free elections, the party
would not stand the slightest chance of winning office.
   Anticipating the loss of the ``national list'' in an informal
talk with reporters last week, senior Politburo member Jozef Czyrek
was blunt about the possibilities.
   Defeat of the list ``would be the biggest political joke ever
committed in Poland,'' he said, with Polish reform communists who
agreed to the elections being perceived as having committed
political suicide. ``They would be laughing like mad in Prague and
Berlin,'' two hardline communist capitals, he added.
   With its lack of support evident, the party is looking to
bolster itself by drawing Solidarity into a ``grand coalition.''
   Solidarity insists it wants to remain in opposition, but the
political weakness of the party makes that seem more and more
difficult. Because of its numbers in the Senate and Sejm and its
mass popular support, the independent union will have a huge say in
policy and appointments.
   For instance, no legislation will be able to get through the new
National Assembly without Solidarity votes. The Senate has a veto
over all bills, and the party lacks enough votes in the Sjm to
override the veto.
   There is also the question of naming a new president and forming
a new government after the new Sejm and Senate are seated.
   Theoretically, Rakowski could keep his post despite having been
denied a parliament seat. But it might be difficult for him to
function effectively as prime minister after such a loss of face,
and there likely will be calls for someone more popular with the
voters to head the government.
   Similarly, the Sejm and Senate are to meet together to name a
president, a newly created executive office with strong powers
under Poland's revamped constitution that was designed to be a
bulwark to keep Poland in the Soviet bloc.
   The presidential election was supposed to be a walkaway for
Polish party leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski because of the party's
built-in majority in the Sejm. But if the ``national list'' seats
are still vacant when the vote is taken, the party will have only a
small three-vote edge.
   There have been popular calls for Solidarity leader Lech Walesa
to offer himself as the opposition's candidate. Such calls are only
likely to increase given the Solidarity election performance.
   President Walesa? Such strange things are starting to look
possible now that Poland has started down the road of democracy.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   John Daniszewski has been the Warsaw
correspondent for The Associated Press since 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
