<HEAD>Dissident Takes Refuge in Embassy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Noted Chinese dissident Fang Lizhi has been
permitted to take refuge in the U.S. Embassy in Beijing, a State
Department official said Tuesday.
   The official, who spoke on condition that he not be identified,
had few details on the circumstances or timing of Fang's arrival,
but said he had been in the embassy since Monday at least.
   ``He took refuge there for his own safety,'' the official said.
   Fand, a 53-year-old astrophysicist who has backed the democracy
movement and called Marxism a failure, was prevented by Chinese
police from attending a dinner with President Bush during the
president's February visit to Beijing even though four less
prominent other dissidents were able to attend.
   Bush and Ambassador Winston Lord protested the police action and
the Chinese government in return said it resented the invitation to
Fang and should have been told of it in advance.
   In the United States, human rights advocates criticized Bush for
not being more assertive on the issue.
