<FIRST>r a AM-StudentSlain     06-06 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Student Slain,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>14-Year-Old Victim Had Moved Away from City Crime</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOWE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 14-year-old girl was raped and strangled in
her grandparents' home, where she had moved to get away from the
crime and drug abuse in Philadelphia, her teacher said.
   ``That's what makes this so sad,'' said Jewell Elliott, principal
of the school Andrea Nicole Thomas had attended.
   ``She came here to get away from violence and the things that
wrap young people up in the city,'' Elliott said. ``She said many
times she wanted to get away from that.''
   The girl's body was found Sunday, the same day her grandparents,
John and Elmira Hawkins, had left for a weeklong Florida vacation.
An autopsy showed she had been raped and strangled. An aunt
discovered the girl's body.
   The teen-ager was scheduled to graduate Saturday with the six
other members of the eighth grade at the Seventh Day Adventist
school.
   Elliott said Miss Thomas, who had two older brothers, went to
school in Philadelphia until sixth grade, when she asked to be
transferred. She returned to Philadelphia for seventh grade and then
asked to be sent back to West Pottsgrove Township near Stowe to
finish eighth grade, Elliott said.
   ``I would see her occasionally at church during her seventh-grade
year, when she would visit her grandparents up here,'' Elliott said.
``She would tell me that boys bothered her at school, that children
skip classes and she said, `I'm not being challenged,' and she
wanted to come back where she knew there was a challenge.''
   No arrests have been made, police said.
</TEXT>
