<DOCNO> AP890606-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1929EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w BC-FoleyText 1stadd   06-06 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Foley Text, 1st add,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: Mr. Speaker.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The accomplishments of the 100th Congress will remain forever a
monument to your leadership.
   And to the great leaders of the Republican Party _ Gerald Ford,
who left this place to assume the presidency as a healing president
in a difficult time in our history, John Rhodes, and Bob Michel.
   And all of my colleagues, past and present, whose vision of the
country, though sometimes sharply different, was marked by a common
commitment to public service, shared concern for improving the
common good, and a love of this House.
   We are proud to call this the people's House, the fundamental
institution of American democracy.
   Although it is not the oldest parliament in the world, it has
existed longer as an independent, popularly elected legislature than
any other parliamentary body in history.
   As we watch the remarkable struggle of people in China, and the
growing aspirations of the people in the Soviet Union, Poland and
elsewhere to take control of their destiny, we should take great
pride that the values that gave this institution its birth and which
have flourished here and sustained us for two centuries now sweep
around the world.
   This body reflects most closely the nation at large.
   It is not, as many have suggested, a fixed, stagnant body.
   It is constantly refreshed by new members from every corner of
the country who have brought their ideas and energy to bear on
behalf of the people they represent.
   Only 7 percent of the House's current members were in the House
when I was first elected in 1964.
   Eighty-one percent of the current members have been elected since
1974.
   More than half of the current members _ 55 percent _ have been
elected since 1980.
   The constant change in membership is a source of great strength
for the House, but fundamentally, and more importantly, the House
reflects the will of the electorate.
   Our business here is the people's business.
   It is time to put divisiveness behind us, to reach out and
address the issues of national policy that members of both parties
are eager to consider.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890606-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1930EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w BC-FoleyText 2ndadd   06-06 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Foley Text, 2nd add,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: to consider.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   We must resolve to build support for schools that nourish the
love of learning and are free from drugs and violence.
   We must deal with the problem of homelessness.
   We must strive to put the country at the cutting edge of economic
innovation and the global economy.
   We must provide for the security of families, from child care to
health care.
   In a time of changing and uncertain circumstances, we must assure
our continued national security.
   We must solve our fiscal problems and protect the national and
global environment.
   On these and other important public issues, we must act
responsibly and resolutely.
   We will not reach any of these goals without a deep respect for
the House as an institution and a reaffirmation of the value of
public service.
   I have been a member of the House for 25 years.
   I take great pride, as we all do, in my profession.
   Election to public office is a free gift of a free people.
   The challenge for all of us in public life is to use that gift to
improve the conditions of those who have bestowed that enormous
trust and responsibility upon us.
   We must take pride in ourselves and in our institution.
   I am confident in the fundamental honesty and dedication of the
members of the House.
   The members of the House today meet and exceed standards of
personal conduct that are higher than at any time in our history.
   I recognize that controversy still exists in some areas, and will
address them.
   I have asked Bob Michel to join me in asking the bipartisan task
force on ethics to complete their work with deliberate speed so that
the House can consider these issues in this Congress, in this
session, in this year.
   The greatness of the House comes from its members working
collectively to address the nation's problems.
   No parliamentary body can survive for long without the basic
comity and trust necessary for us to address the nation's problems
in a constructive way.
   I do not believe we can successfully undertake our public
responsibility by tearing down this House, by abusing its
institutions.
   We cannot tolerate the continuance of the current distrust and
suspicion and expect to fulfill the public's expectations.
   After 25 years in the House, there should be no doubt that I am
proud to be a Democrat.
   I am deeply conscious, however, of the obligation I bear as
speaker of the House.
   I am speaker of the whole House, not of one party, but to each
and every member of the House, undivided by the center aisle.
   I pledge to protect the right and privileges of all members.
   I will seek the consultation, advice and counsel of leaders and
members, and I will welcome expressions of concern from all quarters
of the House.
   I have suggested to the Republican leader that we meet more
frequently to discuss business.
   He has encouraged more orderly and early cooperation on
developing the weekly program, and I welcome that suggestion.
   Together, we reiterate our commitment to the work of the ethics
task force, so that we can put this divisive period behind us.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MORE</HEAD>
