<SECOND>BC-Foley Text, 3rd add,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: behind us.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   We warmly extend the same respect to President Bush, who has
offered to work with us in a spirit of bipartianship.
   I applaud the president's pledge of cooperation and am eager to
accept it.
   Without the cooperation of both branches we will not solve
pressing national problems.
   Politics involves the clash of ideas, and we will inevitably have
disagreements.
   We must be careful that our desire for comity and bipartisanship
does not deter us from considering contentious issues and debating
them vigorously.
   But we must be able to conduct our political battles in an
environment of respect for ourselves, for our opponents and for the
House.
   We cannot allow political differences to become foils for
personal antagonism.
   Let us debate and decide with intensity, even passionate
intensity, but let us debate and decide with respect, not rancor.
   A dozen years ago, Speaker Thomas P. O'Neill stood before the
House prepared to take the oath of office for the first time.
   In his speech, he paraphrased certain principles outlined by the
great Henry Clay that should guide the speaker.
   He promised to be prompt and impartial in deciding parliamentary
questions.
   He pledged to be patient, good-tempered, and courteous toward
individual members.
   He pledged best to employ the talent of the House for full and
fair consideration of issues that come before us.
   He pledged in those ``moments of agitation from which no
deliberative assembly is entirely exempt to remain cool and
unshaken, guarding the permanent laws and rules of the House from
being sacrificed to temporary passions, prejudices or interests.''
   I repeat that pledge to you today.
   You have bestowed upon me a great honor and a great
responsibility.
   I will devote every ability I have to maintaining your confidence
and the integrity of the House of Representatives and to protect the
rights and welfare of all members so that we can fulfill our high
responsibility in representing the people of this nation.
   With God's help, and with your understanding and support, I am
now prepared to take the oath of office.
</TEXT>
