<FIRST>u w AM-GOP-Speaker     06-06 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GOP-Speaker,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Michel Hands Power to Democrats With a Scolding</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-House Leadership Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republican leader Robert Michel on
Tuesday turned a normally ceremonial goodwill gesture toward the
new speaker into a scolding for the majority Democrats.
   Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., was elected speaker to replace Jim
Wright, D-Texas, who resigned rather than continue his battle
against charges that he violated House rules on outside income.
   Michel carried forth the tradition of introducing Foley to the
House, and then took it a step further _ reflecting increasing
frustration and pressure within Republican ranks after more than a
third of a century of Democratic control.
   ``Thirty-five years of uninterrupted power can act like a
corrosive acid upon the restraints of civility and comity,'' said
Michel, whose name was futilely put in nomination by the GOP for
the sixth time.
   The crisis in the House was not the fault of Jim Wright or, as
Wright contended in his resignation speech, to ``mindless
cannibalism,'' Michel said.
   ``It is a catchy phrase. But the distinguished members of the
ethics committee (which charged Wright) ... are neither mindless
nor cannibals,'' he said.
   ``I am all for putting an end to bitterness,'' Michel said. ``I
am all in favor of putting our House in Order. But we don't do so
by sweeping things under the rug.''
   When he finished hammering the Democrats, Michel handed Foley
the gavel.
</TEXT>
