<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Tutu     06-06 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Tutu,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anglican Leader Distressed by Rejection of Women Priests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURBAN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Desmond Tutu said Tuesday
he was anguished by the failure of his fellow Anglican clergymen to
allow women to become priests, and he likened sex discrimination to
apartheid.
   Tutu, the first black to lead the Anglican church in southern
Africa, commented during a meeting of church officials.
   During a vote Saturday, 60 percent of the delegates approved the
ordination of women, but this fell short of the two-thirds majority
needed to change church rules.
   Tutu said Tuesday the outcome had caused him ``very deep anguish
and pain.''
   ``I am very deeply convinced about the rightness of the
ordination of women,'' he said. ``I believe it especially in view of
my own ministry in seeking to work for justice.
   ``I can't see how I can say I oppose apartheid because it refuses
to give access to people because of something they can't change, and
then say no to women.''
   Under apartheid, the white minority government refuses to allow
South Africa's black majority a vote in national affairs and
maintains segregated schools, hospitals and residential areas.
</TEXT>
