<FIRST>r w AM-Crops-Weather     06-06 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crops-Weather,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moisture Uneven, USDA Reports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drenching rains continued to stall field work
in the parts of the nation while additional rain was needed in some
other areas where subsoil moisture is still low, the Agriculture
Department said Tuesday.
   Strong thunderstorms over the weekend brought heavy rains and
flooding to Oklahoma, northeast Texas and northwest Louisiana, where
three to five inches of rain were reported.
   ``Heavy rain also fell on the western Great Plains,'' the
department's 1989 Drought Task Force said in its weekly review.
``Scattered showers over the western Corn Belt brought rainfall of
up to one inch in eastern Nebraska and eastern Kansas.''
   Persistent rain was reported in the eastern Corn Belt, with
amounts of two to four inches in Indiana and Ohio.
   The National Weather Service's 30-day outlook for June calls for
near-normal to above-normal rain throughout the nation except for
below-normal amounts in southern California, the report said.
   In another report, the government's Joint Agricultural Weather
Facility operated by the Agriculture and Commerce departments said
that corn planting nationally was about 93 percent completed by June
4, four percentage points behind normal for the date.
   Planting continued to lag in Indiana, Ohio and Pennsylvania but
was complete or nearly complete in the other major corn states.
   Winter wheat, which suffered greatly from drought in many areas
since it was planted last fall, was reported in ``mostly fair to
poor'' condition. In Kansas, where the crop was hit hard by the dry
weather, winter wheat was turning color and beginning to ripen. In
Texas, the harvest was 8 percent completed, about 15 percentage
points behind normal for this time of the season.
   ``Rain slowed Oklahoma's (wheat) harvest and reduced the quality
of the unharvested crop,'' the report said. ``In Nebraska, Russian
wheat aphids and wheat streak mosaic were continuing problems in the
panhandle.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
