<FIRST>u w AM-Senate-Gregg 1stLd-Writethru a0650 06-06 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Gregg, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0650,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Republicans Boycott Committee Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs first 5 grafs to move up Gregg's name</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans boycotted a Senate Foreign
Relations Committee meeting Tuesday to protest a Democratic-led
probe into the background and truthfulness of Donald Gregg,
President Bush's choice as ambassador to South Korea.
   The investigation's focus is Gregg's possible link to the
Iran-Contra affair. The key questions: Did Gregg assist Oliver L.
North's secret mission to illegally resupply the Nicaraguan Contra
rebels and is he lying about it now?
   Democrats said they may fight the boycott by holding up Bush's
nominations to fill key State Department and diplomatic posts.
   As the new tensions surfaced in a long-simmering dispute, the
absence of GOP members prevented the committee from acting on a
$4.5 billion State Department authorization bill. Also pending was
a $11.5 billion two-year foreign aid authorization measure.
   Gregg, the target of the committee's investigation, served as
Bush's vice presidential national security adviser.
   On Tuesday, eight Democrats gathered to discuss the State
Department bill. The only Republican who showed up was Sen. Jesse
Helms of North Carolina, the panel's ranking GOP member, and he
walked out. A quorum of 10 members is necessary to permit the
committee to act on pending legislation or nominations.
   ``It's very apparent that we are unable to do business, that the
Republicans are objecting to the fact that a legitimate committee
inquiry is taking place into Donald Gregg,'' said Sen. John Kerry,
D-Mass.
   Complaining of ``wholesale boycott,'' Kerry told his Democratic
colleagues: ``I would hope the comity of this institution would not
lead to legitimate business being held up.''
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., who is leading the Gregg
investigation, complained that a lack of cooperation from the
administration is in itself delaying final action on Gregg.
   ``Late last month I sent several letters to administration
officials asking for documents and information relating to Gregg,''
Cranston said. ``I not only have received no material, I have
received no response.''
   Helms said that the boycott is being organized by Sen. Mitch
McConnell, R-Ky., who, Helms said, wants a specific date set for
holding another hearing on Gregg and a specific date for voting on
his nomination.
   ``I don't want anyone suggesting we're holding up anything,''
Helms said. ``We've got a vendetta going on against Mr. Gregg.
That's been clear from the beginning.''
   ``This is an attempt to dredge up Iran-Contra,'' said Helms.
``I'm having a problem on my side because of their discontent over
what Senator Cranston is doing.''
   At that point, Chairman Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., attempted to
move for action on the pending measure.
   Helms stood up.
   ``I'll see you later, Mr. Chairman,'' he said. ``I've got to
defend my side.''
   Helms then walked from the room.
   After huddling with Democratic members, Cranston told reporters
that if Republicans want delay, they are likely to get it.
   ``We may not determine anything for awhile,'' Cranston said.
``This committee may not have any hearings on anything, including
Gregg. ... If this committee can't meet on anything else, maybe the
committee also can't meet on Gregg.''
   The White House and State Department have been urging quick
actions on a nummber of the pending nominations, including those of
Bernard Aronson to be assistant secretary of state for Latin
American affairs and John Kelly to be assistant secretary of Middle
Eastern and South Asian affairs.
   Pell complained that nominations confirmed to date have been
done so with little or no help from Republicans.
   ``We have to carry water for the administration,'' Pell said.
``Their own side is not carrying water.''
</TEXT>
