<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSList-Reax     06-06 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS List-Reax,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>ACLU, Gay Groups Question AIDS List Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposal to collect the names of New Yorkers
infected with the AIDS virus was condemned Tuesday by gay rights
groups and the ACLU as a move that could turn those needing help
away from medical attention.
   ``Our feeling is that anonymity has been the cornerstone of
success in AIDS strategy in New York City. No matter which direction
the epidemic goes, that should not be changed,'' said Clarissa
Cunningham, spokeswoman for the Gay Men's Health Crisis.
   ``If it is, it will drive people underground, away from the
health care that they need.''
   Ms. Cunningham cited statistics from South Carolina as backing
her assertion. After the state required the health department
receive the name of anyone testing positive for the AIDS virus, the
number of tests dropped 50 percent.
   Under the plan proposed Monday by city Health Commissioner Dr.
Stephen Joseph, the city would collect the names of people testing
positive for the virus in order to contact sexual partners or people
who shared needles.
   New York is now one of eight states where anonymous records are
kept of people who test positive.
   Joseph's proposal, made at the Fifth Annual AIDS International
Conference in Montreal, prompted members of the AIDS Coalition to
Unleash Power to disrupt his speech by standing with their backs
toward him and screaming that the commissioner was a liar and
murderer.
   ``You are going to drive us underground!'' ACT UP member Peter
Staley shouted at Joseph during an exchange at the conference.
   While Joseph said he felt confidentiality could be protected,
William Rubenstein of the American Civil Liberties Union said his
group has been opposed to such name-collecting plans since they were
first proposed.
   ``The problem with keeping lists is the potential for
confidentiality violations and possible prejudicial treatment. These
are our civil liberties concerns,'' said Rubenstein.
   Joseph's plan received endorsement Tuesday from City Council
Health Commission Chairman Joseph Lisa, who called the proposal ``an
extremely responsible public health measure.
   ``This will go a significant way to protecting the public,
especially women in the city of New York who are being infected at a
four times greater rate than heterosexual men,'' said Lisa.
</TEXT>
