<FIRST>r a AM-BattleshipDeparture     06-06 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Battleship Departure,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iowa Crewmen Ready To Go To Sea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sailors on the battleship USS Iowa said
Tuesday they are ready to return to sea even though Navy
investigators have not found the cause of a gun turret explosion
that killed 47 crewmen in April.
   ``We'd like to shoot those guns,'' said Rick, a fire control
crewman aboard the battleship. ``It's like falling off that horse.
You've got to get back on it. The longer you wait, the more you're
going to think about it.''
   Lt. Cmdr. Brad Goforth, a ship spokesman, asked that crewmen's
last names not be used because the ship may run into danger during
its cruise to the Mediterranean Sea.
   Rick and seven other Iowa crewmen and spouses took a break from
preparing for a six-month deployment that begins Wednesday to talk
at the Norfolk Naval Station.
   The crewmen and the spouses were in good spirits about the
deployment, the ship's first since the April 19 explosion in gun
turret No. 2 killed 47 crewmen during a training exercise.
   ``The wives that I've spoken with are very supportive of this
deployment, possibly even more so than ordinarily,'' said Becky,
wife of the ship's senior chief.
   ``Deployments are hard ... whether an accident's been involved or
not,'' said Kathy, who stood at a pier beside the ship with her
husband, Michael, a machinist's mate second class.
   Michael, an Iowa crewmen for four years, said the crew's morale
was fairly good.
   ``I've seen it higher but it's not too bad,'' he said. ``We've
got a lot of work to do. We don't have time to sit and mope about
what happened.''
   Along with the usual preparations for six months at sea, the Iowa
crew had to clean and make minor repairs to the No. 2 turret. That
turret must undergo about $13 million worth of repairs, at the
Norfolk Naval Shipyard in Portsmouth after the ship returns, before
its 16-inch guns can be fired, the Navy said.
   The ship's other 16-inch guns also will not be fired until the
Navy completes its investigation of the accident. The Iowa will be
able to use its six five-inch guns and surface-to-surface missiles.
   The No. 2 turret will be used during the cruise to train new
crewmen who replaced the sailors who died in the explosion, Goforth
said.
   The crewmen said they have discussed the various theories about
the explosion that have appeared in the news media, including
reports that one of the turret crewmen may have caused the explosion
to commit suicide.
   ``You're going to have a lot of talk,'' said Doug, a petty
officer 2nd class. It's just something that we just put out of our
minds and we just go about our daily work. But you can't forget and
you've got to wonder yourself, too.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
