<FIRST>u w AM-AssaultWeapons 1stLd-Writethru a0652 06-06 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Assault Weapons, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0652,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Opposing Gun Controls Lobby Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 4th graf pvs, Law Enforcement,' to add National to name
of fraternal group; INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th graf pvs, ``Often you, with
reax from that group's counsel; edits for transition; picks up 7th graf
pvs, Lt. Harry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police chiefs who support gun control do not
represent police in the field, a group of officers from around the
country who oppose limiting access to semiautomatic assault-style
weapons said Tuesday.
   About 225 officers brought to the Capitol by the National Rifle
Association from 49 states _ Hawaii was not represented _ held a
news conference before fanning out to pitch their views to members
of Congress.
   They were here to combat the impact of law enforcement officials
such as Los Angeles Police Chief Daryl Gates and Baltimore County
Police Chief Neil Behan, who are pushing for controls on the
assault-style weapons, including semiautomatic versions of the
AK-47 and Uzi.
   Law enforcement groups that have taken similar stands include
the National Fraternal Order of Police, the International
Association of Chiefs of Police, the National Sheriff's
Association, the National Association of Police Organizations and
the Police Executive Research Forum.
   ``Often you, as news media, hear from the chiefs, the appointed
officials, and they say they speak for us,'' said Patrolman Ray
Maples, president of the Memphis Police Association. ``I'm here
telling you this morning for thousands of us out there that the
chiefs, the appointed officials, do not speak for the law
enforcement officers that are in the field, in the trenches, doing
the job.''
   But Stephen Brown, counsel to the National Fraternal Order of
Police, said his organization represents 200,000 police officers,
not their bosses.
   ``The Fraternal Order of Police does speak for the cop on the
street,'' Brown said. ``There's no chiefs, there's no sheriffs.
They don't speak for anyone except for the cops on the beat.''
   Attending the news conference to express support for the
officers brought in by the NRA were Reps. Larry E. Craig, R-Idaho,
Larkin I. Smith, R-Miss., Harold L. Volkmer, D-Mo., and Ron
Marlenee, R-Mont., as well as Sen. James A. McClure, R-Idaho.
   Lt. Harry Thomas of the Cincinnati Police Department noted that
many of the officers attending were ``under direct orders from
their police chiefs to disassociate themselves from their
respective police departments.''
   ``Some of us are here with our chiefs' blessings, and some of
our chiefs are hoping our planes go down on the way home,'' Thomas
said. ``The remarks that are made here should not be construed as
the official policy of our respective police departments.''
   Officer Leroy Pyle of the San Jose Police Department in
California said it ``offends me'' that some law enforcement leaders
say police are being ``outgunned'' by criminals with assault-style
weapons.
   ``Some of those administrators who are saying that are
repeatedly saying that policemen are afraid, that the policemen are
outgunned, that we're losing. ...We didn't come to this job to
lose, and we don't want anybody saying we're losers,'' he said.
   ``We go out there. We use education, training, tactics and good
common sense. And we win,'' he said.
   The officers said they feared moves to limit access to the
weapons was just the first step toward disarmament of the
population. Thomas noted that in Beijing unarmed demonstrators were
gunned down by army troops.
</TEXT>
