<SECOND>AM-China-Science Academy,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Academy Suspends Exchange With Chinese Academy of Sciences</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Academy of Sciences announced
Tuesday it was suspending a cooperative exchange program with the
Chinese Academy of Sciences.
   Frank Press, the president of the National Academy, said in a
telex message to Chinese Academy of Sciences president Zhou
Guangzhao that Americans ``are shocked and dismayed by the action of
Chinese government troops against peaceful demonstrators.''
   ``While we earnestly hope to maintain our cooperation with your
academy and other Chinese institutions,'' Press wrote, ``we must
suspend all activities for the time being.
   ``We do so in outrage and sadness,'' he concluded.
   The action halts all exchanges between the Chinese Academy and
the National Academy, including a program that involved sending
short-term consultants to Chinese universities.
   The National Academy is a private, non-profit organization of the
nation's most prominent scientists, chartered by Congress to provide
scientific advice to the government.
