<FIRST>r i AM-Khomeini-Will     06-06 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Khomeini-Will,0711</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khomeini's Will Criticizes US, Calls for Islamic Leadership</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Khomeini, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's political
will, read to Iran's parliament, sternly criticized the United
States as a ``vile state terrorist'' and said Iran's leaders must be
concerned with serving Islam and the deprived.
   Khomeini's son Ahmad read excerpts Monday on Tehran radio. On
Tuesday, state television broadcast film of President Ali Khamenei
reading the testament to parliament on Sunday. Khamenei was chosen
Sunday as caretaker leader.
   It was not known whether Khamenei read the entire 29-page
document, which official media said was dated Feb. 15, 1983, with
another page added in 1987. They did not say what was contained in
the extra page.
   Those parts of the will made public said nothing of who should
govern Iran but contained general observations on how to choose the
leaders.
   ``My will to the leadership is that they should occupy themselves
with serving Islam, the Islamic republic, the oppressed and the
deprived,'' Khamenei read.
   ``They should not think that leadership is an egotistical gift.
... It is a heavy, dangerous responsibility. If the experts in
choosing a leadership council or leader consult with prominent
theologians and independent scholars, many problems ... will not
arise.''
   There has been speculation that, in the absence of a single
political figure of Khomeini's stature, Iran may be ruled by a
collective leadership.
   The testament said the president and members of the parliament
should come ``from a class that has felt the deprivation of the
oppressed and will work to better their conditions,'' not from ``the
well-off capitalists and landlords, drowned in pleasures and
excesses.''
   Earlier, official media carried these excerpts:
   ``I have done my duty, which is to give guidance. My hope is that
you will listen to this advice, which will reach you after my death
and is unstained by the desire for power, and save yourself from
God's wrath.
   ``There should be no doubt that the Islamic revolution of Iran is
separate from all other revolutions, in the quality of its struggle
and in its motives.
   ``I have not said and I will not say that today, in this
republic, the great Islam and all its aspects are being implemented
and that ignorant and disorderly individuals are not committing acts
against Islamic laws.
   ``But what I do say is that the legislative, judicial and
executive branches are trying and will try to do a great deal to
make the country Islamic.''
   It is ``better to be wiped out honorably from the face of history
by the hands of criminal Americans and Soviets ... than to have a
super-comfortable life under the red flag of the East and the black
flag of the West,'' Khomeini declared.
   He said Iran had no greater source of pride ``than the fact that
the U.S. with all its huge military arsenal and string of puppet
regimes and the international mass media at its service, has been so
disgraced and humbled against Iran that it does not know to whom it
should resort.''
   Khmomeini said Iran should guard against ``the conspiracies and
plots of the enemies towards the Islamic Republic. In the forefront
of these is America, this vile state terrorist, which has set fire
to the whole world, and its ally the global Zionist (Israel), which
to attain its goals commits such crimes that pens are ashamed to
document and tongues are ashamed to recite.''
   Of Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, his foe in an eight-year war,
and some Arab leaders who supported Iraq, he said:
   ``We are proud that our enemy is Saddam, whom friends and foes
alike recognize as criminal, and violator of international and human
rights. And everyone knows that his treachery to the nation of Iraq,
and the gulf sheikdoms, is not less than his treachery to the
Iranian nation.
   ``The Islamic countries and the oppressed of the world are proud
that their enemies are this Jordanian Hussein the carpetbagger and
Hassan and Hosni Mubarak are followers of Israel the criminal.''
   His references were to the kings of Jordan and Morocco and the
president of Egypt.
</TEXT>
