<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Soviets     06-06 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Soviets,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Offers U.S. Burn Specialists for Soviet Pipeline Explosion Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush visited the Soviet Embassy on
Tuesday to express sympathy for victims of the deadly gas explosion
along the Trans-Siberian Railway and to offer a team of U.S. burn
specialists.
   Bush told Soviet Ambassador Yuri Dubinin that the United States
could send a team of 14 doctors from the Brooke Army Hospital at
Fort Sam Houston in San Antonio, Texas, one of the nation's most
respected burn centers.
   ``I just want you to know it's available... They could be ready
to go immediately,'' Bush told Dubinin. The ambassador thanked Bush
for the ``generous offer'' and said he would relay it at once to
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``You've had more than your share of terrible luck,'' Bush told
Dubinin, mentioning both the freak weekend gas explosion in the Ural
mountains and the devastating earthquake earlier this year in Soviet
Armenia.
   At least 190 people died, 762 were hospitalized and another 250
were missing in the Sunday incident in which two passenger trains
were engulfed by a wall of fire from a ruptured gas pipeline,
according to Tass, the Soviet news agency.
   Bush told Dubinin that the Soviets could take or decline the team
of burn specialists as they wished. ``This is an offer and it may or
may not be something you would want to accept in the final
analysis,'' Bush said.
   He said he knew the Soviet Union had its own burn specialists,
but he said the Fort Sam Houston unit was ``an outstanding burn
center.''
   Bush said the offer included bringing ``some worst cases _ if it
fits your requirements _ to San Antonio.''
   Bush sat at a table covered with red cloth and bordered by black
ribbons in an upstairs room at the embassy,. With Dubinin looking
on, he wrote in the guest book: ``With sympathy _ please convey our
most sincere condolences. George Bush. 6 June 89.''
   Bush and National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft also looked at
an exhibit of photographs from the gas explosion.
   Before heading back to the White House, Bush met privately with
Dubinin for about 10 minutes.
</TEXT>
