<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1944EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Merrimac     06-06 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Merrimac,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hydroelectic Plant Afloat, Headed Upriver</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NU2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's largest prefabricated power plant
began a slow journey Tuesday under tow up the Mississippi River, the
same body of water that it eventually will use to generate
electricity.
   Cables groaned when two tugboats in front pulled and two tugs in
back pushed the massive power plant, the Merrimac, off a dry dock at
a suburban New Orleans shipyard to begin its 208-mile journey
upriver.
   ``I feel real good. I've been working on this thing for 13 years.
We started literally from scratch,'' said Sidney Murray of
Catalyst-Old River Hydroelectric Ltd., one of the investors. ``It's
been exciting for everybody.''
   Murray videotaped the 12-story beige structure as it edged away
from its dock. About 75 spectators cheered from the dock.
   The power plant is 12 stories high, 456 feet long and weighs
about 25,000 tons. Company officials said that although the Merrimac
is smaller than some of the world's largest ships, it is believed to
be the largest structure to ever travel up the Mississippi River.
   The Merrimac is headed for a point 40 miles south of Vidalia,
where it will be fitted for operation in a channel where water will
run from the Mississippi River through the power plant turbines and
into the Atchafalaya River.
   Louisiana's first hydroelectric plant should be fully operational
by July 1, 1990, said Bill Fox of Ebasco, an engineering firm that
worked on the $500 million project.
   The Merrimac will creep upriver at 2 to 4 mph and should arrive
in northeast Louisiana over the weekend, he said.
   ``This is a major milestone,'' Fox said. ``It's been thought out
extremely well. Saving anything less than a hurricane, we ought to
be able to bring it in without any trouble.''
   The major obstacle is already anticipated _ the U.S. Highway 190
bridge at Baton Rouge. The bridge is too low for the tall structure,
so the plant must be partially submerged while it passes underneath.
   The Merrimac will probably be sunk 40 to 50 feet to leave a
clearance of at least five feet between the top of the plant and the
bottom of the bridge.
   The 10- to 20-hour process will be done by pumping water into
large hollow compartments that enable the structure to float. After
the plant clears the bridge, the water will be pumped out and the
Merrimac will resume its journey.
   Once in place near the Old River Control Structure, the Merrimac
will divert water from the Mississippi River through eight giant
turbines. The water will then flow through a two-mile-long channel
into the Atchafalaya River, a 17-foot drop.
   The plant is designed to generate 192 megawatts of electricity,
enough to light a city of 200,000 people.
   Owners of the power plant are the Merrimac Corp. of New York and
Dominion Capital Inc. of Virginia. The town of Vidalia shared
licensing for the project.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890606-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1945EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     06-06 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanon's Shiite Factions Pledge Allegiance to Khamenei</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Khomeini Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanon's two main Shiite Moslem factions
issued statements Tuesday endorsing President Ali Khamenei of Iran,
who was chosen as caretaker leader after the death of Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini.
   New shelling began after nightfall in the 3-month-old artillery
war between Christian army units and a a Moslem alliance of Syrian
troops and Druse militiamen. No casualties were reported.
   ``We declare obedience to Ayatollah Ali Khamenei and swear
absolute commitment to his teachings and orders,'' said a statement
issued by the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God. Hezbollah is
the umbrella group for militant Shiites believed to be holding some
of the 18 foreigners missing in Lebanon.
   The rival Amal faction, a more moderate group backed by Syria,
said it ``supports and blesses the Islamic Republic in its correct
selection of the great successor Ayatollah Ali Khamenei.''
   Khamenei is only a middle-ranking cleric, but is being called
``ayatollah'' since his choice by the Assembly of Experts
established by Khomeini to handle the succession.
   Shiites mourned Khomeini for a third day with a general strike in
west Beirut and other Moslem areas of Lebanon. Khomeini, 86, died of
a heart attack Saturday, 11 days after intestinal surgery.
   Black flags and photo posters of the bearded, black-turbaned
revolutionary patriarch dangled from buildings and mosques in Moslem
west Beirut, the southern slums and Shiite towns in south Lebanon
and the Bekaa Valley.
   Mourners marched to the Iranian Embassy in the seaside Ouzai
suburb and Shiite religious centers in other cities to deliver
condolences.
   ``Death to America, the great Satan,'' read a banner carried by
about 200 mourners in the southern port of Tyre.
   A dozen youths in the Bir el-Abed slum beat their chests and
shaved their heads as worshippers entered the district's mosque for
a memorial service.
   The Lebanese Broadcasting Corp., run by rightist Christian
militias, broadcast Khomeini's funeral live. Cars equipped with
loudspeakers toured the streets in west Beirut and Tyre urging
businesses to close, and most complied.
   ``Close! Close!'' a bearded man shouted from a white Peugeot that
drove across west Beirut's Hamra commercial street flying the
Iranian flag and blaring verses of the Koran.
   ``Sure, sure,'' a grocer replied as he lowered his shutter.
   The car drove away and the grocer murmured: ``Last year it was a
strike to mark the Israeli invasion's anniversary. I wonder whether
we'll be alive next June 6 to observe a strike for any reason.''
   Israel withdrew most of its army from Lebanon in June 1985,
ending three years of invasion and occupation of the south. With the
aid of a surrogate militia, it maintains a ``security zone'' just
inside south Lebanon that ranges in depth from 6 to 10 miles.
   Palestinian guerrilla factions marked the anniversary by issuing
statements condemning Israel.
   Police said nine people were wounded in overnight artillery
exchanges, raising total casualties to 363 killed and 1,430 wounded
since the artillery duels began March 8.
</TEXT>
