<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-D-Day     06-06 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-D-Day,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Marks 45th Anniversary of Invasion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-D-Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Tuesday marked the 45th
anniversary of the Normandy invasion and called for redoubled
efforts to help spread democracy around the globe.
   Bush, in a statement on the anniversary of D-Day, linked the
current stuggle in China and the Allied invasion that hastened the
liberation of Europe in 1945.
   ``The turmoil and confusion of battle that day belied the calm
purposefulness with which freedom confronts tyranny,'' the president
said.
   ``In recent days, the face of the world has again been marked by
dramatic occurrences _ winds of change _ that signify the
determination with which freedom confounds its adversaries,'' he
said.
   He recalled that on the morning of June 6, 1944, Gen. Dwight D.
Eisenhower ``carried in his pocket a draft message declaring the
invasion to have been a failure and taking personal responsibility
for that failure.''
   ``He never needed to use that draft, of course,'' he added.
   ``As with Gen. Eisenhower then, we cannot know with certainty
today whether the forces of freedom will prevail soon or in every
instance,'' Bush said. ``Yet the ultimate victory of freedom and
democracy is inevitable.''
   He said last week's successful NATO summit, as well as ``the
first free elections in Poland in more than 50 years and even the
momentous, tragic events in China give us reason to redouble our
efforts to continue the spread of freedom and democracy around the
globe.''
</TEXT>
