<FIRST>u w AM-HouseLeadership 4thLd-Writethru a0733 06-06 0981</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House Leadership, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0733,980</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foley Takes Gavel as Speaker, Replacing Wright</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Waxman out of whip race, subbing last graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House of Representatives elevated Thomas S.
Foley of Washington to be the 49th speaker in its history Tuesday,
and he immediately appealed to both parties to ``put away
bitterness'' after months of turmoil that led to the forced
resignation of Speaker Jim Wright.
   Foley promised to help return tranquility to a House that has
been ripped by charges and counter-charges of ethical impropriety,
and to put ethics reform on his list of priorities for the year.
   ``I am a proud Democrat,'' Foley declared to the full House after
he was elected and sworn in. He appealed to Republicans as well as
his own party to ``come together and put away bitterness and
division and hostility.''
   ``We need to debate public issues vigorously, even passionately.
But we need to debate and decide with reason and without rancor,''
he said.
   Foley was elected on a party-line vote of 251 to 164, defeating
Republican Leader Robert H. Michel of Illinois. The vote, in a
crowded House chamber, marked the first time a party has changed
speakers in the middle of a congressional term because of a
controversy over ethics.
   Michel, in his concession speech, said, ``I'm all for putting an
end to bitterness. I'm all for putting our House in order. But we
don't do it by sweeping things under the rug.''
   In a final shot at Wright, Michel said members of the ethics
committee who had investigated him were ``neither mindless nor
cannibals'' _ a reference to Wright's call last week for the House
to end the ``mindless cannibalism'' he saw around him.
   Foley preached conciliation all day.
   In one session with reporters, he refused to rise to the bait as
he was asked repeatedly about GOP criticism of him by the Republican
National Committee, which is led by President Bush's former campaign
manager Lee Atwater.
   Foley said he would not get into ``debating matters with Mr.
Atwater. I want to put this House ... and the Congress squarely back
on a track of dealing with the issues that the country elected the
Congress to resolve with the president.''
   He commented after joining other congressional leaders at a White
House meeting on environmental legislation _ and after Bush
congratulated him on his new position.
   ``President Bush is the president of the United States, and every
way that I can work cooperatively with him, and my colleagues in the
Congress, I want to do so,'' Foley said.
   Wright, who turned the gavel over to his successor, praised him
before the House session as a man who could turn the chamber's
attention from backbiting to lawmaking.
   ``My great hope is that the House can return to its most
important business of legislating,'' Wright said, adding that
``vigilantism ... just begets more bad will.''
   Aides in Wright's office packed files and mementoes into boxes,
and workmen hauled them off. Wright spent the afternoon in his
office as Foley and other congressional leaders went to the White
House.
   At a news conference after he returned, Foley said he was asking
two bipartisan House task forces, one on ethics and the other on
campaign reform, to make their recommendations as soon as possible
so legislation could be considered ``in this Congress, this year.''
A ban on congressional speaking fees, linked with a federal pay
raise phased in over several years, could be a possibility, he said.
   Foley, the party's majority leader for the past 2{ years, had
been nominated unanimously by Democrats.
   Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., who also is resigning from the House
because of ethics charges, called Foley ``a man for all seasons _ a
man uniquely suited for this season.''
   ``There is a steadfastness, an inner serenity to this man,'' said
Rep. Louise Slaughter, D-N.Y., who also made a nominating speech for
Foley in the caucus meeting.
   But Democrats were having a hard time forgetting the relentless
assault led by Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., that led to the fall of
Wright. Gingrich, now the House GOP whip, formally filed charges
against the Texas Democrat last year, triggering a year-long ethics
committee probe that cost more than $1.5 million and led to
allegations Wright violated House rules 69 times.
   Wright fought the charges for months, but announced last week
that he would resign not only the speakership but also his
congressional seat.
   Of the ethics commttee and Gingrich, who himself faces ethics
allegations over a book-promotion deal, Slaughter said: ``I want
them to treat him fairly, but I certainly want them to treat him.''
   Republicans on Tuesday circulated lapel buttons that said,
``Reform, not Revenge.''
   ``What you have is the schoolyard bully who's afraid of getting
punched back,'' said Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass.
   The Republican political machine, under the leadership of Atwater
at the Republican National Committee and Edward Rollins at the
National Republican Congressional Committee, has taken on a harder
partisan edge and has plans to exploit the ethics issue.
   One GOP political source, who spoke only on condition of
anonymity, said the campaign arm is sifting through Democrats'
financial disclosure forms looking for mistakes they can capitalize
on.
   The Democrats are expected to select a replacement for Foley as
majority leader next week. Richard Gephardt of Missouri, who ran
unsuccessfully last year for the Democratic presidential nomination,
is considered the favorite over Ed Jenkins of Georgia.
   The whip's race to replace Coelho is a contest among three
already powerful House Democrats: William H. Gray III of
Pennsylvania, the chairman of the House Democratic Caucus; David
Bonior of Michigan, the chief deputy whip, and Beryl Anthony of
Arkansas, chairman of the Democratic Congressional Campaign
Committee. A fourth potential candidate, Henry Waxman of California,
said Tuesday he would not seek the post.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
