<FIRST>u w AM-DemocraticLeaders 1stLd-Writethru a0628 06-06 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democratic Leaders, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0628,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats to Fill Other Top House Posts Next Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-House Leadership, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th graf pvs, So both, to show caucus now scheduled for
Wednesday. Subs graf 8, Four already-powerful, and graf 11, Gray's opponents,
with Waxman dropping from whip's race.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The promotion of Democratic Rep. Thomas S.
Foley to speaker of the House leaves other leadership gaps his party
hopes to fill quickly.
   Foley, D-Wash., who had held the post of majority leader,
succeeded Jim Wright Tuesday, six days after Wright announced he
would step down because of charges that he violated House rules on
outside income.
   But the next in line for Foley's No. 2 post, Democratic Whip Tony
Coelho, D-Calif., also is resigning _ rather than face an ethics
inquiry like the one that ended Wright's career.
   So both the No. 2 and No. 3 Democratic slots in the House need
filling. With Democrats eager to put the ethics episode behind them
and limit any political damage, a party caucus has been scheduled
for next Wednesday on those races.
   Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri is widely considered the
favorite to succeed Foley as majority leader. Gephardt, who ran
unsuccessfully for the Democratic presidential nomination last year,
is considered a strong spokesman for the party without any potential
ethics issues in his background.
   Opposing him is Rep. Ed Jenkins of Georgia, one of the more
conservative Democrats. Jenkins, like Gephardt, is a popular member
of the Ways and Means Committee, and he enjoys the backing of that
panel's chairman, Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill.
   ``It's a good competition without acrimony,'' Gephardt said
Tuesday.
   The race for the title of majority whip narrowed to three
already-powerful Democrats on Tuesday when Rep. Henry Waxman,
D-Calif., announced that he would not be a candidate.
   Rep. William H. Gray III of Pennsylvania, currently chairman of
the House Democratic Caucus, is considered the front-runner.
   However, he's been battling published reports that the Justice
Department is conducting a preliminary investigation of his
personnel practices including an allegation about a no-show
employee. He has denied any wrongdoing and has questioned the timing
of leaks that occurred just as he was running for whip.
   Gray's remaining opponents in the race are Reps. David Bonior of
Michigan, the chief deputy whip, and Beryl Anthony of Arkansas, the
chairman of the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee.
   If Gray wins, his caucus chairmanship will be vacant. Two
lawmakers, Steny Hoyer of Maryland and Barbara Kennelly of
Connecticut, have announced they would like to succeed Gray.
   The death last week of Rep. Claude Pepper, D-Fla., also made
vacant the powerful post of chairman of the Rules Committee. A
Democratic caucus was scheduled for Wednesday to put Rep. Joe
Moakley of Massachusetts in that position.
   Coelho has announced he will leave the House on June 15, and
Wright also has said he will give up his Texas seat this month. With
Pepper's death, three House seats long held by Democrats will be up
for election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
