<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1850EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-EthnicDisputes 1stLd-Writethru a0651 06-06 0703</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Ethnic Disputes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0651,0721</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Debate With Ethnic Unrest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Riots, Bjt ^Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to RECAST, edit,
DELETE references to dissident and to Nagorno-Karabakh as ``predominantly
Azerbaijani''; picks up 10th, `On April 9...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent Soviet writer said during parliamentary
debate Tuesday on nationalist unrest that soldiers covered up ethnic
violence three years ago in Kazakhstan.
   The debate in the Congress of People's Deputies took place at a
time of more ethnic troubles, this time in the Central Asian
republic Uzbekistan. At least 50 people were reported killed over
the weekend.
   Writer Mukhtar Sakhanov said a letter from intellectuals in
Kazakhstan charged that soldiers used dogs and shovels to disperse
protesters and that the number of deaths has been kept secret.
   That protest was the first in a long series of ethnic
disturbances under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of
greater openness and social and economic reform.
   Sakhanov summarized the letter, then turned it over to Gorbachev
during Tuesday's session.
   It said the number of deaths in rioting in the republic's
capital, Alma Ata, was greater than the 32 killed last year during
violence last year between ethnic Armenians and Azerbaijanis.
   ``According to incomplete data, about 3,000 people were arrested,
hundreds of them were sentenced to long prison terms, thousands were
excluded from schools or fired from work,'' said the letter written
by seven Kazakh intellectuals. Copies were circulated in Moscow by
Kazakh activists.
   The violence in Sumgait, the Azerbaijani capital, was caused by a
dispute over Nagorno-Karabakh, an enclave in Azerbaijan whose
population is predominantly Armenian. The territory was assigned to
Azerbaijan in 1923, but Armenia wants to annex it.
   On April 9, troops battled pro-independence demonstrators in
Tbilisi, the capital of the Georgian republic, and at least 20
demonstrators were killed. The use of shovels and a debilitating gas
by soldiers who broke up that protests has caused national outcry.
   The Baltic republics of Lithuania, Estonia and Latvia also have
been beds of unrest as activists press for more autonomy.
   Official reports have said that only a couple of people were
killed in the Kazakh rioting, which broke out after the republic's
Communist Party chief Dinmukhamed Kunaev, an ethnic Kazakh, was
replaced by Russian Gennady Kolbin.
   The letter demanded a legislative commission be formed to
investigate the rioting.
   Also Tuesday, Russian writer Valentin Rasputin characterized the
dominant Russian population as a victim rather than master of the
vast Soviet bureaucracy.
   Ethnic minorities blame centralized control on domination by
Russians in Moscow, but Rasputin, of the Siberian city Irkutsk, said
the system had ``plundered Russia to such an extent that it is just
on this side of survival.''
   He complained that when Russians begin talking of their own
national culture and traditions, they immediately make other ethnic
groups wary.
   Members of the newly formed Soviet of Nationalities, the house of
the Supreme Soviet legislature that is assigned to deal with ethnic
questions, also met Tuesday and debated the ethnic unrest issue.
   It named the Communist Party chief of Uzbekistan, Rafik Nishanov,
as their chairman after questioning him about the violence in his
republic.
   Of 252 deputies present, five voted against Nishanov and 11
abstained.
   Gorbachev, presiding over the chamber, said the tone of some of
the debate ``leads to concern,'' but that he was satisfied with it.
   ``I'm very pleased because of the informal character of
discussion,'' he said. He said the house cannot duck hard questions.
``This is the people's life and we have to approach it seriously,''
Gorbachev said.
   The Soviet of Nationalities met after a morning session of the
2,250-member Congress.
   Lithuanian deputies demanded veto power over selection of the
chairman of the Soviet of Nationalities. When the house refused to
go along a deputy who did not identify himself raised the
possibility of Lithuanian secession.
   ``This is a constitutional right, and I do not want my native
Lithuania to be in such a bad union if it goes like this,'' he said.
   Deputy Vladimir Yarovoi complained to the Congress that Estonian
officials were discriminating against others. Reform in Estonia is
``a one-way street where there is no place for Russians,'' he said.
</TEXT>
