<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 2002EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     06-06 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHNSON CITY, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wilbur the pig and Bilbo the hobbit
have a lot to teach grade-schoolers if only more educators and
parents would stop being afraid of fantasy literature, a professor
said Tuesday.
   Reading aloud in the classroom has grown more popular in the last
15 or 20 years, but such books as ``Charlotte's Web'' and ``The
Hobbit'' remain on the outskirts of structured curricula, Dr.
Roberta Herrin said.
   Herrin teaches fantasy literature at East Tennessee State
University and is helping coordinate a workshop next week for
teachers and librarians on the use of often-classic fantasy tales.
   The importance of self-esteem is explained through the
experiences of Wilbur in ``Charlotte's Web,'' Ms. Herrin said.
Charlotte, a spider, befriends the self-pitying pig and encourages
him to stand on his own four feet.
   Bilbo Baggins in ``The Hobbit'' finds his true identity after he
accepts a challenge from the wizard Gandalf.
   Students are more apt to learn the importance of such traits in
the framework of fantasy, Ms. Herrin said.
   ``You start with a narrative, a story, that engages their
interest and move from that to the very practical and concrete
applications,'' she said. ``That's very different than coming in and
saying, `Today we're going to study geography.'''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON, D.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After failing to sell his Potomac, Md.,
home for several months, former Sen. Birch Bayh, D-Ind., is taking a
different approach.
   The home was listed in a classified ad in Sunday's Washington
Post this way:
   ``Senator and Mrs. Bayh have slashed the price of their Potomac
home to way below market. They haven't been so beaten down since Dan
Quayle did it to 'em in 1980.''
   Quayle, now vice president, ended Bayh's Senate career during the
Reagan landslide of 1980.
   Bayh and his wife, Kitty, are selling their suburban home to move
back into Washington, he said.
   ``We decided we would try this to get people's attention.''
</TEXT>
