<FIRST>u w AM-Foley-Notebook     06-06 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foley-Notebook,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>From Reagan To Alice, A Day In The Life Of Tom Foley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Random observations from the day Tom Foley
became speaker of the House of Representatives:
   
   A CALL FROM REAGAN: The first telephone call Foley received upon
returning to his office just moments after being sworn in was from
former President Reagan. Foley took the call in private, but said
later Reagan called to ``send his best wishes. It was a very
generous and kind thing to do.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE LOYAL OPPOSITION: The three Republican members of the
Washington state congressional delegation have all expressed their
admiration for Foley any number of times, but when it came time to
vote for him they followed the party line and voted for Republican
Leader Bob Michel of Illinois. However, Reps. John Miller, Rod
Chandler and Sid Morrison joined with the Democratic members of the
delegation to escort Foley to the speaker's rostrum after the vote.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   A PUBLIC MOMENT FOR A PRIVATE LADY: Foley's wife, Heather, has
always avoided the public spotlight, but when Foley introduced her
during his speech the House gave her a standing ovation. Sitting
with her in the gallery were author Kitty Kelley, a longtime friend,
and Pamela Harriman, the grand dame of the Democratic Party.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   FOR THE RECORD: Foley voted present when his name was called
during the voting for speaker. The only other ``present'' vote was
cast by Michel.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   FINALLY A SMILE: Foley would have preferred becoming speaker
under different circumstances and as he left his office for the
Democratic caucus he said he felt ``more a sense of somber
responsibility than excitement.'' As he sat on floor while the roll
was called, he had a serious look on his face. He finally broke into
a smile when Jim Wright handed him the gavel after the election.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   APPLAUSE FROM BEHIND CLOSED DOORS: Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash., said
the loudest applause during the Democratic caucus came during
California Rep. Tony Coelho's seconding speech of Foley's
nomination. According to Dicks, Coelho said ``They (the Republicans)
are the party of Newt Gringrich. We are the party of Tom Foley.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   AUTHOR PLEASE: When Minority Leader Michel introduced Foley, he
took note of Foley's western roots. Michel said, ``Tom Foley coming
from the Great Pacific Northwest reminds me of the line of poetry
that says: `But Westward look, the land is bright.'''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WHERE WERE THE WASHINGTON WINES? Foley hosted a reception in his
office for close friends and current and former staff after becoming
speaker. Though Washington state produces some good white wine, the
white wine was from France and California.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   DEPARTING FROM THE TEXT: On only rare ocassions does Foley speak
from a prepared text. His best speeches are usually from general
talking points or are extemporaneous. Foley spent time during the
morning working on his acceptance speech, but when he delivered it
he followed it only in part. ``He followed it only vaguely,'' said
one staffer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WHO IS THIS MAN? Foley was asked at his first formal news
conference to introduce himself to the American public. ``I'm 60
years of age, 6-foot-4 and reportedly weigh 240 pounds, though I
hope to make that less,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   A DOG'S LIFE: Foley's dog Alice has attracted a lot of attention
over the past week, with some photographers more interested in
taking pictures of her than the speaker. But Foley has bad news
about her: ``Alice may not be with us much longer,'' he said.
``She's going on 17 years old, is totally deaf and it takes 12 hours
of sleep to get her going in the morning.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
