<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Israel     06-06 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Israel,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israelis and Allied Militiamen Attack Hezbollah Bases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HASBAYA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An armored force of Israeli soldiers and
allied militiamen left Israel's ``security zone'' in south Lebanon
on Tuesday to attack bases of the pro-Iranian Hezbollah militia in
the western Bekaa Valley.
   Police said two Israeli helicopter gunships supported a two-hour
assault on two Hezbollah bases.
   The attackers moved behind repeated strafing runs by Cobra
gunships into Berket Jaber village on the zone's northern edge, then
struck at Maydoun village six miles further north, the police
reported.
   In Jerusalem, the army said Israeli soldiers killed two
guerrillas and ``there were no wounded among our forces.'' It gave
the location as north of the zone near the village of Houne.
   Lebanese police said helicopter strafing runs started brush fires
that set some houses ablaze. A spokesman gave the casualties count
as one Hezbollah fighter wounded.
   Voice of the South, the radio station of the South Lebanon Army
militia, said the raiders seized arms, arms, ammunition and
explosives.
   Earlier Tuesday, an armored personnel carrier of the
Israeli-sponsored militia hit a land mine near Qantarah, two miles
northwest of the zone. The radio reported two militiamen wounded.
   Israel established the border zone, which varies in depth from
six to 10 miles, in 1985 after withdrawing from a three-year
invasion and occupation of south Lebanon. It keeps about 1,000
soldiers in the zone and the predominantly Christian militia has
2,500 men.
</TEXT>
