<FIRST>r i AM-Ethiopia-Coup     06-06 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethiopia-Coup,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Says 28 Rebel Commanders Died in Coup Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mengistu Haile Mariam said
Tuesday nearly 30 senior officers who tried to overthrow his Marxist
government three weeks ago were killed or committed suicide.
   Mengistu told his first news conference since the coup attempt
that two generals took their own lives in Addis Ababa on May 16, the
first day of the rebellion, and loyal soldiers killed 11 generals
and 15 senior officers three days later in Asmara, capital of
Eritrea province.
   He said 24 generals and 150 officers had been arrested and the
investigation was continuing. He said involvement of a foreign power
had ``not been established.''
   Maj. Gen. Haile Ghiorgis Habte Mariam, the defense minister, was
the only loyalist killed and two soldiers were wounded, Mengistu
said.
   ``There was not a single civilian casualty, and no property was
damaged in the capital or Asmara,'' he told the journalists.
   The rebellion began when the president left the country for a
visit to East Germany. Loyal soldiers quickly crushed the revolt in
Addis Ababa, but the 2nd Army held out in Eritrea for three days.
   Mengistu quickly returned home to face the most serious crisis of
his 12 years as head of the government established when he and a
group of other army officers overthrew Emperor Haile Selassie in
1974.
</TEXT>
