<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1914EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-China-USReaction     06-06 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-US Reaction,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anger, Fear Spur Trip Cancellations, Business Pullouts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China Network, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Protest banners and tour cancellations Tuesday dramatized
American dismay at the crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators in
China, as politicians and businesses weighed the costs of
disengaging from the world's most populous country.
   Anguished Chinese-Americans and others sympathizing with the
student protesters in Beijing continued to find ways to express
their anger at the bloodshed in Tiananmen Square on Sunday.
   Hundreds of Chinese and American protesters filled the steps of
the South Carolina Statehouse in Columbia holding banners that read,
``Trial for the butchers of Beijing'' and ``Our fallen heroes are
immortal.''
   University of California scholars in Irvine imposed an
educational boycott against the Chinese government, canceling trips
to Beijing.
   Maxwell Fry, an economics professor who was to have advised the
Chinese government on fighting inflation, said, ``I am not willing
to exchange views with them on the economy under the current
circumstances.''
   Twelve Indiana legislators and three businessmen canceled a trip
to promote trade and industrial cooperation between the state and
its sister province in China.
   Jackie Hughes, a native of Taiwan who owns a Gainesville, Ga.,
boutique, put a white ribbon outside her business and said she hopes
the practice catches on.
   The pro-democracy movement has used blue ribbons and headbands,
but Gainesville restaurant owner John Liang said white represents
peace in China and is the traditional Chinese color of mourning.
   Luming Zhao, one of 15 Chinese exchange students who have handed
out hundreds of black armbands at Central Washington University in
Ellensburg, said he had told a television reporter last week that
the military would not use force.
   ``I realize now I was naive. An army shooting at the people _ I
just can't believe it,'' said Zhao, 31, a graduate student from near
Shanghai.
   Another native of China said the violence unearthed buried
feelings.
   ``I thought I'd totally settled here and adopted it as my country
with China as my motherland,'' said Calvin Chien, 47, a senior
consultant in the Du Pont Co. engineering department in Wilmington,
Del. After the Beijing confrontation, he said, ``all of a sudden I
woke up. I have a much deeper tie to China.''
   With China facing the threat of civil war, the State Department
urged Americans in Beijing to leave.
   The only U.S. commercial airline serving the Chinese capital,
United Airlines, reported that its Monday flight took just five
people in, but had 307 flying out, to Tokyo. Figures for Tuesday's
flight will be available Wednesday, spokesman Joe Hopkins said in
Chicago.
   Hopkins said United had no plans to increase flights to the
Chinese capital, but had shortened turnaround times to ensure jets
arrive and depart during daylight.
   Northwest Airlines has changed its twice-weekly flight to
Shanghai to avoid leaving planes there overnight, and Thursday's
flight is fully booked, spokesman Bob Gibbons said. ``A much smaller
load is going into Shanghai than coming out,'' he said.
   Douglas Aircraft Co. chartered a plane to withdraw its 51 people
from Shanghai and two other cities. Of the hundreds of American
companies that have invested at least $3.5 billion in China since
relations were normalized, many withdrew employees from Beijing but
fewer left sites more remote from the violence.
   In Albany, New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, insisting he ``wouldn't
second guess'' President Bush's suspension of military sales to
China, expressed concern that the state's businesses might suffer.
   Cuomo, a Democrat, said he would ``call upon our congressional
delegation ... to be very vigilant about making sure that if there
are cutbacks, they not affect us inordinately.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
