<FIRST>r w AM-US-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0727 06-06 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0727,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Pleased with Solidarity Electoral Strength</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs with Bush reaction; picks up 6th graf pvs,
A State</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Tuesday hailed the election
results in Poland as ``an important step toward freedom and
democracy.''
   ``The Polish people face a difficult task ahead, but their first
steps have been firmly in the right direction,'' Bush said in a
brief statement.
   Solidarity candidates won a decisive majority in the new
100-member Polish Senate and virtually all of the 161 seats
available to the opposition in the 460-seat legislative Sejm,
according to unofficial results of Sunday's balloting.
   Bush applauded the results and said, ``I am encouraged by the
responses of both the Polish government and members of the
opposition.''
   ``The Polish people are now taking steps that deserve our active
support. We will work in concert with our allies to help Polish
democracy take root anew and sustain itself,'' Bush said.
   The State Department also applauded the outcome, departing from
its normal policy of not taking sides in foreign elections by
calling the results ``victory for all Poles.''
   The United States normally expresses support for electoral
processes in foreign countries without taking sides among competing
parties.
   While praising the concession statement by Poland's Communist
Party, State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said Tuesday,
``The U.S. regards Solidarity's apparent victory as a victory for
all Poles.''
   A State Department official, insisting on anonymity, admitted the
official position prepared for the daily press briefing was not
properly phrased.
   ``We had no intention of taking sides,'' the official said. ``We
should have tightened up the language.''
   The official said he did not believe a retraction would be issued
since only one reporter had asked about the statement.
   Another official expressed no misgivings about the statement,
saying, ``We feel Solidarity better represents the people of Poland
than the other fellows (the communists).''
</TEXT>
