<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-06 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Severe Thunderstorms Hit Texas, Oklahoma, Florida</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe thunderstorms pelted northwest Oklahoma with hail Tuesday
and a tornado in Florida skipped through Clearwater, felling trees,
downing power lines and tearing shingles from rooftops.
   The thunderstorms moved eastward through western Texas Tuesday
afternoon.
   A flash flood watch was posted for extreme southern Oklahoma on
Tuesday night and into Wednesday for north-central and northeast
Texas, including the Dallas-Fort Worth area.
   Rain and thunderstorms were widespread across the south Atlantic
Coast and into portions of the central Gulf Coast.
   The tornado in Clearwater, on Florida's central Gulf coast,
snapped a palm tree in front of a school filled with youngsters and
ripped an awning from a minor-league baseball field, but no injuries
were reported.
   Nearly an inch of rain fell on Wilmington, N.C., in one hour
Tuesday morning. In the southern Appalachians, an inch and a quarter
fell within two hours in Bell County in southeast Kentucky.
   Rain also fell over parts of the middle and northern Atlantic
Coast, with nearly an inch at Portland, Maine.
   Scattered thunderstorms developed over the central Rockies and
central high Plains, producing small hail in the Colorado Springs,
Colo., area.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included
nearly 2 inches at Tampa, Fla., an inch and a quarter at Wilmington,
N.C. and about an inch at Charleston, S.C., and Portland, Maine.
   Clear skies prevailed across the middle Mississippi Valley and
across the West.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 54
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 99 degrees at
Beeville, Texas. The low in 48 contiguous states Tuesday morning was
29 degrees at Truckee, Calif.
   The forecast for Wednesday called for showers and thunderstorms
from the southern Plains to the Gulf Coast, the southern and middle
Atlantic Coast and southern New England, from Oklahoma and Arkansas
to western Missouri and along the Missouri Valley to North Dakota,
and from Minnesota to northern Michigan; and widely scattered rain
showers from eastern Montana to eastern Colorado.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 60s near the shores of
Lake Superior and along sections of the Pacific Coast, the 90s in
sections of Florida and from southern Texas and New Mexico to
interior valleys of California and southwest Oregon, over 100
degrees in the desert Southwest and along the Rio Grande Valley of
Texas, and 70s and 80s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
