<HEAD>Foley's New Job Brings $15,500 Raise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley got a raise
Tuesday.
   Prior to taking the oath that made him speaker, the former
majority leader earned $99,500 a year. By moving up to the top post
in the House he boosted his earning to $115,000 annually.
   The Washington Democrat will not pick up many new perks, since he
already enjoyed the benefits of a House leadership seat.
   As majority leader, Foley was driven around in a government-owned
Lincoln Town Car. He will keep the car and driver.
   Foley already has extra staff members, and most of them will move
from the majority leader's office to the speaker's office.
   As speaker, Foley will become chairman of the 31-member
Democratic Steering and Policy Committee, which decides party policy
matters and makes committee assignments. He has been a member of the
committee.
