<SECOND>AM-China-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0748,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summary of Developments in China</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with U.S. saying leaders apparently
left capital. Pick up with Government Statement. Edits thereafter to trim.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are developments in China
Tuesday:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ARMIES EXCHANGE FIRE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Armies loyal to hard-line and moderate government leaders traded
gunfire in the capital, winesses said.
   Witnesses said the 27th Army, which invaded the city Saturday to
crush the pro-democracy movement, fought with soldiers from the 28th
Army, believed loyal to Zhao Ziyang, the moderate Communist Party
chief who was stripped of his post last month. There were no reports
of casualties.
   Hundreds of citizens flocked to welcome soldiers who said they
were from the 38th Army, based in Beijing. The 38th Army is said to
have opposed the martial law crackdown and refused to fire on
civilians.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>U.S. SAYS LEADERS APPARENTLY LEFT CAPITAL</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the United
States has been in contact with midlevel Chinese officials but
failed to contact top-level officials in Beijing. ``The assumption
has been that the top-level people have moved out to other
locations,'' he said. ``It's like the place is closed down. ...
There's no indication who the leadership is.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>GOVERNMENT STATEMENT</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   In the first appearance of a top official since last weekend,
government spokesman Yuan Mu said China is ``not afraid'' of the
universal condemnation of the government's actions.
   ``The rebellion has not been completely quelled,'' he said. ``The
situation in the capital remains very grim.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OFFICIAL CASUALTIES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced that nearly 300 people were killed, more
than 7,000 were injured and said the figure included soldiers,
``thugs,'' bystanders and 23 students.
   The official figures were far lower than some unofficial
estimates from diplomats of more than 3,000 deaths.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>VIOLENCE CONTINUES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers continued firing into crowds around Beijing. Witnesses
reported a small boy killed and a girl wounded in the head. Police
in riot gear cruised the streets in vans as night fell, beating up
and shooting passers-by.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OTHER DEMONSTRATIONS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-government demonstrations spread to Shanghai, Nanjing,
Chengdu, Shenyang and other cities.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CHINESE DISSIDENT</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Noted Chinese dissident Fang Lizhi was permitted to take refuge
in the U.S. Embassy in Beijing, a U.S. State Department official
said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>LI SHOOTING</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   A young guard reportedly shot four times at Premier Li Peng in
Beijing's Great Hall of the People on Sunday, slightly wounding him
in the thigh.
   The guard was immediately killed, according to the report in a
Hong Kong daily.
   Chinese sources said the man shot Li because a relative was
killed by soldiers in Tiananmen Square.
</TEXT>
