<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 2057EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Contras     06-06 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Contras,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contras Announce Election Plans; Won't Go Home Yet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Contras on Tuesday again defied U.S. pressure to
return to Nicaragua and vote in February's elections, saying they
will organize exiles and maintain their military strength.
   ``The State Department has urged us to return as quickly as
possible,'' said Aristides Sanchez, spokesman for the Contra
directorate's majority. ``But that is counterproductive ... it would
be premature.''
   Only one of the Nicaraguan rebels' seven directors, Alfredo
Cesar, has said he will go back to his homeland without conditions.
He is scheduled to arrive in Managua next week to begin preparations
for national elections.
   The directorate is based in Miami, which was chosen for its
proximity to the Central American country and its large Nicaraguan
community.
   Cesar's action ``shows different criteria, and those are not the
criteria of the majority _ we think it divides the opposition,''
Sanchez said.
   The rebels, who are receiving only non-lethal aid from the United
States, will also resist pressure to disband their troops
concentrated in Honduran camps just north of the Nicaraguan border,
the spokesman said.
   ``If the elections are a fraud, and if they do not produce a
constitutional, free, democratic country, the troops should be
viable to take up the struggle again,'' he said.
   The Contra rebel groups were supposed to be reintegrated into
civilian life under the Central American peace plan approved by the
region's presidents, but the Contra leadership has refused, accusing
the Sandinistas of violating their guarantees under the pact. The
Bush administration has threatened to renew military aid to the
Contras if the national elections are unfair.
   In an official statement announcing their electoral strategy, the
Contra directors pledged Tuesday to deliver a minimum 250,000
Nicaraguan exile votes to the opposition in February.
   Nicaragua's population of about 3 million includes 1.75 million
voters, according to the government. But exiles would have to return
to Nicaragua to vote under the law, which the opposition is trying
to change to allow voting in consulates.
   As many as half a million Nicaraguans have fled the war and
economic chaos in their country, with most settling in neighboring
Central American countries and the United States.
   The Contra statement said the Contra leaders will not return to
Nicaragua until they have successfully concluded talks with the
internal opposition aimed at unifying anti-Sandinista groups and
settling on a single presidential candidate.
   The Contras will insist on a ``national dialogue'' to set
conditions for February's vote, the statement said.
   ``With a unified opposition, the candidate should take the
initiative to call all Nicaraguans back to support them,'' Sanchez
said. ``Returning before that would be premature.''
   The Contras and the Internal Civic Opposition are meeting to
establish such a united front, Sanchez said.
   Asked how long the unification might take, he said ``we had hoped
it would already be done,'' refusing to give a deadline for the
talks to end.
   He said the Sandinistas have blocked the negotiations with a
series of ``impediments,'' such as denying visas to participants to
freely enter and leave Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
