<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 2106EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-UnionMarch 1stLd-Writethru a0660 06-06 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Union March, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0660,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Striking Miners Begin March to Charleston</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with miners arriving at camp, quotes;
picks up 8th graf pvs, `The miners...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN GILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOGAN, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coal miners seeking support for two strikes
completed the first leg of a six-day march to the state capital
Tuesday, camping at the site of a battle between union and
government forces nearly 70 years ago.
   The miners on strike against the Pittston Coal Group expected to
join up with two other groups of marching miners, plus machinists on
strike against Eastern Airlines, for a multiunion rally Sunday at
the state Capitol in Charleston, with Jesse Jackson scheduled as a
speaker.
   ``We'll be singing all the way. We're not calling this off for
rain, sleet, snow or nothing,'' said Bethel Purkey, president of
United Mine Workers Local 5815.
   About 60 striking UMW members left their picket shacks near Logan
early Tuesday on the 85-mile march toward Charleston, he said.
   The Logan marchers at mid-afternoon reached Blair Mountain, the
site of a 1921 confrontation between federal troops and coal miners
struggling to organize West Virginia's mines.
   The miners lost that battle in a bloody era of the state's
history, but the confrontation marked a turning point in the UMW's
rise to power. The marchers planned to erect a plaque to commemorate
the battle.
   ``They passed this way to win what they got, so we're passing
this way to keep what we've got,'' said John Tomblin, 35, of Logan.
   In addition to Jackson, Sunday's rally is expected to draw
representatives of almost every other labor union in the state. UMW
President Richard Trumka is scheduled to attend, but Gov. Gaston
Caperton is undecided.
   ``We're going to Charleston to see what side of the fence the
governor's on,'' Tomblin said.
   The miners who set out Tuesday are part of a strike in West
Virginia and Virginia against the Pittston Coal Group. Pittston
workers walked out April 5 after working 14 months without a
contract.
   Another group of Pittston miners from the Logan area in southern
West Virginia planned to join the marchers Saturday.
   A third group of miners on strike against the New Beckley Mining
Corp. at the company's Glen Daniel mine also planned to join the
march Saturday. New Beckley miners have been off the jobs since
January.
   The battle of Blair Mountain was a result of a long history of
poor miners trying to organize and coal companies working maintain a
status quo.
   The UMW had been formed in 1890 but its attempts to organize
workers in southern West Virginia's Logan and Mingo counties met
with a coal company practice of firing anyone who joined the union
and evicting them from company-owned houses.
   The conflict led to the ``Matewan Massacre'' on May 19, 1920, in
which 10 people, including seven coal company detectives and
Matewan's mayor, were killed. The next year, Mingo County Sheriff
Sid Hatfield, a defender of the union, was shot and killed at the
McDowell County Courthouse where he was standing trial for murder in
connection with the Matewan shootout.
   Upon news of Hatfield's death, miners gathered at Marmet, outside
Charleston, for an invasion of Logan and Mingo counties and at Blair
Mountain met federal troops who had been called from Kentucky and
Virginia.
   Three union men were killed and 40 men from both sides were
wounded. The state brought 543 people to trial _ 22 on treason
charges _ but the treason charges were dropped and all others were
acquitted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
