<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 2108EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CountryAwards     06-06 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Country Awards,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shelton, Travis, Cash Honored</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rising country music star Ricky Van
Shelton, voted four awards by the public, said he knows now why
fellow singer Randy Travis has always been so happy.
   Travis has dominated country music awards for the past three
years, but Shelton was the bigger winner at the 23rd annual Music
City News Country Awards presentations Monday night.
   Shelton won male vocalist of the year, single of the year and
favorite music video, both for ``I'll Leave This World Loving You,''
and best album for ``Loving Proof.''
   ``I know why he (Travis) smiles so much now,'' Shelton said
backstage at the Grand Ole Opry House. ``It's wonderful.''
   Travis earned one award, entertainer of the year, the top honor
of the 16 presented. It marked the second straight year he won the
award.
   ``I've been lucky to win what I have,'' he said, reflecting on
his dozens of awards. ``I've always said I knew the time will come
when I won't win. I've got to be thankful for what I have and I've
had plenty.''
   Another country star who's received his share of awards, Johnny
Cash, won another Monday night and President Bush helped honor him.
   Cash was presented the Living Legend Award for a distinguished
career after a videotaped message from Bush was played.
   ``Your songs have helped reawaken patriotism in America,'' the
president said. ``In every sense of the word, you are a true living
legend.''
   Cash, who spoke by satellite from Hawaii where he was on vacation
following a European concert tour, said, ``It's a very humbling
experience to receive an award like this.''
   ``I'm as excited as Ricky Van Shelton must be,'' said Cash.
   For the fifth straight year, Reba McEntire was chosen No. 1
female vocalist. This year, the honor qualified as a wedding
present, coming just two days after she married Narvel Blackstock,
her manager, in Lake Tahoe, Nev. The marriage was announced Monday
afternoon.
   ``This award means to me one more time that I'm accepted,'' she
said backstage after accepting her plaque.
   The awards were presented during a two-hour syndicated television
special. Some stations will broadcast a delayed version of the show
later this week.
   All winners were picked by subscribers to The Music City News, a
monthly country music magazine published in Nashville.
   Patty Loveless, a cousin of country queen Loretta Lynn, was voted
Star of Tomorrow over the late Keith Whitley and three others. In
her acceptance remarks, she paid tribute to Whitley, who died of an
alcohol overdose May 9.
   ``Keith Whitley lives on with his music as far as I'm
concerned,'' she said.
   The Statler Brothers quartet was voted group of the year for the
sixth straight time, raising their total number of Music City News
awards through the years to a record 39.
   Other winners were: Ray Stevens, comedian of the year for the
fourth straight time; Ricky Skaggs, instrumentalist of the year; the
Judds, vocal duo of the year; the Whites, gospel group of the year;
The Nashville Network's ``Nashville Now,'' No. 1 TV series for the
fifth year; ``A Country Music Celebration: 30th Anniversary of the
Country Music Association,'' best TV special, and Dwight Yoakam and
Buck Owens, vocal collaboration (two or more performers).
</TEXT>
