<FIRST>u p AM-NJGovernor 1stLd-Writethru a0696 06-06 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NJ Governor, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0696,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Florio Wins Democratic Primary; Tight GOP Race, pickup at dash</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Covering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. James Florio easily captured the
Democratic nomination for governor Tuesday, while four Republicans
were locked in a close battle for a chance to succeed outgoing Gov.
Thomas H. Kean.
   Florio, who barely lost to Kean eight years ago, trounced two
rivals in the Democratic primary. With 9 percent of precincts
reporting, Florio had 19,356 votes or 64 percent, Assemblyman Alan
Karcher had 5,680 votes or 19 percent and Princeton Mayor Barbara
Sigmund had 5,195 votes or 17 percent.
   In an eight-way GOP race, Rep. James Courter, who started the
race as the frontrunner, led with 9,045 votes or 24 percent. Close
on his heels were Attorney General Cary Edwards with 8,813 votes or
24 percent and state Sen. William Gormley with 8,736 votes or 24
percent. State Assembly Speaker Chuck Hardwick was fourth with 6,307
votes or 17 percent.
   Republican state Sen. Gerald Cardinale, who sounded a
conservative theme, was running a distant fifth and three other
Republicans who ran low-budget campaign _ Lois Rand, Thomas
Blomquist and James Kolyer _ trailed far behind.
   Kean, barred by law from seeking a third consecutive four-year
term, made no endorsement in what became one of the state's closest
GOP primaries in recent history.
   Florio, who lost to Kean in 1981 by 1,797 votes out of 2.3
million cast, deliberately kept a low profile on the campaign trail
and refused to engage in much debate with his more liberal opponents.
   In Sacramento, Calif., voters decided whether the Rancho Seco
nuclear power plant should become the first such facility in the
nation permanently closed by the electorate. The referendum on the
troubled 15-year-old plant was non-binding, but the commissioners
who operate it said they would abide by the results.
   Elsewhere, in Jackson, Miss., Democratic state Rep. Kane Ditto
was expected to best three token opponents in voting for mayor. And
in Florala, Ala., ousted Mayor H.T. Mathis tried to get his old job
back. Mathis, 86, who drew national attention last year when he
declared ``National Voodoo Week'' in the southern Alabama town, was
removed from office in August for abusing his pardoning power,
willful neglect of duty and incompetence.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   All of New Jersey's major candidates agreed to accept public
financing and limit their campaign spending to $2.2 million. That,
plus Republican Kean's decision not to endorse any of the four
leading candidates also helped level the playing field.
   In New Jersey's GOP race, Courter stuck to his theme that he
alone was not from the state capital of Trenton, and did not
participate in creating the state's automobile insurance and budget
problems.
   Edwards emphasized his seven years of experience as a top adviser
and cabinet official in the Kean administration, saying he has
experience making hard decisions and writing budgets.
   Hardwick appealed largely to the conservative wing of the
Republican party and courted the pro-life and gun lobbies.
   Gormley spent most of his time and money in southern New Jersey,
aligning himself with Kean and going after moderate voters.
   During a grueling four months of campaigning, the GOP candidates
confronted each other at roughly 30 different forums, including five
hours of sometimes rancorous televised debates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
