<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 2114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-China-Senate     06-06 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Senate,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Urges Bush to Consult Allies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted 100-0 Tuesday to urge
President Bush to consult immediately with U.S. allies on imposing
international sanctions against the Chinese government ``to
demonstrate abhorrence'' over the killing of thousands of unarmed
students.
   The House earlier voted 406-0 to approve a resolution condemning
the violence used against pro-democracy demonstrators in Beijing and
commending the president for acting to end military cooperation with
China.
   The Senate resolution also commends Bush and condemns ``the
brutal use of force by the government of the People's Republic of
China against unarmed advocates of democracy and human rights in
China.''
   But it also urges serious consideration of steps that go beyond
those taken so far by the president, including the consideration of
international sanctions.
   These include:
   _Calling on the U.S. Export-Import Bank and the Overseas Private
Investment Corp. to review financing of trade with China ``in light
of existing legal requirements for adequate human rights treatment
and the deteriorating condition of human rights in China.''
   _Urging those U.S. agencies charged with liberalizing procedures
for export licenses for sales to China to ``take into account the
current situation in China in making their decisions.''
   _Urging the Voice of America to immediately increase
Chinese-language programming.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, and Minority
Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., said the administration supported the
resolution.
   Mitchell said that while the United States cannot control events
in China, ``it is within our power to express the views of the
American people clearly, unequivocally and unambiguously ... in
total condemnation and denunciation of the actions that have been
taken.''
   ``We have witnessed a great leap backward in China,'' said Dole.
``I hope it is not too late for China's leaders to come to their
senses.''
   Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., said an increase in Voice of America
broadcasts can be accomplished quickly and ``do a service for the
people of China''
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said, ``This resolution is mild
compared to what the majority of us would like to see done to those
responsible for these atrocious acts.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890606-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 2117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-China 4thLd-Writethru a0773 06-06 1042</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-China, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0773,1,040</SECOND>
<HEAD>Americans Urged To Leave Chinese Capital</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 26th graf, ``The Senate,'' which is 4th bullet graf,
on House and Senate resolutions.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As rival troops squared off in Beijing, The
Bush administration said Tuesday that China's senior leaders
appeared to have left the capital and urged the 1,440 Americans in
the city to get ut themselves.
   ``It's like the place is closed down,'' said White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater. ``There's been no communication from the
leadership. There's no indication who the leadership is.''
   At the State Department, spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler called the
situation in Beijing ``tense and unsettled.''
   She acknowledged there may be dissension within the Chinese armed
forces and a U.S. intelligence source, commenting on the grounds of
anonymity said, ``What we're seeing, first, is a political struggle,
the outlines of which are very vague. Plus there is a serious
division'' within the Chinese Army leadership.
   Fitzwater said the U.S. Embassy has been in contact only with
mid-level Chinese officials but has had ``no contact with the
top-level people _ and we've tried.
   ``The assumption has been that the top-level people have moved
out to other locations. We tend to believe it.''
   Tutwiler, meanwhile, referring to the shooting of hundreds of
students demonstrating for democracy, told reporters:
   ``We have reason to believe that all elements of the Army do not
support what is taking place. We have no firm evidence of armed
clashes.''
   The Chinese capital was threatened with civil war as armies loyal
to rival political factions were reported battling in the city.
   The U.S. intelligence source said his information was that Army
units from Beijing had refused to move against the students in
Tiananmen Square even as Army elements from Nanjing carried out
Sunday's bloody attack.
   ``We're hearing all the reports of shooting between Army units,
but we have not confirmed that ourselves,'' the source added.
   An official, speaking on conditition of anonymity, said U.S.
intelligence reports reaching Washington estimated the death toll at
3,000, in line with estimates by diploatic sources in Beijing but 10
times the Chinese government estimate. This official said the
reports stressed the toll could go higher.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III decided to encourage
Americans to leave Beijing after a long telephone conversation
Monday night with James Lilley, the U.S. ambassador there. Baker was
told 50 percent to 75 percent of the employees of American firms had
already decided to leave.
   Ms. Tutwiler said arrangements were being discussed with United
Airlines and Northwest Airlines to supplement their regular service
from China with charter flights to carry out Americans.
   But United spokesman Joe Hopkins said in Chicago that his airline
had no plans to add flights.
   ``We're just operating our regular schedule'' of three flights a
week, he said.
   Indeed, one State Department official said that regularly
scheduled flights were proving adequate, so far, to handle the
number of Americans leaving the capital.
   ``We cannot order them to leave,'' the official said of the
Americans choosing to stay.
   In other developments:
   _A State Department official noted Chinese dissident Fang Lizhi
has been allowed to take refuge in the U.S. Embassy in Beijing.
   The official, who requested anonymity, said Fang, a 53-year-old
astrophysicist who had been denied permission to meet with President
Bush when he visited China in February, ``took refuge for his own
safety'' and has been at the embassy at least since Monday.
   _Bush directed the Justice Department not to move against Chinese
nationals whose visas have expired. Ms. Tutwiler said the visitors
could stay indefinitely.
   Subsequently, Attorney General Dick Thornburgh issued an order
allowing 73,000 Chinese students and 250,000 Chinese visitors and
business travelers to stay in the United States if they request
one-year extensions of their visas.
   _The National Academy of Sciences announced it was suspending a
cooperative exchange program with the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
   Frank Press, the president of the National Academy, said in a
telex to Chinese Academy of Sciences president Zhou Guangzhao that
the exchanges were being suspended ``in outrage and sadness'' and
that Americans ``are shocked and dismayed by the action of Chinese
government troops against peaceful demonstrators.''
   _The Senate and House voted without dissent for resolutions
condemning the violence in Beijing, with the Senate resolution
urging President Bush to consult U.S. allies on possible
international sanctions against China.
   On Monday, even after Army troops assaulted the pro-democracy
students in Tiananmen Square, the State Department encouraged
Americans in China simply to stay in touch with the U.S. Embassy or
the four U.S. consulates.
   ``I can't point to any specific thing that happened,'' Ms.
Tutwiler said about the newest State Department guidance. ``Every
day is different.''
   Elsewhere in China, the 7,360 Americans who are permament
residents were advised to consider leaving the country ``depending
on the local situation.'' Ms. Tutwiler said they should not leave
through Beijing.
   Additionally, the families of the 428 American diplomats and
workers at the U.S. Embassy and the consulates were given permission
to leave the country.
   ``There is no drawdown of embassy officers,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
``The embassy and our four consulate offices continue to operate
fully.''
   Apart from permanent residents and U.S. officials, an estimated
4,000 Americans are traveling in China at ny particular time.
Tourists were advised not to go there.
   ``It is not an order to leave, but we are encouraging them to
leave,'' a U.S. official said in reference to the advice the embassy
was giving to the American residents of Beijing.
   Sources said telephone calls were being made systematically to
all American residents of the capital, who had been asked earlier to
make the embassy aware of their whereabouts.
   Ms. Tutwiler and the other officials, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said that no Americans were known to have been threatened
directly, but that the situation was too chaotic for them to safely
remain in China.
   On Monday, Bush suspended more than $600 million in U.S. arms
sales to China but stopped short of advocating economic sanctions,
at least for now.
   The decision to encourage Americans to leave, however, could
itself have a severe impact on American businesses operating in
China and on commercial ties to the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
