<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 2131EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-SpendingBill 2ndLd-Writethru a0763 06-06 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spending Bill, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0763,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Nears Completion of Spending Bill for Veterans, Others</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 4-5 pvs bgng: ``Democrats said,'' with 3 grafs bgng:
``Democrats said,'' Senate defeating amendment on South Africa and adopting
tax law language; one graf edited for transition and picks up 7th graf
pvs: ``Is there,'' The Senate has recessed until Wednesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate sculpted the final contours of a
catchall bill Tuesday rushing $3.3 billion to veterans programs, a
shattered West Virginia telescope and a host of other projects and
making pronouncements on policies domestic and foreign.
   Lawmakers had hoped their third day of debate on the legislation
would be the last as they sorted through amendments to a ``dire
emergency'' measure President Bush first proposed in March.
   But they bogged down over an amendment offered by Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., to delay some of the new catastrophic care
provisions for the elderly under Medicare, including the surtax on
people more than 65 years old designed to pay for the program. Some
senior citizens have complained about the tax, which can reach a
maximum of $800 for the wealthiest of them.
   Democrats said catastrophic care changes should be made in
separate legislation, and work on the bill was scheduled to continue
Wednesday.
   The Senate rejected 69-29 an amendment by Sen. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., allowing the Transportation Department to block aid to
communities refusing to give work on public transit projects to
companies that conduct business with the pro-apartheid regime of
South Africa.
   It also adopted by voice vote a provision by Senate Majority
Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, calling on Congress to rework a tax
law business considers burdensome.
   That followed a 50-49 defeat for Sen. Robert Kasten, R-Wis., who
instead wanted the Senate to repeal the tax law, which forces
companies to prove their health benefits are as generous to low-paid
workers as they are to executives. For procedural reasons, Kasten
would have needed 60 votes to prevail.
   Kasten called the provision ``unwise, unworkable and just plain
unfair.'' Democrats agreed that the tax law needs revamping, but
said revoking it would be a mistake.
   ``Is there any reason we should be favoring management?'' asked
Senate Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas.
   The legislation is aimed at providing extra money for the rest of
fiscal 1989, which ends Sept. 30. It contains $1.2 billion for
veterans programs, $892 million for student loans, $342 million for
the costs of last summer's Western forest fires, and money for
efforts including foster care, refugees, the United Nations, and
food stamps.
   It also bestows federal money on a host of projects of a less
sweeping nature, but championed by various legislators for local
consumption.
   Thus, it contains $75 million to rebuild a 26-year-old West
Virginia radio telescope that collapsed last November, sought by
Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.
   Thanks to Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., $275,000 would
be set aside for Kansas State University to advise farmers on coping
with drought. Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, garnered $500,000 for
engineering work on a lake in Cincinnati that has filled with
sediment. Wyoming's two GOP senators, Malcolm Wallop and Alan
Simpson, got $400,000 for a study of last summer's fires at
Yellowstone National Park.
   In a boon to senators from 39 states, the measure also supplies
$6.6 million to continue subsidizing air carriers serving small
communities.
   The legislation also carries provisions stating the Senate's
views on an assortment of topics.
   The chamber wants the Agriculture Department to buy more apples
for the federal school lunch program to help the country's ailing
apple industry, thanks to Washington state's two senators, Democrat
Brock Adams and Republican Slade Gorton.
   It wants the Department of Health and Human Services to hire more
employees in Honolulu, in the home state of Appropriations Committee
member Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii.
   And it doesn't want Panamanian Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega to be
able to name a new administrator of the Panama Canal Commission,
which by treaty Panama's leader is entitled to do.
   One thing the bill does not have is $822 million for various
anti-drug programs contained in the $3.7 billion version of the
legislation the House passed last month. That discrepancy and others
will have to be worked out by negotiators before the bill can be
sent to the White House for Bush's signature.
   Bush, citing the federal deficit, has threatened to veto the
measure if it has any money for drug programs. The measure Bush
initially proposed was for $2.2 billion.
</TEXT>
