<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 2241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FederalDams     06-06 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Federal Dams,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Bars State Water Flow Regulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court ruled Tuesday that states
cannot regulate water flows from federally approved power dams,
rejecting arguments from 17 Western states that had sought the
authority in order to protect fish.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that the Federal
Energy Regulatory Commission, a presidentially appointed agency, has
exclusive power under federal law to set standards for hydroelectric
projects, including water flows needed to protect fish.
   The ruling, which upheld a 1987 FERC decision, affects all types
of water power projects, including larger utility-owned dams, which
periodically must be relicensed. It is primarily important in the
West, where small hydroelectric projects have flourished since
Congress passed a law in 1978 requiring utility companies to buy
electricity from those projects when oil prices exceeded certain
levels.
   The states, led by California, were supported by several
environmental groups, which in written arguments to the court called
hydroelectric development ``one of the greatest threats to our
nation's free-flowing rivers.''
   ``The states tend to be the most knowledgeable, the most
sensitive to the resources at stake, and they have a major role to
play'' in protecting fish and wildlife, said John Echeverria,
general counsel of American Rivers, which led a half-dozen
environmental groups.
   The federal agency's position was supported by small dam
operators and major utility companies, who said state regulation
would disrupt hydroelectric development.
   One such project was the Rock Creek dam, a 3,000-kilowatt project
on a tributary of the South Fork of the American River about 40
miles east of Sacramento.
   FERC approved the dam in 1983 and required operators to maintain
a flow of 11 cubic feet per second of water into Rock Creek from May
to September, and 15 cubic feet per second from October through
April, to protect an important trout spawning ground.
   The California Water Resources Control Board, at the request of
state fish and game officials, set flow standards in 1986 of 30 and
60 cubic feet per second for the same two periods, saying the lesser
flows were inadequate to protect the fishery.
   Rock Creek officials objected to FERC, which ruled in 1987 that
it had sole authority to set the flow rates. The dam was completed
in 1986 and has operated under the federal standards.
   The other states supporting California's position were Alaska,
Arizona, Hawaii, Idaho, Kansas, Montana, Nebraska, Nevada, New
Mexico, North Dakota, Oklahoma, Oregon, South Dakota, Utah,
Washington and Wyoming.
</TEXT>
