<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 2301EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Chile     06-06 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pinochet Warns Against Human Rights Trials Of Military</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA VERGARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Augusto Pinochet said the armed
forces will not tolerate human rights trials by special courts or
the Congress after a civilian government takes over next march.
   The lame-duck military president also said he will remain as army
commander after handing over power to a successor to be elected in
national balloting Dec. 14. He said his continuing on an army chief
was necessary ``to ensure Chile's institutional organization.''
   Pinochet's remarks came Monday at a meeting with Chilean women
journalists and were carried by local newspapers Tuesday.
   Under the constitution, Pinochet can stay on as army commander
for eight years after stepping down as president. The opposition
vehemently opposes that clause, but the 73-year-old Pinochet has
refused to change it.
   Asked about allegations of human rights violations under his
military government, Pinochet said he agrees ``some cases must be
dealt with by the courts.'' But he added, ``I cannot accept that
members of the services be targeted for revenge or that special
courts be organized in Congress.''
   He hinted that the future democracy could be threatened if that
happens.
   ``There would be a reaction against that'' from the military, he
said, ``and I don't want to even think what might happen.''
   Pinochet seized power in a bloody 1973 coup, overthrowing an
elected leftist government. Hundreds of leftists later were rounded
up. Many were tortured or killed and thousands forced into exile.
   The Roman Catholic Church and human rights groups here and abroad
have documented the cases of about 750 people who disappeared after
being arrested by security agents.
   Opposition leaders say they are not out for revenge but intend to
find the truth about human rights violations and bring those
responsible to trial.
   They insist their aim is to try individuals, not the armed
services as such.
   Pinochet emphasized that the armed forces have decided to return
to barracks and move away from the political arena after 16 years in
power.
   ``Now, I say so long, and It's your problem now,'' he said.
``It's over for me and for the army.''
   He said the military was leaving in disappointment, considering
the Chilean people as having been ``ungrateful'' to them.
   He referred to last October's national referendum in which voters
overwhelmingly rejected a military proposal extending his term until
1997. The outcome obliged Pinochet to call the December election.
   ``We received a country in chaos, and were are leaving a decent
country,'' Pinochet said.
</TEXT>
