<FIRST>u a AM-China-TouristsRdp     06-06 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Tourists Rdp,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Americans Returning from China Recount Tales of Horror</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE BUCKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans returning from China recounted tales of horror,
including one man who said he watched as troops opened fire into
crowds of students and was shocked because ``I've never seen people
mowed down, murdered.''
   Merv Lapin of Vail, Colo., returned from Beijing on Monday, two
days after Chinese troops moved in on pro-democracy demonstrators in
Tianmen Square, killing hundreds in the most violent suppression of
a popular movement in Communist China's 40-year history.
   The stockbroker and amateur hockey coach was on his seventh visit
to China, where he coaches children's hockey in Manchuria. He
stopped in Beijing on his way home.
   ``I saw one soldier go down on his knee _ maybe more than one,
things were moving so fast ... and he started firing into the
crowd,'' Lapin said. ``There was more than one soldier firing. My
guess is there were four, five, six-thousand soldiers.
   ``They started firing indiscriminately into the students. I saw
people falling ... It was chaos at this point.
   ``I was in a state of shock _ I've never seen people mowed down,
murdered,'' Lapin said. ``No one thought this was going to happen.
The students were just standing there with locked arms, some five or
10 deep. The feeling I got was that they were surprised. Everyone
started running and screaming.
   ``I saw bodies lying there _ it had to be in the hundreds _ and I
saw a tank roll over the bodies.''
   At San Franciso International Airport on Tuesday, Kathleen
Tiedeman, a delegate with the U.S. China Joint Seminar on Industry,
Trade and Economic Development, said she tried to get to Tiananmen
Square _ first in a taxi, then on the backs of bicycles pedaled by
students.
   ``We were about two miles from the square when the gunfire
started: there was no mistaking it,'' Tiedeman said. ``Then a wave
of panic took place. I tripped, and then two thoughts came: One, I'm
going to be shot, and two, I'm going to be trampled.
   ``My friend threw himself over me and said: `Stay down. Don't
move.' When we got up, we saw about 20 dead people all around us,''
she said.
   Passengers arriving at Los Angeles International Airport said
they were overjoyed to return to American soil.
   Carol Young said that from her hotel room she was able to see the
tanks approaching the center of the city.
   ``It was very frightening,'' she said. ``I could see the tanks
coming down the street. I could see the guns. I could see the guns
raise.''
   At New York City's Kennedy Airport, Helaine Harte, 23, of
Livingston, N.J., who was attending the Beijing College for
Economics, was among several Americans returning from China.
   ``I was really sorry to see what was going on there,'' she said.
``When the protests started and the demonstrations for democracy,
there was lots of joy and goodness but it all turned to disaster
this weekend.
   ``You see tanks in the street, places burning, you hear gunfire _
it's very, very frightening,'' she added. ``I had to leave but I'm
sorry that I did.''
   Ms. Harte said she had called the U.S. Embassy for help in
getting to the airport in China, but was told she would have to get
there on her own. She finally bribed a taxi driver with a sum she
said was more than he normally makes in a year.
</TEXT>
