<FIRST>u a AM-Time-Paramount 1stLd-Writethru a0796 06-06 0730</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Time-Paramount, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0796,0755</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paramount Launches $10.7 Billion Bid for Time</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with comment from analyst, Paramount, ADDS background;
minor editing throughout. A version also moving on the financial wire.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramount Communications Inc. late Tuesday
announced a $10.7 billion takeover offer for publishing and cable
giant Time Inc., which already plans a merger with Warner
Communications Inc.
   Paramount, an entertainment and communications company formerly
known as Gulf &amp; Western Inc., said it offered $175 a share for all
of Time's stock.
   The announcment came less than three weeks before Time and Warner
shareholders are scheduled to vote on the merger agreement announced
in March.
   The Time-Warner merger plan calls for a stock swap that the
companies valued at $18 billion and said would create the world's
largest media and entertainment company.
   Time said its board would review the proposal and advised its
shareholders not to do anything until they heard from the company.
   Warner officials had no immediate comment.
   Time, Warner and Paramount are all based in New York.
   Time shares closed at $126 Tuesday in consolidated New York Stock
Exchange trading, up $2.75.
   Paramount made its announcement after the market closed, and the
company noted it was offering a price 60 percent higher than Time's
share price just before the Time-Warner deal was announced.
   There had been speculation for weeks that a bidder could emerge
for Time despite its merger agreement with Warner. But Time
executives have privately insisted the company was not for sale.
   Harold Vogel, who follows the entertainment industry for Merrill
Lynch &amp; Co., called it a ``fascinating situation.''
   ``My feeling is that this is going to entail a much lengthier
battle than Time and Warner had anticipated,'' Vogel said. ``Both
companies were obviously in a rush to get this done as fast as
possible for concern that someone could come in and upset the
proposed merger.''
   Martin S. Davis, Paramount's chairman and chief executive, said
Time and Paramount ``are a superb business fit.''
   He said the acquisition of Time would represent ``the culmination
of a six-year strategic transformation of our company into a leader
in publishing and entertainment, a focus reflected by our new name.''
   ``Together we will be the foremost American communications
company, capable of competing on a global scale against foreign
media giants,'' he said.
   Paramount announced in April that it intended to sell its
consumer and commercial finance business, The Associates. It is
expected the sale could produce $3 billion or more in revenue.
   Paramount said Citibank has committed to provide $1 billion in
financing for the offer and has said it is highly confident of its
ability to arrange a syndicate of lenders to provide the rest.
   Davis said he told Time's chairman and chief executive, J.
Richard Munro, that Paramount was willing to negotiate all aspects
of its proposal.
   Paramount also said it would immediately withdraw its offer if
Time shareholders approve the Warner transcation.
   Both Warner and Time shareholders are scheduled to vote on the
proposed merger, a stock swap that the companies valued at $18
billion, on June 23.
   In a statement, Time said Davis advised Munro in a telelphone
call Tuesday evening that ``Paramount was launching a hostile offer
for Time's shares.''
   Time said the offer was ``in contradiction to explicit assurances
Mr. Davis had previously given Mr. Munro,'' but did not elaborate.
   Time has indicated that it has a $5 billion credit line available
to begin its own offer for Warner or defend itself against a
takeover.
   Paramount's entertainment interests include Paramount Pictures,
Paramount Television and Paramount Home Video. It owns Madison
Square Garden and two professional sports teams: the New York
Knickerbockers in basketball and the New York Rangers in hockey. It
also owns the MSG cable Network and a 50 percent interest in the USA
cable network.
   In publishing, Paramount owns Simon &amp; Schuster, Prentice Hall and
Pocket Books.
   Time is the largest U.S. magazine company, publishing such titles
as Time, People, Sports Illustrated amd Fortune. It owns the book
companies Scott, Foresman and Co.; Little Brown and Co.; Time-Life
Books Inc.; and Book-of-the-Month Club Inc.
   It also holds an 82 percent stake in the cable television systems
company American Television and Communications Corp. and owns the
cable programmer Home Box Office Inc., which includes the HBO and
Cinemax pay-TV services.
</TEXT>
