<FIRST>r f PM-Northwest 1stLd-Writethru f0016 06-06 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0016,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>NWA Rejects Bids, Invites Revisions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS New 9th graf, KLM spokesman ... with Northwest,'' to
UPDATE with KLM comment. Picks up 9th graf pvs, Checchi would ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Initial buyout offers for NWA Inc. have been
rejected and suitors for the parent of Northwest Airlines have been
given until June 16 to enhance their proposals.
   ``None of the proposals is sufficiently more attractive than the
others,'' a five-member review committee set up by NWA's board of
directors said Monday in a letter to bidders.
   The letter said each of the bids is ``subject to unacceptable
material conditions.'' It directed interested buyers to address
regulatory concerns and asked for revised bids to propose
compensation for NWA in the event it accepts an offer that later
collapses.
   ``Bidders should specifically address their ability to
consummate a transaction in light of financing and other
conditions,'' the letter said.
   The committee's letter also repeated a statement that ``there
can be no assurance that a sale of NWA or any other transaction
will result from NWA's review of alternatives.''
   NWA stock tumbled $1.87{ to close at $106.87{ a share in
consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading Monday.
   Pan Am Corp., which earlier made a proposal valued at $3.3
billion, was the only announced bidder to say immediately it would
submit a revised bid, but the company did not reveal details.
   Other known bidders are billionaire Marvin Davis, whose $2.7
billion offer earlier this year started the bidding process; Alfred
Checchi, a Los Angeles investor who heads a group that includes KLM
Royal Dutch Airlines and the Australian holding company Elders IXL
Ltd.; and Northwest's 20,000-member Machinists' union.
   KLM spokesman Peter Wellhuner said today that the Dutch state
airliner was not surprised by the move and is studying its options.
He said there is a ``good possibility'' the Checchi group will
``get in touch again with Northwest.''
   Checchi would not comment on the rejection. A spokesman for
Davis said the oil mogul would study the committee's letter ``and
for now will withhold any reaction to it.'' Guy Cook, president of
the International Association of Machinists District Lodge 143, did
not return telephone calls seeking comment.
   Barbara Beyer, president of Avmark Inc., an aviation consulting
firm in Arlington, Va., said NWA's move could be designed to
broaden the scope of bidders for the nation's fourth-largest
airline. Suitors who were told the bidding would be conducted in a
single round could by angered by such a development, she said.
   Among those rumored as a possible suitor is the New York
takeover firm Kohlberg, Kravis Roberts &amp; Co., which could now step
in and make a bid if it missed the initial deadline, Beyer said.
   A KKR spokesman has declined to say whether the company is a
bidder. The company continued its silence Monday.
   U.S. Transportation Secretary Samuel K. Skinner has informed NWA
his department would review any proposed leveraged buyout of the
airline to judge the financial fitness of the proposed new owner.
   NWA's review committee will meet with department officials to
discuss Skinner's concerns, the company said Monday.
   The committee said in its letter that suitors are welcome to
meet with NWA management to seek more information about the
airline, based in the Minneapolis suburb of Eagan, but the letter
stressed that the meetings would not include negotiations.
   ``You should be aware that no aspect of any of the proposals has
been disclosed to members of NWA management,'' the letter said.
   The quote prompted rumors that NWA management, led by Chairman
Steven Rothmeier, was assembling its own buyout proposal, said Kurt
Rivard, an analyst for Dain Bosworth Inc. of Minneapolis. But
Rivard said he doubted such a move was in the works.
   Rothmeier told reporters in April that no management-led buyout
offers were planned.
</TEXT>
