<FIRST>u f PM-OPEC 2ndLd-Writethru f0042 06-06 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-OPEC, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0042,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Report Shows OPEC Production Up, Estimates Higher Demand</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS New grafs 5-6, Today, Mana Saeed ... new ceiling, to
UPDATE with comments from UAE minister. Minor editing thruout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer_</UNK>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC nations increased their oil
production to 21 million barrels a day in May, the highest output
so far this year, according to estimates released today.
   The International Energy Agency also predicted in its Monthly
Oil Market Report that demand for the cartel's oil would rise in
the second half of the year to about 20.85 million barrels a day,
up from a previous estimate of 20.4 million barrels.
   The ministers of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries were meeting in Vienna to set new price and
production guidelines for the rest of the year. The ministers
opened their formal strategy meeting Monday, then adjourned to hold
private bargaining sessions.
   Estimates of demand for their crude were heavily influencing
discussions.
   Today, Mana Saeed Otaiba, oil minister of the United Arab
Emirates, a persistent overproducer in the cartel, said he would
like to see OPEC boost its daily production to between 20 million
and 21 million barrels from the current 18.5 million barrels.
   Otaiba refused to say how much he'd like of the extra output.
The primary issue in the talks, he said, ``is to get everybody
within the new umbrella of 20 or 20 plus (million barrels a day) as
a new ceiling.''
   ``There's definitely movement toward an agreement,'' said Iraq's
oil chief, Issam Abdul Raheem al-Chalabi, but he did not elaborate.
   No date was set for resumption of their formal talks.
   Anticipating more demand for their crude, the ministers seemed
intent on fixing a higher output ceiling _ of as much as 20 million
barrels a day _ for the second half of the year.
   The ministers also appeared to be leaning toward retaining their
benchmark price of $18 a barrel. Saudi Arabia has recommended
discontinuing the target price.
   The sticking point in their bargaining is how to divide up the
extra output among the 13 countries. Kuwait and the United Arab
Emirates want a bigger share of any increase.
   The energy agency's report said OPEC production in May rose
about 500,000 barrels from April.
   ``This was primarily the result of higher production in Kuwait
and Nigeria, partly offset by a small decline in Iranian and
Ecuadorian production,'' it said.
   Oil futures prices recently have been rising amid speculation
about the outcome of the OPEC meeting. Other developments also
helped drive up energy prices Monday, including the death of
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, the Soviet gas pipeline explosion and
turmoil in China.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the contract for July
delivery of West Texas intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude oil, rose 38 cents to $20.52 a barrel Monday. Prices of
refined products also rose.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
