<HEAD>Wheat Prices Lower Despite Sales to China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed today on
the Chicago Board of Trade despite increased sales of wheat to
China.
   Monday's announcement that China has purchased 1.85 million
metric tons of wheat sent wheat prices higher in early trading
today, but prices moved lower as trading progressed.
   The wheat sale apparently had been negotiated over the previous
two weeks, said Jerry Gidel, an analyst with LIT America Inc. in
Chicago.
   Despite the announcement of the sale, analysts say there is
concern the turmoil in China could disrupt industry and commerce in
that huge commodity-trading nation.
   Corn prices were higher despite word that Egypt and Turkey have
made major corn purchases from France instead of the United States.
   Soybean prices were mostly higher, although the strong dollar is
expected to continue to hamper export sales.
   At the open, wheat was 1{ cents lower to } cent higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.94 a bushel; corn was a \ cent
lower to } cent higher with July at $2.64{ a bushel; oats were a {
cent lower with July at $1.68{ a bushel and soybeans were } cent
lower to 3{ cents higher with July at $7.09 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat prices were lower in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent to .55 cent lower with June at 68.82
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent lower to .13 cent higher
with August at 79.20 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent to .30 cent
lower with June at 48.45 cents a pound; pork bellies were .30 cent
to 1 cent lower with July at 31.55 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled higher on Monday.
