<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1218EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Colorado-Ute     06-06 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Colorado-Ute,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banks Force Colorado-Ute Into Bankruptcy Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three creditor banks have filed a petition to
force financially strapped Colorado-Ute Electric Association into
involuntary Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization.
   Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co., United Bank of Denver and
Norwest Bank Minneapolis, which are each owed $10 million, filed
the petition in federal bankruptcy court in Denver at the close of
business Monday.
   The filing, however, will not affect electric service to
Colorado-Ute's 14-member rural electric cooperatives, which in
turn, serve 49 of the state's 63 counties.
   Colorado-Ute serves nearly 600,000 Coloradans and is $1.1
billion in debt, with $877 million in assets.
   The utility has 20 days to respond to the banks' petition. If it
opposes the filing, a judge will hold a hearing to determine
whether the petiton is justified; otherwise, the case will proceed
as an ordinary Chapter 11 filing.
   Colorado-Ute said its two biggest creditors _ the federal Rural
Electrification Administration and the National Rural Electric
Cooperative Finance Corp. _ paved the way for Monday's filing by
refusing to accept a payback plan endorsed by the cooperative and
other creditors. The power supplier owes REA $417 million and CFC
$262 million.
</TEXT>
