<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0349</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rebounded today as concerns
about the political situation in China abated somewhat and bargain
hunters moved into the market following Monday's sharp decline.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks was up 19.85 to
2,500.55 as of noon EDT after falling 37 points on Monday.
   Advancing issues were ahead of decliners by a margin of about 7
to 4, with 844 stocks rising, 468 falling and 534 unchanged on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 85.44 million shares at midday.
   Jack Barbanel, a first vice president with Gruntal &amp; Co. Inc.,
said the market, whose sharp decline Monday was partly attributed
to worries about China, believed that over the long term, the more
conservative side of the Chinese government will fall, leaving more
democratic forces running the country.
   That could mean more fighting in China in the near future, but
traders were reassured by the possibility of peace there later on,
Barbanel said.
   Analysts also blamed Monday's drop on Wall Street to continuing
concern about the U.S. economy and to program selling.
   Buyers returned to the market today to take advantage of lower
prices, but Barbanel cautioned that there was still room for
further consolidation.
   Leading the NYSE's most active list was RJR Holdings, which rose
| to 23[ after RJR Nabisco said it was selling five food businesses
for $2.5 billion. The sales were expected as part of the company's
plan to reduce debt following its acquisition by Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts &amp; Co.
   Boeing was up 2 to 77|, AT&amp;T was up { to 35~ and General
Electric rose ] to 55.
   American Cynamid, which announced Monday it would acquire Praxis
Biologics Inc. for about $237 million in securities, was down 2 to
53{.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 1.10 to 180.99. On the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index rose 0.84 to 360.42.
