<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-UnitedStates     06-06 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-United States,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Reopens Anti-Dumping Process On U.S. Propane Product</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Commission said Tuesday it
will consider whether to continue anti-dumping measures against
U.S. imports of propylene alcohol, a propane-derived product used
in making printing ink, paints and cosmetics.
   The U.S. producers of propylene alcohol are Union Carbide Corp.
of Danbury, Connecticut; Eastman Chemical International Co.,
Kingsport, Tenn., which is part of Eastman Kodak Co.; and Hoechst
Celanese Corp., a subsidiary of West Germany's Hoechst AG.
   Current anti-dumping measures against imports of U.S. propylene
alcohol were first decided in April 1984. They were due to expire
last year, but will be kept in force until the new investigation is
completed, the European Commission said.
   According to a commission statement, the anti-dumping case was
reopened at the request of the European Council of Chemical
Industry Federations (Cefic), a Brussels-based group representing
more than 80 percent of EEC production of the chemical.
   Cefic has alleged that U.S. producers export their product at
about 10 percent below their internal market price. According to
European producers, U.S. production capacity of 92,000 metric tons
a year exceeds U.S. internal demand by about 65,000 tons.
   Cefic said U.S. export of propylene alcohol to the EEC has risen
to 14,762 tons in 1988, worth roughly $10 million, from 6,758 tons
in 1985, even with the anti-dumping measures.
   Under the current measures, the U.S. companies have undertaken
not to undercut European companies' pricing in the EEC.
</TEXT>
