<FIRST>r f PM-SpendingBill 1stLd-Writethru f0026 06-06 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spending Bill, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0026,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tax Battles Next as Senate Debates $3.3 Billion Spending Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with four grafs to UPDATE with debate beginning. Picks
up 5th graf pvs, Kasten's amendment ... A version moving on general news
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats and Republicans bickered today over
whether to repeal a tax law that businesses find burdensome, as the
Senate struggled to complete a wide-ranging, $3.3 billion spending
bill.
   As the Senate began its third day of debate on the legislation,
Sen. Robert Kasten, R-Wis., offered an amendment repealing a
section of the 1986 tax-revision law that he said has ``wreaked
havoc'' on companies because of its complexity and costs.
   Democrats countered with a provision that conceded the tax
requirement is ``onerous'' and urged its reworking by Congress
later in the year.
   President Bush first asked Congress more than two months ago to
provide extra money for this year for several federal agencies.
Since then, the measure has grown not only in size but in breadth,
attracting an assortment of amendments ranging from U.S. policy in
Panama to work on an Ohio lake.
   Kasten's amendment revokes a requirement that businesses satisfy
a complex test to prove that their health insurance plans are not
more generous to upper echelon employees than they are to low-paid
workers. Companies have complained that the provision, which took
effect this year, has created mounds of paperwork. Small businesses
in particular have been unhappy.
   Kasten called the problem ``the No. 1 domestic issue in America
today'' in a written statement last week, and his amendment was
co-sponsored by at least 13 other GOP senators. Bush, Senate
Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, and House Ways
and Means Committee Chairman Daniel Rostenkowski, D-Ill., have said
the requirement needs to be reworked.
   Another amendment, to be offered by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.,
temporarily postpones the surtax now imposed on elderly Americans
as the price for new Medicare coverage of catastrophic care. Senior
citizens have complained about the expense, which will cost a
maximum of $850 in 1989 for the wealthiest Americans over age 65.
   Bush initially requested the legislation in March, seeking $2.2
billion for veterans, college students, forest fire costs and other
needs. By the time the House passed the bill last month, it had
grown to $3.7 billion, slightly surpassing the Senate's version.
   In the Senate, the legislation has garnered a slew of amendments
that range from the global to the parochial.
   A provision added last week directs the Army Corps of Engineers
to spend $500,000 this year on a project in Mill Creek Lake in
Ohio. The measure was sponsored by the state's two Democratic
senators, Howard Metzenbaum and John Glenn.
   The bill also picked up language sponsored by Sen. Dan Coats,
R-Ind., expressing the Senate's disinclination to approve a Panama
Canal Commission administrator named by Panamanian ruler Manuel
Antonio Noriega. By law, the chief of government of Panama can
nominate a new chief for the agency in January. That choice must be
approved by the Senate and by Bush, and the Senate served notice it
would not go along with the Panamanian strongman.
   The 1989 federal fiscal year runs through Sept. 30.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
