<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   06-06 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rallied Tuesday to close
significantly higher on the London Stock Exchange, breaking a
five-day string of losses.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index rose 18.9
points, or 0.9 percent, to finish at 2,107.4, its best level of the
day. At its lowest, the index was down 10.9 points in early trading.
   The market opened lower on the back of Wall Street's fall Monday
and on continued worries about British interest rates and violence
in China.
   A bit of strength in the pound around midday, combined with some
bargain hunting and expectations of a higher opening on Wall
Street, started the London market moving higher.
   The rally gathered strength as Wall Street opened for business,
with the Dow Jones industrial average up about 20 points when
trading in London came to a close.
   The rally was driven in part by technical factors, as a short
supply of stock accentuated the effects of a small amount of
institutional buying, dealers said.
   Volume rose to a moderate 445.8 million shares from Monday's
359.2 million shares.
</TEXT>
