<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1403EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-RJRNabisco-Europe     06-06 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-RJR Nabisco-Europe,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>RJR Sells 5 European Units to French Company for $2.5 Billion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco Inc. said Tuesday it sold five of its
European businesses to BSN, a French food and beverage company, for
$2.5 billion in an effort to reduce some of its debt from a record
buyout.
   BSN bought the United Kingdom biscuit business of Nabisco
Brands; British snack food makers Walker's Crisps and Smith's
Crisps; The Belin Group, a French biscuit and pastry business; and
Saiwa, a biscuit and snack producer in Italy.
   The five European companies had pretax profit of $137 million on
sales of $1.2 billion in 1988.
   RJR Nabisco put the European units on the block last month,
saying the sales would be part of an effort to reduce the company's
overall debt by about $5.5 billion.
   In the wake of its $24.5 billion takeover by Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts &amp; Co., completed earlier this year, RJR has annual interest
payments of about $3 billion.
   The company has been expected to sell several assets in an
attempt to reduce that debt.
   Emanuel Goldman, an analyst with PaineWebber Inc. in San
Francisco who follows RJR, said the BSN deal demonstrates that
there should be eager customers for any RJR units made available.
   ``This indicates that, indeed, the RJR properties are hot
properties,'' he said. ``It is one thing to project that, and
another to actually see it.''
   BSN and RJR are ranked one and two, respectively, in the biscuit
and snack food business in France, Goldman said, and the deal
reinforces BSN's powerhouse status at home.
   BSN did not have a major presence in the United Kingdom, though
RJR Nabisco did, Goldman added. ``All of a sudden, they (BSN) are a
big player in the British snack market,'' he said.
   BSN markets a variety of biscuit, dairy and grocery products, as
well as beer, champagne and mineral water.
   ``BSN has acquired five attractive food businesses, each
possessing strong brands, distribution and sales systems,
manufacturing facilities and management,'' RJR Chairman Louis V.
Gerstner Jr. said.
   ``As part of BSN, one of Europe's premier food and beverage
companies, these businesses should continue to develop and
prosper,'' he said.
   Gerstner said the sale, while helping RJR reduce its debt, will
not diminish the company's competitive standing.
   ``The size and strength of our food businesses in North America
continue to place RJR Nabisco among the world's leading cookie,
cracker and snack producers,'' he said.
</TEXT>
