<FIRST>u f AM-Saudi-OilStrike     06-06 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Saudi-Oil Strike,0263</SECOND>
<UNK>Saudi Arabia Makes New Oil Strike</UNK>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia, the world's largest oil
exporter, has made a new oil find in the Khurais region southeast
of the capital of Riyadh, oil industry executives said Tuesday.
   Officials at the Saudi Aramco oil company, reached by telephone
from Bahrain, confirmed the report but refused to give details
about its potential.
   The company is based in the kingdom's Gulf city of Dhahran.
   The new find results from a large-scale high-technology
exploration program launched by Saudi Aramco in 1986, the company
officials said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   As part of the program, Saudi Aramco drilled a new wildcat well
in the Khurais region 125 miles southeast of Riyadh. The drillers
hit a small amount of oil in a reservoir and had some gas shows.
   First reports suggested that oil discovered in that region was
not in commercial amounts, but Saudi Aramco was optimistic about
the gas.
   Sources close to Saudi Aramco say the gas discovery was sizeable
and commercially viable, but the company officials declined to
confirm or deny the report.
   Saudi Aramco announced this year its proven oil reserves have
risen to 252 billion barrels from 169 billion barrels. Its annual
report for 1988 speculated that remaining reserves could be as high
as 315 billion barrels.
   Saudi Arabia has the world's largest known oil reserves. Almost
all are in areas managed by Saudi Aramco, which has discovered 52
oil fields and one commercial gas field in 55 years of exploration.
</TEXT>
