<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1445EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Paramount     06-06 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Paramount,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Posts 18 Percent Profit Increase for 2nd Qtr</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Will be updated with closing stock prices.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramount Communications Inc., formerly known as
Gulf &amp; Western Inc., said Tuesday its second-quarter profit rose 18
percent, as strong results in entertainment and financial services
more than offset seasonally weak results from educational
publishing.
   On a separate matter, the company declined comment on a
published report in USA Today that Paramount was weighing making a
bid for Time Inc., which is already in an agreement to merge with
Warner Communications Inc.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Paramount was up 37{
cents a share at $33.37{ at midday while Time was up $2.75 a share
at $126.
   In its earnings report, Paramount reported net income of $65.6
million, or 55 cents a share, in the three months ended April 30
compared with $55.5 million, or 46 cents a share, a year earlier.
   The 1988 earnings results included a net gain of $4.8 million
from the sale of the company's 30 percent interest in a
videocassette duplication business.
   Second-quarter revenue rose 12.7 percent to $699 million from
$620 million a year earlier. The revenue figures exclude results
from The Associates, the consumer and commercial finance business
that Paramount put up for sale in April.
   For the first six months of the year, Paramount said it earned
$134.8 million, or $1.13 a share, up 12 percent from $120.2
million, or $1 a share, a year earlier.
   Six-month revenue, excluding The Associates, rose 10.5 percent
to $1.47 billion from $1.33 billion a year earlier.
   Paramount did not break out its quarterly and six-month revenue
figures for The Associates.
   Martin S. Davis, chairman of Paramount, said he expects oprating
income from entertainment and publishing this year would
approximate the $432 million reported 1988. He said 1989 earnings
including results from The Associates to the date of its sale would
exceed the 1988 total of $384.7 million.
   In the second quarter, he said income from continuing operations
included record contributions from the entertainment business, due
to sharp increases in Paramount Pictures' operations and gains by
its Madison Square Garden unit.
   The entertainment results included the success of the movie
``The Naked Gun: From the Files of Police Squad'' and the
syndication of television show ``Star Trek: The Next Generation''
and strong sales to pay cable services.
   Madison Square Garden operations benefitted from higher
attendance at New York Knickerbocker basketball games, NBA league
expansion revenues and increased ticket sales at New York Rangers
hockey games which more than offset a decline at the MSG Network, a
cable service that had higher costs associated with the startup of
its New York Yankees cablecasts this spring.
   Publishing results reflected seasonal losses in educational
operations, which traditionally have their highest sales in the
second half of the year.
</TEXT>
