<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1507EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-TrainingAmerica     06-06 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Training America,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: U.S. Needs More, Better On-the-Job Training</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. employers must train workers more and better
and reward enhanced skills to remain competitive internationally,
according to a study released Tuesday by the American Society for
Training and Development.
   ``The United States can educate and train employees outside the
workplace until it is blue in the face, but if employers do not
design institutions and jobs that use and reward learning, all
efforts will make little difference,'' the report said.
   The study was released at the annual meeting here of the
45-year-old Alexandria, Va.-based society, which represents nearly
50,000 professionals involved in employer-based training.
   The group includes managers, administrators, educators and
researchers who devise in-house training. Their work ranges from
teaching illiterate workers to read, to improving sales and
customer service skills, to educating executives in running a
company.
   ``Analysis of the available data and case studies of individual
employers leads to the conclusion that employers' current
commitments to training and development are probably
insufficient,'' the report said.
   It said that while learning in the workplace can boost
individual opportunity and corporate competitiveness, ``learning
has a relatively low standing and low frequency in the American
workplace.''
   Citing federal Bureau of Labor Statistics data, the report said
11 percent of American workers receive formal training and 14
percent get informal on-the-job training to prepare for jobs.
   By the year 2000, the report said, 65 percent of all jobs will
require some training or education beyond high school, compared
with 54 per cent now.
   The report recommended that:
   _Employers set short-term targets of spending 2 percent of
payroll on formal training and increasing the proportion of workers
tapped for extra training to nearly 15 percent, from 10 percent
now. The long-term goal should be 4 percent of payroll costs to
train 30 percent of employees.
   _The government create tax incentives to induce employers to
improve the quality of worker training.
   _Employers and educators join to raise the level of workplace
training and education.
   _Firms establish workplace incentives for advanced training
through performance-based selection, appraisal and rewards.
   The study was the second in a month to warn that weak job
training was hurting U.S. productivity.
   A two-year Massachusetts Institute of Technology study called
``Made in America'' concluded that national proseprity was
undermined by industrial weakness. It recommended that companies
offer workers more on-the-job training and learning opportunities
to improve productivity.
</TEXT>
