<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-89 1505EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-China-USBusiness 1stLd-Writethru   06-06 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-US Business, 1st Ld-Writethru,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Douglas Aircraft Withdraws 51 People, About-Face From 24 Hours Earlier</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with decision by aircraft maker to evacuate staff; edits
throughout to conform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Douglas Aircraft Co. became the latest big U.S.
company to pull expatriate workers from strife-racked China today,
chartering a plane to withdraw its 51 people from Shanghai and two
other cities.
   The move by the division of McDonnell Douglas Corp., a partner
in a joint-venture aircraft assembly plant outside Shanghai, was an
about-face from the company's position a day earlier when it said
business was normal.
   The company also became one of the first U.S. businesses to
charter a plane for evacuations and one of the first with big
operations outside Beijing to withdraw. Up to now most of the
evacuees have been from the capital, which has been in turmoil
since the weekend when troops killed hundreds of civilians.
   ``We've changed our situation in China. We decided last night to
begin pulling our people out of China back to Hong Kong,'' Douglas
Aircraft spokesman Donald Hanson said from company headquarters in
Long Beach, Calif. ``The situation apparently has changed
overnight.''
   Hanson said the company's 43 people based just outside Shanghai,
seven people based in the southwest city of Chengdu and one
representative in the northeast industrial center of Shenyang would
leave as soon as possible.
   Many other U.S. businesses that had reacted cautiously toward
China's political crisis also have been withdrawing workers from
Beijing and a growing number are becoming gloomy about the
longer-term impact to their investments.
   ``Now with this random shooting in Beijing it's no longer fun.
Anyone who approaches a window risks his life,'' Jerome Cohen, an
international lawyer who helped pioneer the American business
presence in China, said Monday.
   ``With respect to our own staff, I think it is time to withdraw
for a while,'' said Cohen, whose firm of Paul, Weiss, Rifkind,
Wharton &amp; Garrison has offices in China. ``Until this weekend I
thought that was unwarranted. But now we have to think of people's
safety.''
   United Airlines, the only U.S. carrier to Beijing, was heavily
booked on its 400-seat flight out of the capital today, spokeswoman
Sara Dornacker said.
   By early this afternoon the airline had not added any flights,
although there were reports the U.S. embassy in Beijing was trying
to charter planes to help evacuate American nationals.
   Ms. Dornacker said UAL was continuing to deliberately delay the
Tokyo-Beijing leg of its regular U.S.-to-Beijing flight by 15 hours
to avoid an overnight layover in the capital, fearing the airport
might close.
   Northwest Airlines spokesman Kevin Whalen said earlier that the
airline's Tokyo-Shanghai flight also was delayed to minimize ground
time in Shanghai, ``just because the situation is so fluid there.''
   Robert Cox, a senior executive of the international law firm of
Baker &amp; Mckenzie, said his China-based staffers had left for Hong
Kong because of the concern for personal safety, and ``clients are
dealing with the situation there the same as we are.''
   ``The implications of this are profound,'' Cox said. ``I don't
see how anyone doing business there couldn't set those plans in a
state of suspension.''
   U.S. business reaction to the chaos in China is particularly
important because American investment is one of the biggest
influences on the country's effort to modernize.
   More than 600 U.S.-Chinese joint ventures have been signed since
Washington and Beijing normalized relations 10 years ago, with
American investment there totaling at least $3.5 billion. The
United States is one of China's biggest trading partners.
   ``A political uncertainty and a standoff is one thing. A
massacre is another,'' said Martin Weil, a spokesman for the U.S.
China Business Council, a Washington-based organization of American
companies. ``Everybody's going to have to factor that in.''
   General Electric Co., International Business Machines Corp. and
Chrysler Corp. were among companies that said they had evacuated
people because of the violence in Beijing and the growing
uncertainty elsewhere in the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
