<FIRST>u f PM-CNWBuyout 2ndLd-Writethru f0134 06-06 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CNW Buyout, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0134,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Board Approves Management Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Japonica terminating offer;
PICKS UP 3rd graf pvs, `The agreement...</HEAD>
<NOTE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CNW Corp.'s board of directors today approved a
$1.6 billion buyout offer made by a corporation including CNW
management, ending a two-month hostile takeover bid by Japonica
Partners.
   The corporation was formed by Blackstone Capital Partners LP and
includes Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Inc., a New York-based
securities firm, and the Union Pacific Corp., CNW officials said.
   Japonica announced in New York it was terminating its bid
because of the deal and said it would decide whether to sell some
or all of its CNW shares.
   The agreement calls for acquisition of CNW by Blackstone and a
management group led by company chairman and chief executive
officer Robert Schmiege for $45.50 per share in cash, and $4.50 per
share of pay-in-kind preferred stock with a 17 percent dividend
rate.
   Blackstone, a private New York investment banking firm, will
hold a controlling interest in CNW under the agreement.
   The transaction , valued at $1.6 billion, is based upon
approximately 19 million CNW shares outstanding and the assumption
of CNW debt.
   The offer was approved by a special CNW board committee that was
evaluating bids for the Chicago-based rail company.
   CNW is the parent of the Chicago and Northwestern Transportation
Co., a 6,000-mile railroad with 8,500 employees that operates in
nine states, most of them in the Midwest.
   Japonica, CNW's largest shareholder with an 8.8 percent stake,
has been attempting a takeover since April 27. Japonica's
$44-a-share offer values CNW at $722 million.
   New York-based Japonica is headed by two former Goldman Sachs &
Co. investment bankers, Paul B. Kazarian and Michael Lederman.
   Japonica officials did not immediately return telephone calls
seeking comment.
   Bethlehem, Pa.-based Union Pacific Railroad relies heavily on
the North Western's Chicago-to-Fremont, Neb., line for east-west
freight traffic. The Union Pacific accounts for about 40 percent of
the North Western's shipments, analysts say.
   Union Pacific recently paid $1.5 million for an option to buy
the Iowa Interstate Railroad, a regional line between Iowa and
Chicago. Officials said the line would have served as a substitute
to the North Western should a hostile takeover disrupt freight
service.
   Officials of Japonica had said they planned to sell CNW's real
estate, excess equipment and Chicago-area commuter lines if their
takeover bid was successful.
   The railroad's union on Friday made a proposal to buy the
company that would have given employees a one-third stake in the
railroad.
</TEXT>
