<HEAD>Wheat Prices Drop Despite China Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed lower
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, with wheat prices falling
despite announcement of a major sale to the People's Republic of
China.
   Monday's announcement that China purchased 1.85 million metric
tons of wheat was expected to be a boost to prices, but that didn't
happen.
   ``The sale was already factored into the market so there was
some liquidation,'' said Jon Horton, an analyst with Research
Department Inc. in Chicago.
   Horton noted that there was also some commercial selling of
wheat futures because of a lack of business.
   ``There is so much uncertainty in China, people aren't willing
to pay $4 a bushel for wheat, which what it was getting to,'' he
said.
   Corn prices dropped in a spillover from the sale of wheat
futures, despite word from the Agriculture Department that recent
severe weather in Ohio could prevent planting of about 50 percent
of that state's planned corn crop.
   Soybean prices fell as investors purchased old crop futures and
sold new crop. Analysts say the strong dollar is expected to
continue to hamper export sales.
   At the close, wheat was } cent to 3 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.92{ a bushel; corn was 1\ cents
lower to } cent higher with July at $2.63{ a bushel; oats were 2
cents to 3{ cents lower with July at $1.65{ a bushel; soybeans were
3 cents lower to 1{ cents higher with July at $7.07 a bushel.
