<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Unions     06-06 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Unions,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unions Try To Stay Optimistic About Possible Buyout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines union leaders told striking
workers Tuesday to remain optimistic about a possible buyout, but
the troubled carrier said the prospects of a deal were dead.
   A federal bankruptcy judge Monday said Eastern should begin
negotiating on plans to reorganize as a smaller carrier after an
investor group led by the unions and a Chicago businessman failed
to put together a takeover deal.
   ``The fat lady just sang,'' Eastern spokesman Jim Ashlock said.
   ``I can tell you it's absolutely untrue,'' Frank Ortis, vice
president of the Machinists local, told members at the union hall
who gathered to discuss apparent bad news in their three-month-old
strike. ``So let's hang in there.''
   Eastern said the ruling by Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland
ended buyout possibilities by Chiacgo commodities trader Joseph
Ritchie and the unions, who nonetheless maintained it was alive.
   Joel Zweibel, the attorney for the committee representing major
creditors, said in court the proposal was ``interesting and
constructive'' but wouldn't be possible without Eastern approval.
   The group met Saturday with representatives of Eastern parent
Texas Air Corp. but failed to win support for the buyout plan,
which included a $100 million equity investment and $210 million in
union wage concessions.
   The judge directed Eastern to begin talks with creditors over
the company's plan to sell $1.8 billion in assets and reorganize in
bankruptcy court as a smaller carrier.
   Lifland said the Ritchie group could continue discussing its
offer with creditors, but that the court no longer would consider
it unless it was acceptable to Eastern.
   ``It's always there in the minds of some who would like to keep
it alive,'' Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said, but added:
``There are no buyers out there.''
   But pilots union spokesman Ron Cole countered that Lifland did
not kill the Ritchie bid or give approval to the Texas Air Chairman
Frank Lorenzo's awaited reorganization plan.
   Cole said the unions believe the creditors will reject the
rebuilding plan, which focuses on mass asset sales the union says
would leave Eastern too crippled to compete.
   The unions also contend that management won't be able to hire
enough qualified pilots and mechanics.
   ``We don't think Mr. Lorenzo is going to find enough
professional people to put his airline back without the unions,''
said Wally Haber, a Machinists general chairman. ``He's got people
out there, but they're round pegs for square holes.''
   The pilots union urged its members not to ``make any rash
decisions'' based on what the union called inaccurate information
from news reports about Lifland's ruling.
   Ritchie set a meeting for Wednesday in Washington between his
group and David I. Shapiro, the court-appointed examiner for
Eastern.
   ``I thought the unions were grasping at straws,'' said Mark
Daugherty, a Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. analyst. ``I think it's
pretty much dead now.''
   Eastern sought bankruptcy protection from creditors on March 9,
five days after pilots and flight attendants joined striking ground
workers represented by the Machinists union in a walkout that
virtually grounded the airline.
   Under bankruptcy law, Eastern has the exclusive right until
early July to submit a reorganization plan. Eastern's lead
attorney, Harvey Miller, said Monday that Eastern probably would
propose its plan within two to three weeks.
   Eastern already has discussed an outline of a reorganization
scheme with the creditors' committee, Miller said.
</TEXT>
