<FIRST>r f AM-LeasingScam     06-06 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Leasing Scam,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brothers Charged in Leasing Scam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two brothers have been indicted on charges of
stealing more than $1.7 million in equipment leasing schemes
involving Bell Atlantic Systems and Morgan Guaranty Trust Co.,
officials said Tuesday.
   The Manhattan district attorney's office said a 17-count
indictment charged Tuvia ``Ted'' Stern, 27, and Ephraim Stern, 34,
of Brooklyn, with illegal use of a legal tax-saving device last
year.
   The Sterns sold printing equipment from two companies they owned
to Bell so they could generate a cash profit. They then leased back
the equipment so they could use it while writing off the lease cost
as a business expense, according to the indictment.
   If the Sterns had kept the equipment in the first place, the
only financial advantage would have been the annual depreciation
for taxes.
   Such transactions are legal, but the indictment said the Sterns
sold property to Bell that was ``greatly overvalued and in some
instances was owned by others and in some instances did not exist.''
   In one case, according to Assistant District Attorney George
Donahue, the Sterns bought the Mayflower Printing Co. in June 1988
for $50,000 and sold it and nonexistent assets to Bell Atlantic for
$600,000 a few months later.
   To keep the scheme going, the Sterns allegedly used phony
financial statements and invoices and fictitious eople.
   In another case, the Sterns used their lawyer's bank account to
steal $265,000 from Morgan Guaranty, Donahue said.
   The Sterns aface up to 25 years in jail if convicted of the top
count of first-degree grand larceny.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
