<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     06-06 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Petroleum Prices Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices weakened slightly Tuesday
as OPEC ministers struggled to reach an agreement on raising crude
oil production.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the contract for July
delivery of West Texas intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude oil, dipped 6 cents to $20.46 per 42-gallon barrel following
Monday's rise of 38 cents. Prices of refined petroleum products
posted larger declines.
   The crude contract held up well given the developments at the
conference of ministers representing the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries, said Chris McCormack, an energy broker at
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   ``All the news to me seems to be bearish. The bickering among
members about production, quotas and allocations was a negative
influence on energy prices,'' said McCormack.
   Negotiations among the cartel ministers meeting in Vienna bogged
down Tuesday as they tried to agree on allotting a proposed
cartel-wide oil production increase among its 13 member nations.
   Some members are believed to favor dividing any additional
production evenly but Kuwait apparently has demanded a larger share
while several other countries would like special treatment.
   On production, the ministers are considering a proposal to
increase the cartel's output ceiling from the current 18.5 million
barrels a day to 19.5 million in the July-December period.
   The United Arab Emirates, however, favors a boost to between 20
million barrels and 21 million barrels.
   As the OPEC discussions were taking place, a new report was
released which estimated that current production by OPEC members
far exceeds the self-imposed quota.
   The International Energy Agency said OPEC nations produced oil
at a daily rate of 21 million barrels last month, the highest
amount so far this year.
   Energy market analysts said the violence in China and the
problems stemming from the explosion of a natural gas pipeline in
the Soviet Union had little impact on prices Tuesday. These events
had been among the factors responsible for Monday's gains.
   The July contract for No. 2 heating oil, which rose 1.87 cents
Monday, fell 0.91 cent to 51.00 cents a gallon on the New York
Mercantile Exchange. The contract for July delivery of unleaded
gasoline settled at 64.94 cents a gallon, off 0.86 cent, almost
erasing Monday's increase of 0.95 cent.
</TEXT>
