<FIRST>u f AM-CrazyEddie     06-06 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crazy Eddie,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Creditors Seek Involuntary Bankruptcy Against Electronics Retailer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of five creditors filed a petition
Tuesday for involuntary bankruptcy against electronics retailer
Crazy Eddie to try to recoup $860,000 from the company that once
boasted ``insane'' prices.
   Crazy Eddie has 20 days to contest the petition before it must
liquidate its assets, said Michael Fox, an attorney for the
creditors.
   The company also has the option of filing for bankruptcy under
Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy law, he said.
   A Crazy Eddie spokesman, who would not give his name, said the
company's board of directors was meeting late Tuesday and planned to
issue a statement.
   The petition, filed in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Manhattan,
represents Cobra Electronics Group of Dynascan Corp.; Phonemate,
Inc.; Code-A-Phone Corp.; Southwestern Bell Telecommunications Inc.;
and Northwestern Bell Phones, an affiliate of U S West Company.
   Crazy Eddie, known for its frenetic broadcast commercials
claiming that ``Our prices are insane!'' announced in March that it
was closing 17 of its 43 stores overnight in a bid to cut losses.
   At the time, the Edison, N.J.-based company said a drop in sales
compounded by a massive inventory shortage, excessive long-term debt
and ``certain unprofitable locations'' had drained its working
capital.
   In their petition, the five creditors claim Crazy Eddie is
liquidating its assets without taking into account the debts to its
creditors.
   ``Crazy Eddie has been the subject of speculation about its
financial condition for several months,'' Fox said in statement. ``A
pending shareholder lawsuit, continued operating losses and the
departure of key personnel have further eroded investor and supplier
confidence in the discounter.''
   Fox said an unofficial committee of major creditors that was
formed to negotiate with Crazy Eddie had failed to reach an accord.
   ``My clients believe that it is in their best interests ... that
the bankruptcy court become involved,'' he said.
   Crazy Eddie's stock closed at 25 cents a share in
over-the-counter trading Tuesday, unchanged from the previous close.
The stock is down from 53 cents in March and had been as high as $21
three years ago.
</TEXT>
