<HEAD>Dollar Lags; Gold Leaps</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price of gold shot up nearly $12 an ounce in
late trading Tuesday, while the dollar sagged.
   Some dealers said gold rallied in a belated response to the
turmoil in China, but others said technical factors were behind the
late spurt. The dollar was actually lower earlier Tuesday in Hong
Kong, which is most sensitive to what happens in China.
   Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid at $376.70 a
troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $364.80 on Monday. That brought
it back to its levels of early May, but still well below the levels
of January, when it was over $400 an ounce.
   The rally began in New York when some futures traders who had
sold gold short in anticipation of a decline became nervous and
decided to buy gold to even their books, said Bernard Savaiko,
senior metals analyst at PaineWebber Inc.
   ``It seemed to feed on itself as the day progressed,'' he said.
   There was no major economic news to account for the retreat of
the dollar after its gains Monday.
   A pattern of sharp, unexplained drops in the dollar indicated the
Federal Reserve might have sold dollars secretly, said Michael
McGuinness, an investment officer in foreign exchange at Harris
Trust &amp; Savings Bank in Chicago.
   Several traders have speculated in the past two weeks that the
Federal Reserve and other central banks are trying to get extra
impact from their intervention by concealing it more than in the
past.
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.5665 to buy one pound, compared to $1.5815 late Monday. Later in
New York the pound rose to $1.5710 from $1.5655 on Monday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rosed 1.98 yen to a closing 142.63 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 143.28 yen. In New York the dollar fell to 142.67
yen from 142.95.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.9735 West German marks, down from 1.9855; 1.7095
Swiss francs, down from 1.7140; 1.2010 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2019; 6.7060 French francs, down from 6.7455; and 1,434 Italian
lire, down from 1,442.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday:
1.9850 West German marks, up from 1.9630; 1.7240 Swiss francs, up
from 1.6950; 6.7360 French francs, up from 6.6645; 2.2370 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.2010; 1,443.00 Italian lire, up from 1,416.50;
1.2015 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2003.
   In Hong Kong, gold fell $3.76 a troy ounce to close at a bid of
$365.44.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $365.25 per troy
ounce, compared with late Monday's $366.25. In Zurich, gold dropped
to a bid of $365.30 compared with $366.00 late Monday.
   But on the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for
current delivery rose to $379.90 a troy ounce from $367.50 on Monday.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $5.28 a troy ounce, compared with
Monday's $5.31. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current
delivery rose to $5.431 an ounce from $5.264 on Monday.
