<FIRST>u f AM-AlaskaSpill-Tourism Bjt   06-06 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alaska Spill-Tourism, Bjt,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Touts Alaska Tourism, Says Tourists Have Nothing To Fear
From Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RORY MARSHALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alaska's governor and tourism officials, fearing
that Americans picture their state as a soiled paradise since the
biggest oil spill in U.S. history, began a damage-control tour
Tuesday to promote the vast reaches unaffected by the disaster.
   ``If you went to Alaska and if you wanted to see the oil, you
would have to go to a pretty substantial expense and a lot of
trouble to do so,'' Gov. Steve Cowper told a news conference.
   Tourism is a $750 million-a-year industry for Alaska, and ranks
behind only oil and seafood among the state's biggest industries,
Dow said.
   Cowper and other Alaska officials emphasized that as large as the
March 24 spill was, it was virtually lost amid the state's huge
unaffected expanses of land and water.
   Cowpwr said the spill affected only 2 percent of Alaska's 6,640
miles of coastline. That included just 5 percent of the shoreline
within Prince William Sound, where the tanker Exxon Valdez ran
aground and spilled 10.9 million gallons of crude.
   Thomas M. Dow, president of the Alaska Visitors Association, a
tourism industry group, showed slides taken since the spill,
portraying untouched beaches within the sound, a cruise ship
crossing the sound, and sea lions in the area where the spill
drifted.
   ``There's no hiding from the fact that it's been a tragedy,'' Dow
said. ``But for visitors, few if any will see its impacts on these
remote areas.''
   Officials have no firm projections how many potential visitors
may be deterred by the oil spill, but sport-fishing lodge operators
have reported inquiries from their customers and some outright
reservation cancellations, Cowper said.
   Like commercial fishermen, tour operators and others in tourism
will be entitled to compensation from Exxon if they can show damages
as a result of the spill, Cowper said.
   The state spent $10.8 million on tourism promotion in 1988, and
the Legislature budgeted $11.4 million for this year.
   This year's budget is supplemented by $4 million from Exxon, part
of which is financing this week's promotion trip to Seattle and New
York, as well as print and television advertising.
   One of the ads shows a picture of a smiling Marilyn Monroe
without her beauty mark. ``Without it, the picture may have changed,
but her beauty hasn't,'' the ad reads. ``The same is true of
Alaska.''
   In addition, 154,000 copies of a letter from Cowper were sent to
people who had inquired about visiting Alaska, assuring them the oil
spill would not affect their travel plans.
   Before the spill, Alaska tourism officials predicted just over
780,000 people would visit the state this season, its 30th
anniversary of statehood. That would have been up from 709,664 in
1988 and would match 1986, the best year ever, when a number of
visitors to British Columbia's Expo 86 world's fair included Alaska
in their tours.
   Some visitors may be drawn to Alaska because of publicity about
the spill and the environmental damage it wrought, officials said.
   Some entrepreneurs may even arrange tours of oil-fouled areas,
Dow predicted.
   ``I think it's probably correct to say we're getting people up
there who want to see the oil spill,'' Cowper said. But, he added,
``they're going to have a hard time.''
</TEXT>
