<FIRST>r f AM-Nintendo     06-06 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nintendo,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nintendo Intends to Become Information Supplier in U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Nintendo Co. is developing a plan that could use the machines
that run its popular video games as part of a network for delivering
information to U.S. households, a spokeswoman for the company said
Tuesday.
   The plan apparently would transform Nintendo Entertainment System
units into inexpensive home computers providing a range of news,
possibly about stock markets, travel and other topics.
   The units are plastic boxes, retailing for around $100, that hook
up to television sets to display such hit Nintendo games as ``Super
Mario Brothers 2,'' ``Zelda II,'' and ``Mike Tyson's Punch-out.''
   The company has held discussions with American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph Co. to explore the technological possibilities of having
Nintendo devices form part of an information delivery network,
according to the spokeswoman, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Nintendo intends to pursue the concept and hopes to work out the
mechanics of a plan by next year. No formal arrangements have been
made with AT&amp;T or any other company, the spokeswoman said.
   AT&amp;T confirmed in a brief news release that it was discussing a
number of possibilities with Nintendo. However, it stated that ``no
business relationship has been agreed upon and no contracts have
been signed.''
   The announcement was issued in response to published reports that
indicated Nintendo and AT&amp;T had joined forces to set up an
information supplying network.
   Peter Main, vice president of marketing for Nintendo Co., the
American subsidiary of the Kyoto, Japan-based Nintendo Co. Ltd.,
wouldn't elaborate on the plan in an article published Tuesday in
the Wall Street Journal. He also declined to identify what company
might provide the database information.
   Main was said to be traveling Tuesday and unavailable for comment.
   Fuller details about Nintendo's strategy are to be revealed
Wednesday when company executives meet with securities analysts in
New York, the company spokeswoman said.
   Nintendo's Japanese parent company already delivers an assortment
of information over its ``Family Computer'' devices in Japanese
households.
</TEXT>
