<FIRST>r f AM-Chrysler-Jeep     06-06 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chrysler-Jeep,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Petition Drive Launched to Keep Jeep in Toledo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials launched a petition drive Tuesday
to keep Chrysler Corp.'s Jeep plant in Toledo after a contract
between the United Auto Workers and Chrysler expires in 1992.
   Democratic City Council candidate Carty Finkbeiner, who is
leading the drive, said volunteers will try to collect 200,000
signatures from people asking Chrysler to keep the plant open.
   Local labor leaders are helping to organize the petition drive.
   Finkbeinder said ``a convoy of Jeeps'' will travel to Chrysler in
Detroit in the fall to deliver the petitions with the message:
``Manufacturing is not dead in Toledo. Long live manufacturing in
Toledo. Long live Jeep.''
   Some automotive industry analysts predict Chrysler will close the
Jeep plant when the current contract expires or in the mid-1990s,
when production of a new generation of Jeeps begins at the company's
new Detroit plant.
   Chrysler has said it will continue to produce the Jeep Cherokee,
which dominates the sport utility market, at the Toledo plant as
long as it continues to sell.
   Company officials also have said they will negotiate a new
contract with UAW Local 12 when the current accord expires.
   ``As far as Chrysler is concerned, the petition drive isn't
necessary because we have that agreement until 1992, which is a long
time in the auto industry,'' Chrysler spokesman Doug Nicholl said.
</TEXT>
