<FIRST>r f BC-AmericanMedical     06-06 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-American Medical,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Private LBO Firm Backs $1.8 Billion Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A previously announced $1.8 billion
buyout bid for American Medical International Inc. is backed by the
New York leveraged buyout firm Clayton &amp; Dubilier Inc., it was
revealed Monday.
   The friendly offer for the hospital company, organized by
minority shareholder Dr. M. Lee Pearce of Miami, is valued by the
offerer at $24 a share. Of that, $21 a share is cash and the rest
in securities.
   Clayton &amp; Dubilier, a private firm that financed the $960
million management buyout of Colgate Palmolive Co.'s Kendall Co. in
October, leads the buyout group, according to AMI.
   A special committee of the company's board is studying the
offer, AMI said in a news release.
   The potential buyers set a June 15 deadline, and indicated they
were willing to negotiate for a higher price, AMI said.
   Pearce, one of several shareholders who have been pressing the
company to boost its earnings and stock price, first offered to buy
the company in March. Then he valued the offer at $24 a share and
said the portion of that to be in the form of securities would
range from $2 a share to $4 a share.
   American Medical owns 75 hospitals in the United States and
overseas.
   The emergence of Clayton &amp; Dubilier eases doubts about the
seriousness of the offer, said Rae Alperstein, who follows the
company for the Bateman Eichler, Hill Richards investment firm in
Los Angeles.
   ``The investment community was concerned about whether Pearce
was serious and whether he could get the financing,'' Ms.
Alperstein said. ``I think what this says is a deal is going to get
done.''
</TEXT>
