<FIRST>r f BC-Prime-MAIBasic     06-06 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Prime-MAI Basic,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Drops Court Appeal Against MAI Basic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc. has dropped its appeal to the
1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals seeking to enjoin MAI Basic Four
Inc.'s unsolicited takeover bid because MAI's recent revision of its
offer made the appeal irrelevant.
   ``It no longer made sense to pursue that deal,'' Prime spokesman
Joseph Gavaghan said Tuesday.
   Gavaghan said MAI's offer of $19.50 cash per share would actually
be $14.80 per share on a fully diluted basis and ``does not reflect
the intrinsic value of the company.'' Prime is encouraging
stockholders to resist MAI's offer, he said.
   Prime's board of directors postponed the company's annual
stockholders meeting from June 14 to July 26 to ``provide for an
orderly, active and effective exploration of all financial
alternatives,'' officials said in a statement Tuesday.
   Prime's board has said it is discussing acquisition possibilities
with interested parties and is contemplating a possible
recapitalization.
   On Monday, MAI officials said Prime's consideration of other
takeover offers was a ``a deliberate attempt to confuse Prime
stockholders.''
   Last Thursday, MAI lowered its tender offer 50 cents a share
because of Prime's projected results in 1989 and 1990.
   MAI, which is about one-fourth the size of Prime, which is based
in the Boston suburb of Natick, owns about 1.2 million shares of
Prime stock. Since it launched its hostile bid in November, 33.3
million shares were tendered under the $20 offer, representing
nearly 70 percent of the outstanding shares and just under 50
percent of Prime's stock on a fully diluted basis.
   Gavaghan said Prime's executive council has agreed to meet with
MAI Chairman Bennett LeBow at an unspecified future date.
</TEXT>
